nd what factors make slacktivism campaigns successful in mobilizing the masses. The attendees will participate in an interactive and real-time experiment, in which they will respond to and discuss examples of slacktivism campaigns. A leading newspaper journalist and an advertising expert will join the discussion about how online slacktivism campaigns can reach traditional media, and create impact for your brand or message.   \r\n\r\nThis session will start by examining six case studies, such as Wakker Dier’s campaign against C1000’s cheap meat offers, Greenpeace’s campaign against Nuon’s coal-fired power station in the Eemshaven, and Change.org’s petition for fair-trade flowers aimed at FTD, etc.\r\nNext we’ll get voting – Which one would you support and why? The public can vote for one of a series of pairs of different campaigns. Using real-time analysis we will be able to investigate what the critical success factors are for encouraging public participation in a slacktivism campaign.\r\n\r\nWe’ll finish with a presentation and discussion of voting results: what makes the public lend their support to a slacktivism campaign?\r\n','2011-09-15 08:00:00','2011-09-15 10:00:00','2011-06-30 15:20:29','2011-08-21 15:50:32',1,NULL),(109,'Creative Commons',12,'In line with PICNIC Festival’s focus on open data, Creative Commons is presenting a session on “open licensing” and its impact on the open data movement. Many organizations are singing the praises of open data. Even the government is beginning to embrace the value and necessity of opening up data sources. But the actual “openness” of some the available data is debatable.\r\n\r\nCreative Commons Netherlands will look at practical examples and will explore the (legal) implications of opening up data with a panel of interesting speakers.\r\n','2011-09-15 11:30:00','2011-09-15 13:00:00','2011-06-30 15:21:47','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(110,'Mycoform to Mycotecture',12,'Mycology - the branch of biology that deals with the study of the properties and uses of fungi - has revealed the potential for mycelia (the vegetative part of fungus) to filter water (mycofiltration), bioremediate soils (mycoremediation), and create an alternative food protein (mycoprotein). Moreover, it can become a material for various industrial applications. Investigations have determined that mycelia in its natural state can hold up to 30,000 times its mass, and when treated as a material for industrial use, can withstand compression of nearly 200 times it own weight. Its processing production is low-tech and requires fewer resources and less fossil fuel consumption, resulting in a low embodied energy. However, the benefits extend beyond the capabilities of its production and application; it is renewable, biodegradable, highly regenerative, abundant, and it\'s growth is based on the decomposition of matter. The latter is of specific interest since it can break down matter that has a low ability for bio-degradation or is non-biodegradable within the next 1000 years, such as hydrocarbons. Therefore, mycelia can potentially reduce our parts-per-million carbon-offset through its production, creating the first net carbon footprint that is a deficit - ironically suggesting that a solution to a crisis stemming from a finite resource lays in the use of a non-polluting, renewable resource.\r\n\r\nThe question is: Should we intervene in, or interrupt, metabolic cycles and capture the mycelia to use as a material opportunity for architecture? Does this decision depend on the implications of designing mycotecture as a strategy for successfully working within the metabolism of its ecosystem?\r\n\r\n\r\nWorkshop Objectives \r\nThe ONE Lab Biodesign on Mycoform to Mycotecture aims to establish a smart, self-sufficient, perpetual-motion construction technology option. By combining fungal mycelia with varying types of organic substrates and carefully controlling their expansion within prefabricated molds, we will create the literal growth of structural materials. Participants are encouraged to think about the architecture that can emerge from this material, as well as its life cycle in an ecosystem.\r\n\r\n','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-06-30 15:22:18','2011-08-21 16:14:46',1,NULL),(111,'Workshop',12,'','2011-09-15 13:45:00','2011-09-15 15:15:00','2011-06-30 15:23:44','2011-08-21 15:33:53',1,NULL),(112,'tba',5,'','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-09-16 15:15:00','2011-06-30 15:24:09','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(113,'Workshop',12,'','2011-09-15 08:00:00','2011-09-15 10:00:00','2011-06-30 15:34:01','2011-08-21 15:31:06',1,NULL),(114,'Best Scenes in Town Challenge',12,'<b>ʻBest Scene in Townʼ</b> is a mobile design challenge that explores how we can interact with the city through our mobile phones. In ʻBest Scene in Townʼ student teams enter a series of hands-on creative sessions to design, develop and ultimately pilot their mobile concepts for a\r\nlive audience with the 7scenes platform.\r\nʻBest Scene in Townʼ challenges are big and small, but always push the boundaries of mobile\r\ninteraction. The challenge has been organized with several partners for different city themes\r\nover the last year and is focused at the new young professional – the university student.\r\nWith the PICNIC festival and Amsterdam Innovation Motor the challenge has found great\r\npartners in realizing the ambition of connecting international universities with each other.\r\n\r\n<b>ʻBest Scene in Townʼ @ PICNIC ʻ11</b>\r\nFollowing last year\'s success, the challenge has grown even larger with students participating from Parsons - The New School for Design (US), MIT (US), Hong Kong Design Institute (China), University of Amsterdam (NL), Utrecht University (NL) and the Amsterdam University of Applied Sciences (NL). \r\n\r\nFor a summary <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7w4AwLVKea8\"> check out the video.</a>\r\n\r\nMore at <a href=\"http://www.bestsceneintown.com\"> www.bestsceneintown.com</a>','2011-09-16 08:00:00','2011-09-16 10:00:00','2011-06-30 15:34:25','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,'2011/07/12/03_18_47_335_Screen_shot_2011_07_12_at_12.17.03_PM.png'),(115,'Vodafone Mobile Clicks Nominees',4,'','2011-09-15 11:30:00','2011-09-15 13:00:00','2011-06-30 15:35:34','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(116,'COMM: Digital Media for a Better Future',5,'COMM offers an attractive program of presentations, discussions and workshops featuring a selection of guest speakers from Africa. The session at PICNIC Festival is closely tied to the themes of the COMM event: technology and sustainability combined with development in Africa.\r\n\r\nCOMM will host a full day of sessions during PICNIC Festival 2011. COMM’s topics have a creative, educational, practical, innovative and social character, with a primary focus on mobile telephony. Our African partners will demonstrate the innovative solutions they developed themselves using mobile technology, mapping, open data and web 2.0 that contribute to the development of the economy and/or society. The projects will be presented and discussed during the morning session of COMM.\r\n\r\nVisitors to COMM will get a better impression of the impact that ICT, mobile technology, and new media (combined with old media) can have on the living conditions of Africa’s urban and rural inhabitants. How can these technologies, especially mobile, improve and strengthen the social and economic developments in Africa? How can we give a voice to people who might otherwise never be heard? ','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-06-30 15:35:51','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(117,'Food rituals workshop',3,'One of the most intimate daily routines we have as humans is eating. Each culture has their own specific ways to nourish themselves: some eat with their hands, others with a fork and knife, or yet others with chopsticks. What we eat varies as well and connected to each dish comes specific ways to consume it.\r\n\r\nThrough observations of everyday human rituals we find inspiration for unique designs\r\nportraying differences and culture. In this workshop we will explore the participants (Dutch and other) food rituals and co-create new objects. The designers will show objects created from French and Swedish food-rituals.\r\n\r\nThe workshop will be led by the following designers; Alexandre Bau (France), Birgitta Ralston (Sweden), Jan Brauer (Germany) and Åshild Stav (Norway)\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-09-15 13:45:00','2011-09-15 15:15:00','2011-06-30 15:36:29','2011-08-21 16:03:54',1,NULL),(118,'COMM: Digital Media for a Better Future',5,'COMM is a one-day program at PICNIC Festival 2011, followed by two-day conference in 2012 on the innovative, creative and technical applications and economic growth in the field of ICT and mobile phones, focusing on Africa. At COMM you are an active player. Projects and companies are presenting their current work and technical applications. Field experts and specialists will lecture and give workshops focusing on real issues, ethics, environment and techniques. Our mission is to contribute to a better world through digitally connecting the Netherlands, other western countries and developing economies.\r\n\r\nCOMM offers an attractive program of presentations, discussions and workshops featuring a selection of guest speakers from Africa. The session at PICNIC Festival is closely tied to the themes of the COMM event: technology and sustainability combined with development in Africa.\r\nCOMM will host a full day of sessions during PICNIC Festival 2011. COMM’s topics have a creative, educational, practical, innovative and social character, with a primary focus on mobile telephony. Our African partners will demonstrate the innovative solutions they developed themselves using mobile technology, mapping, open data and web 2.0 that contribute to the development of the economy and/or society. The projects will be presented and discussed during the morning session of COMM.\r\n\r\nVisitors to COMM will get a better impression of the impact that ICT, mobile technology, and new media (combined with old media) can have on the living conditions of Africa’s urban and rural inhabitants. How can these technologies, especially mobile, improve and strengthen the social and economic developments in Africa? How can we give a voice to people who might otherwise never be heard?\r\n','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-09-16 15:15:00','2011-06-30 15:36:46','2011-08-21 16:25:48',1,NULL),(119,'European Creative Business Network Creative Trade Mission: Opening Session',8,'Official start of the Trade Mission with a short plenary opening in the ECB Network pavilion, followed by a tour of the PICNIC Marketplace. \r\n\r\nECB Network companies have the opportunity to present their company at the Marketplace and pitch their company during lunchtime. The rest of the day is to explore PICNIC on your own; walk around, network and to take a look at all speakers. The first day of the Trade Mission will end with a dinner at the PICNIC venue.','2011-09-15 08:00:00','2011-09-15 10:00:00','2011-06-30 15:37:45','2011-08-21 15:19:44',1,NULL),(120,'ECBN Plenary Session',8,'The second ECB Network creative trade mission takes place from 14 to 16 September during PICNIC Festival 2011 in Amsterdam. The ECB Network is delighted to have the opportunity to invite over 40 European entrepreneurs from its network to attend this exciting event. On the 14th, we’ll host a welcome dinner. The trade mission’s official program begins on Thursday the 15th.\r\n\r\nThe ECB network organizes the second creative trade mission in close cooperation with its Dutch founding partners: City of Rotterdam, City of Eindhoven and Creative Amsterdam. Another important partner is the Dutch Creative Residency Network, consisting of Bink36, Creative Factory, Puddingfabriek, Strijp-S and Westergasfabriek. \r\n\r\nDay 1 – Welcome dinner and drinks in the center of Amsterdam. Registration of participants starts in the afternoon.\r\n\r\nDay 2 – Official start of the Trade Mission with a short plenary opening in the ECB Network pavilion, followed by a tour of the PICNIC Marketplace. \r\nECB Network companies have the opportunity to present their company at the Marketplace and pitch their company during lunchtime. The rest of the day is to explore PICNIC on your own; walk around, network and to take a look at all speakers. The first day of the Trade Mission will end with a dinner at the PICNIC venue.\r\n\r\nDay 3 – The ECB Network companies will turn their new ideas and inspiration into a 5-minute presentation to potential investors and clients. This presentation will take place at 16:00 at the ECB Network pavilion. A jury of industry specialists and newcomers will judge the product ideas and will have concrete investment budget to spend. One or more ideas will be selected for investment.\r\n\r\nThe ECB Network Creative Trade Mission will be officially closed at 17:25. Afterwards the ECB Network party takes place at the PICNIC venue. The Network party ends at 20:00. We’ll provide all attendees with suggestions for nightlife and creative events during the weekend, in case they want to extend their stay in Amsterdam.\r\n\r\n','2011-09-16 08:00:00','2011-09-16 10:00:00','2011-06-30 15:38:21','2011-08-21 15:20:03',1,NULL),(121,'From Database Cities to Urban Stories',8,'<b>Using technology to run our cities: promises and perils</b>\r\n\r\nOur cities are increasingly becoming data-rich environments. The ecology of apps, visualizations and location-based or context-aware media and information systems generated around urban data environments, have the potential to radically transform the way we understand, inhabit and build our cities.\r\n\r\nThe first European Journalism Centre (EJC) session will bring leading thinkers from academia and the arts to explore the implications of the instruments we use to make sense of our cities on our experience and understanding of cities, as well as on issues of governance and policy making. What are the advantages of the practices and instruments we use today to better understand the processes that govern our cities? What are the perils? What are the politics of these infrastructures? How are they positioned within larger social, cultural, environmental and political concerns? What kinds of futures can we imagine? How do we design infrastructures that help support active citizen engagement? What are the appropriate forms of urban planning, design and policy? \r\n\r\nWhether you are interested in technology design, media production, or policy making focused on issues of urbanization and media technologies, or developing services around data, this session will give you the opportunity to enter into a conversation with various experts about the issues that you care about.\r\n','2011-09-15 11:30:00','2011-09-15 13:15:00','2011-06-30 15:38:49','2011-08-22 08:00:08',1,NULL),(122,'ECBN Pitch session',8,'The second ECB Network creative trade mission takes place from 14 to 16 September during PICNIC Festival 2011 in Amsterdam. The ECB Network is delighted to have the opportunity to invite over 40 European entrepreneurs from its network to attend this exciting event. On the 14th, we’ll host a welcome dinner. The trade mission’s official program begins on Thursday the 15th.\r\n\r\nThe ECB network organizes the second creative trade mission in close cooperation with its Dutch founding partners: City of Rotterdam, City of Eindhoven and Creative Amsterdam. Another important partner is the Dutch Creative Residency Network, consisting of Bink36, Creative Factory, Puddingfabriek, Strijp-S and Westergasfabriek. \r\n\r\nDay 1 – Welcome dinner and drinks in the center of Amsterdam. Registration of participants starts in the afternoon.\r\n\r\nDay 2 – Official start of the Trade Mission with a short plenary opening in the ECB Network pavilion, followed by a tour of the PICNIC Marketplace. \r\nECB Network companies have the opportunity to present their company at the Marketplace and pitch their company during lunchtime. The rest of the day is to explore PICNIC on your own; walk around, network and to take a look at all speakers. The first day of the Trade Mission will end with a dinner at the PICNIC venue.\r\n\r\nDay 3 – The ECB Network companies will turn their new ideas and inspiration into a 5-minute presentation to potential investors and clients. This presentation will take place at 16:00 at the ECB Network pavilion. A jury of industry specialists and newcomers will judge the product ideas and will have concrete investment budget to spend. One or more ideas will be selected for investment.\r\n\r\nThe ECB Network Creative Trade Mission will be officially closed at 17:25. Afterwards the ECB Network party takes place at the PICNIC venue. The Network party ends at 20:00. We’ll provide all attendees with suggestions for nightlife and creative events during the weekend, in case they want to extend their stay in Amsterdam.\r\n','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-06-30 15:39:10','2011-08-21 15:20:41',1,NULL),(123,'From Database Cities to Urban Stories',8,'<b>From database cities to urban stories: what are the success stories?</b>\r\n\r\nThis session will examine how technology projects can help to mobilize citizens around issues such as urban development and environmental sustainability - from new forms of data-driven journalism (EveryBlock) to projects that aim to represent things that are usually invisible or intangible such as waste disposal (<a href=\"http://senseable.mit.edu/trashtrack/\"> http://senseable.mit.edu/trashtrack</a>) or urban air quality (<a href=\"http://www.intheair.es/\">www.intheair.es/</a>). \r\n\r\nIn the second European Journalism Centre (EJC) session we take a look at successful examples and the rationale behind those examples. We will ask questions such as: How do we design infrastructures that mobilize citizens around issues and help support active citizen engagement? What role can journalists play in this environment? Can they be instrumental in making sense of the urban information flows? How can they support citizens in shaping the urban environment in new ways?\r\n\r\nWhether you are interested in technology design, media production, or policy making focused on issues of urbanization and media technologies, or developing services around data, this session will give you the opportunity to enter into a conversation with various experts about issues that concern your area of interest.\r\n\r\n\r\n','2011-09-15 13:45:00','2011-09-15 15:15:00','2011-06-30 15:39:37','2011-08-21 15:29:34',1,NULL),(124,'ECBN Pitch session',8,'The second ECB Network creative trade mission takes place from 14 to 16 September during PICNIC Festival 2011 in Amsterdam. The ECB Network is delighted to have the opportunity to invite over 40 European entrepreneurs from its network to attend this exciting event. On the 14th, we’ll host a welcome dinner. The trade mission’s official program begins on Thursday the 15th.\r\n\r\nThe ECB network organizes the second creative trade mission in close cooperation with its Dutch founding partners: City of Rotterdam, City of Eindhoven and Creative Amsterdam. Another important partner is the Dutch Creative Residency Network, consisting of Bink36, Creative Factory, Puddingfabriek, Strijp-S and Westergasfabriek. \r\n\r\nDay 1 – Welcome dinner and drinks in the center of Amsterdam. Registration of participants starts in the afternoon.\r\n\r\nDay 2 – Official start of the Trade Mission with a short plenary opening in the ECB Network pavilion, followed by a tour of the PICNIC Marketplace. \r\nECB Network companies have the opportunity to present their company at the Marketplace and pitch their company during lunchtime. The rest of the day is to explore PICNIC on your own; walk around, network and to take a look at all speakers. The first day of the Trade Mission will end with a dinner at the PICNIC venue.\r\n\r\nDay 3 – The