. This session includes two new influential business models: alternative money and use of crowds. \r\n\r\nGuest speakers during this session include: \r\n♥	Burohappold.com (world-famous city engineers, known for the WTC memorial and le Louvre Dubai)\r\n♥	Ontwikkellab Rotterdam\r\n♥	Mobile Brainbank (ex-Nokia mobile engineers)\r\n♥	Mediagilde (incubator in Amsterdam)\r\n♥	Qoin (time banking experts)\r\n♥	Seeds (social crowdfunding)\r\n♥	Hans Robertus (chairman DDW)\r\n\r\nThe session will include discussion and a plenary presentation from our guest speakers on topics like the role of time banking as an alternative system of trade.\r\n','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-09-16 15:15:00','2011-06-30 15:46:14','2011-08-21 16:22:33',1,NULL),(134,'Switched Identities',1,'Identity Bureau by Heath Bunting is developed in collaboration with SKOR | Foundation for Art and Public Domain\r\n\r\nHeath Buntings project is part of SKOR\'s new initiative NetArtWorks: <a href=\"http://www.skor.nl/nl/site/item/netartworks-heath-bunting\"> www.skor.nl/nl/site/item/netartworks-heath-bunting </a>\r\n','2011-09-16 08:45:00','2011-09-16 09:00:00','2011-06-30 15:48:07','2011-08-23 13:39:03',1,NULL),(135,'Holland from Above',1,'Erik van Heeswijk','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-09-16 11:55:00','2011-06-30 15:48:41','2011-08-23 14:11:35',1,NULL),(136,'Urban Screens',1,'','2011-09-16 12:15:00','2011-09-16 12:35:00','2011-06-30 15:49:21','2011-08-23 14:18:12',1,NULL),(137,'Wrap Up PICNIC',1,'','2011-09-16 13:30:00','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-06-30 15:49:54','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(138,'Award Ceremony Vodafone Mobile Clicks',1,'','2011-09-16 14:15:00','2011-09-16 15:15:00','2011-06-30 15:50:37','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(139,'COMM: Digital Media for a Better Future',5,'COMM is a one-day program at PICNIC Festival 2011, followed by two-day conference in 2012 on the innovative, creative and technical applications and economic growth in the field of ICT and mobile phones, focusing on Africa. At COMM you are an active player. Projects and companies are presenting their current work and technical applications. Field experts and specialists will lecture and give workshops focusing on real issues, ethics, environment and techniques. Our mission is to contribute to a better world through digitally connecting the Netherlands, other western countries and developing economies.\r\n\r\nCOMM offers an attractive program of presentations, discussions and workshops featuring a selection of guest speakers from Africa. The session at PICNIC Festival is closely tied to the themes of the COMM event: technology and sustainability combined with development in Africa.\r\n\r\nCOMM will host a full day of sessions during PICNIC Festival 2011. COMM’s topics have a creative, educational, practical, innovative and social character, with a primary focus on mobile telephony. Our African partners will demonstrate the innovative solutions they developed themselves using mobile technology, mapping, open data and web 2.0 that contribute to the development of the economy and/or society. The projects will be presented and discussed during the morning session of COMM.\r\n\r\nVisitors to COMM will get a better impression of the impact that ICT, mobile technology, and new media (combined with old media) can have on the living conditions of Africa’s urban and rural inhabitants. How can these technologies, especially mobile, improve and strengthen the social and economic developments in Africa? How can we give a voice to people who might otherwise never be heard?\r\n\r\n','2011-09-16 08:00:00','2011-09-16 10:00:00','2011-06-30 15:51:31','2011-08-21 16:24:11',1,NULL),(140,'Open Data Unconference',2,'During last year’s PICNIC Festival, we brought speakers, stakeholders and participants together to discuss the possibilities and implications of open data. Over the course of the year, the topic has flourished worldwide and many open data initiatives were undertaken, especially in the form of competitions and open data portals. These have generated lots of momentum: data was unlocked, Apps and websites were built and new policies were discussed at the local, national and international level. However, these initiatives have more often than not lacked a clear vision of the wider goals, second order effects and follow-up. A lot has been discovered, but there are still burning questions, like:\r\n\r\n•	Criticism is limited now, but what does the future look like?\r\n•	How do we ensure that non-programmers can also benefit?\r\n•	How sustainable are the initiatives that came up?\r\n•	Should some data be paid for, and are we okay with that?\r\n•	What are the limits of openness and who determines them?\r\n\r\nThese and many more questions need to be addressed to prevent the initial enthusiasm from fading. We have to learn from where we stand, and we even might need to come up with certain answers that we all agree upon in order to move forward.\r\n\r\nThe PICNIC Open Data Unconference is an ideal opportunity to take a closer look at these questions and various Open Data topics presented at PICNIC Festival 2011. The accumulated intellectual capital will provide more than enough stimuli for discussion, and the results will be documented. You are warmly invited to share your questions and your point of view.\r\n\r\nThe Open Data unConference is organized by Waag Society, Creative Commons NL, PICNIC, Nederland Opent Data & Amsterdam Innovatie Motor','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-06-30 15:52:01','2011-08-21 16:34:15',1,NULL),(141,'Open Data Unconference',2,'During last year’s PICNIC Festival, we brought speakers, stakeholders and participants together to discuss the possibilities and implications of open data. Over the course of the year, the topic has flourished worldwide and many open data initiatives were undertaken, especially in the form of competitions and open data portals. These have generated lots of momentum: data was unlocked, Apps and websites were built and new policies were discussed at the local, national and international level. However, these initiatives have more often than not lacked a clear vision of the wider goals, second order effects and follow-up. A lot has been discovered, but there are still burning questions, like:\r\n\r\n•	Criticism is limited now, but what does the future look like?\r\n•	How do we ensure that non-programmers can also benefit?\r\n•	How sustainable are the initiatives that came up?\r\n•	Should some data be paid for, and are we okay with that?\r\n•	What are the limits of openness and who determines them?\r\n\r\nThese and many more questions need to be addressed to prevent the initial enthusiasm from fading. We have to learn from where we stand, and we even might need to come up with certain answers that we all agree upon in order to move forward.\r\n\r\nThe PICNIC Open Data Unconference is an ideal opportunity to take a closer look at these questions and various Open Data topics presented at PICNIC Festival 2011. The accumulated intellectual capital will provide more than enough stimuli for discussion, and the results will be documented. You are warmly invited to share your questions and your point of view.\r\n\r\nThe Open Data unConference is organized by Waag Society, Creative Commons NL, PICNIC, Nederland Opent Data & Amsterdam Innovatie Motor','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-09-16 15:15:00','2011-06-30 15:52:23','2011-08-21 16:35:12',1,NULL),(142,'Community Outsourcing',4,'How are new models of technology-enabled community engagement affecting the way our cities are designed, our governments managed and our services delivered? ','2011-09-16 08:00:00','2011-09-16 10:00:00','2011-06-30 15:53:02','2011-08-21 16:37:16',1,NULL),(143,'THNK',4,'','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-06-30 15:53:44','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(144,'World Smart Capital',6,'','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-09-16 15:15:00','2011-06-30 15:54:23','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(145,'Vodafone Mobile Clicks Nominees',4,'','2011-09-15 08:00:00','2011-09-15 10:00:00','2011-07-11 14:50:07','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(146,'PICNIC academy',4,'','2011-09-15 13:45:00','2011-09-15 15:15:00','2011-07-11 14:50:31','2011-08-21 16:06:04',1,NULL),(147,'Hello Avatar: 9 Principles of X-Reality Design',1,'','2011-09-16 08:25:00','2011-09-16 08:45:00','2011-07-11 15:24:22','2011-08-23 13:36:32',1,NULL),(148,'Building the Meta-City',1,'Building the Meta-City, looks into how mobile computing is driving the collective building of virtual layers onto the world. In particular it looks at cities and the spaces inhabited and how real space entangles with virtual spaces\r\n\r\nIn brief: it\'s about the impact of deep metadata, location information, augmented experiences and virtual spaces\r\n\r\n','2011-09-16 08:00:00','2011-09-16 08:25:00','2011-07-11 15:25:13','2011-08-23 13:30:56',1,NULL),(149,'Trust Me and I’ll Trust You',1,'<b>Trust Me and I’ll Trust You: the changing dynamic between Millennials, Brands and Trust</b>\r\n \r\nIt’s time to rethink the role of trust, consumers and your creative concepts. Amanda Mooney is setting the stage to spark as many ideas as possible in her 20 minutes session. Let’s challenge the  relationship between brands and consumers - particularly Millennials, the 8095ers (born between 1980 and 1995). We’ll look at how brands mobilize and engage and how the evolving dynamics of trust – paramount in any successful relationship –influences strategy. At Edelman, we have seen and documented the changes of trust over the years. Millennials in particular expect brands to connect with their passions and to help them achieve something different in their community – whether that community is in their pocket, online or on the street where they live. We now coalesce around shared interests rather than shared locations and we actively choose the communities we join. How do you evolve your brand to be a catalyst instead of a traditional marketer and develop deep, lasting engagement with consumers through building trust? Come and see for yourself','2011-09-16 09:40:00','2011-09-16 10:00:00','2011-07-11 15:25:47','2011-08-25 08:27:39',1,NULL),(150,'Lunch break',4,'Lunch','2011-09-16 10:00:00','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-07-12 10:56:29','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(151,'Coffee break',4,'','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-07-12 10:56:53','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(152,'Open Data: Data Visualisation',6,'Forum Virium joins PICNIC all the way from Helsinki to look at open data in general and data visualization in particular. These “infographics” play a key role in exposing hidden patterns in behavior within the city and reveal the possible impact of the impact this data can have.','2011-09-16 08:00:00','2011-09-16 10:00:00','2011-07-12 10:57:50','2011-08-21 16:28:38',1,NULL),(153,'COMM: Digital Media for a Better Future',5,'COMM is a one-day program at PICNIC Festival 2011, followed by two-day conference in 2012 on the innovative, creative and technical applications and economic growth in the field of ICT and mobile phones, focusing on Africa. At COMM you are an active player. Projects and companies are presenting their current work and technical applications. Field experts and specialists will lecture and give workshops focusing on real issues, ethics, environment and techniques. Our mission is to contribute to a better world through digitally connecting the Netherlands, other western countries and developing economies.\r\n\r\nCOMM offers an attractive program of presentations, discussions and workshops featuring a selection of guest speakers from Africa. The session at PICNIC Festival is closely tied to the themes of the COMM event: technology and sustainability combined with development in Africa.\r\n\r\nCOMM will host a full day of sessions during PICNIC Festival 2011. COMM’s topics have a creative, educational, practical, innovative and social character, with a primary focus on mobile telephony. Our African partners will demonstrate the innovative solutions they developed themselves using mobile technology, mapping, open data and web 2.0 that contribute to the development of the economy and/or society. The projects will be presented and discussed during the morning session of COMM.\r\nVisitors to COMM will get a better impression of the impact that ICT, mobile technology, and new media (combined with old media) can have on the living conditions of Africa’s urban and rural inhabitants. How can these technologies, especially mobile, improve and strengthen the social and economic developments in Africa? How can we give a voice to people who might otherwise never be heard?\r\n\r\n','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-07-12 11:00:05','2011-08-21 16:25:08',1,NULL),(154,'THNK',4,'','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-09-16 15:15:00','2011-07-12 11:01:03','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(157,'Lunch break',4,'Lunch','2011-09-14 10:00:00','2011-09-14 11:30:00','2011-07-21 18:59:36','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,NULL),(158,'Nominee Presentations Green Challenge',4,'','2011-09-14 11:30:00','2011-09-14 13:00:00','2011-07-21 19:02:14','2011-08-18 14:00:19',1,'2011/07/21/12_03_45_383_Green_Challenge_2011.png'),(159,'Nominee Presentations Green Challenge',4,'','2011-09-14 13:45:00','2011-09-14 15:15:00','2011-07-21 19:05:07','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,'2011/07/21/12_03_45_383_Green_Challenge_2011.png'),(160,'Coffee break',4,'','2011-09-14 13:00:00','2011-09-14 13:45:00','2011-07-21 19:06:24','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,'2011/06/30/05_49_47_128_117e8dd389282e27c14ac2bb4545a4e4_l.jpg'),(161,'Vodafone Firestarters',6,'Vodafone Firestarters is a traveling talk show that takes place at a series of events within the art, music, technology and fashion industries. \r\n\r\nInnovative people within a worldwide network surround Vodafone. With Firestarters, Vodafone would like to share the knowledge of these innovative people with the rest of the world via online videos and inspire people by unlocking this inexhaustible source. This edition of Firestarters will be hosted in collaboration with PICNIC Festival.\r\n\r\nDuring each Firestarters session, a discussion will take place concerning the topics innovation and mobile internet, specifically innovation in technology. Journalist Ernst-Jan Pfauth (NRC) will be the moderator during these sessions. Joining him on stage are four selected guests. \r\n\r\nThe discussions are open to all visitors of PICNIC Festival 2011 and will take place on Wednesday, 14 September 2011. The videos will be available online at  <a href=\"http://www.vodafonefirestarters.nl\"> www.vodafonefirestarters.nl </a> after the event.\r\n\r\n <a href=\"http://www.vodafonefirestarters.nl\"> www.vodafonefirestarters.nl </a> \r\n<a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/firestartersNL\">www.twitter.com/firestartersNL</a>','2011-09-14 13:45:00','2011-09-14 15:15:00','2011-07-21 19:20:18','2011-08-21 13:51:58',1,'2011/07/21/12_16_25_836_Firestarter_FinalLogo.jpg'),(162,'Lunch break',12,'','2011-09-14 10:00:00','2011-09-14 11:30:00','2011-07-21 19:21:41','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(163,'Future Study Wisdom of the Crowd',9,'In this creative workshop we aim to develop a future scenario in which citizens co-create government and politics. What if every citizen becomes a Member of Parliament and what if they distributed tasks such as initiating, budgeting, weighing, prioritizing and monitoring? How can future smart cities and social media facilitate these social processes?\r\nThis workshop is part of the future study “Wisdom of the Crowd” carried out at STT, a think tank on technology and society. In this study we explore the future of the wisdom of the crowd in twenty years. What will be next after crowdsourcing, Wikipedia and Twitter? Will we find a way to make better use of our society and the people in it, sharing knowledge and ideas, collaborating, co-creating and making decisions collectively? How can artificial intelligence and the Internet of Things help mankind to become more collectively intelligent? And how can we use this intelligence and everyone’s participation to tackle complex problems such as a healthy lifestyle and clean environment?\r\n\r\nMore information about this future study can be found at \r\n<a href=\"http://www.wisdomofthecrowd.nl\">www.wisdomofthecrowd.nl</a> \r\n','2011-09-14 08:00:00','2011-09-14 10:00:00','2011-07-21 19:28:14','2011-08-21 14:49:10',1,'2011/08/21/07_49_10_994_cropped_zwermflightweb_ed.jpg'),(164,'Coffee break',12,'','2011-09-14 13:00:00','2011-09-14 13:45:00','2011-07-21 19:29:16','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(165,'Light lab',3,'','2011-09-14 08:00:00','2011-09-14 10:00:00','2011-07-21 19:34:23','2011-08-21 15:15:36',1,NULL),(166,'Lunch break',12,'','2011-09-15 10:00:00','2011-09-15 11:30:00','2011-07-21 20:19:14','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(167,'Coffee break',9,'','2011-09-15 13:00:00','2011-09-15 13:45:00','2011-07-21 20:20:47','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(168,'Urban Mobility – Challenges, Ideas, Startups',6,'This workshop session will offer insights into the latest developments in urban mobility services and the possibilities in this field powered by interactive technologies. The audience will be invited to collaborate in groups to create ideas for services that go beyond the car – fueled by the ubiquitous web. The workshop will end with a presentation of the best ideas.\r\n\r\nThe holistic approach of the session will be ensured by the interdisciplinary input of esteemed experts from various backgrounds. \r\n\r\nThe workshop is hosted by BMW i. (<a href=\"http://www.bmw-i.com/en_ww/experience-bmw-i\">www.bmw-i.com/en_ww/experience-bmw-i</a>)\r\n','2011-09-15 13:45:00','2011-09-15 15:15:00','2011-07-22 08:32:53','2011-08-21 15:54:33',1,NULL),(169,'Re/designing the Biology of Cities',2,'Cities consume large amounts of resources -- food, fuel, materials -- most of which is transported long distances. Cities also produce large amounts of waste, most of which is disposed of locally. How can we spend less money and energy moving resources to cities? Architects, urban planners, and designers will soon have new tools in hand to address this problem. This session will present new biological technologies that will enable cities to locally produce food and materials via recycling. The infrastructure for this new mode of production will look very familiar to residents of Amsterdam: greenhouses and beer brewing. And just like brewing beer, this production will take place at both the large and the small scale. This session will have presentations on using microbes to turn cellulose into replacements for petrochemicals (Blue Marble Biomaterials), using algae to recycle sewage into useful biomass (NASA), and growing a city’s entire food supply in a greenhouse (The Polydome Project). A roundtable discussion with the audience will follow.\r\n\r\nThe 20th century was built on fire and mining. The 21st will be built using biological systems that are much more efficient. With a combination of high-tech jobs and distributed production, biological production will move into cities, enabling those cities to make more of the stuff they use. Locally made materials will supply industry and will allow cities to send less capital overseas to import energy and materials in the form of petroleum. Recycling and production in urban areas will soon look radically different than it does today.\r\n','2011-09-15 08:00:00','2011-09-15 10:00:00','2011-07-22 08:34:14','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(170,'BCreative & ImMediaTe: Launch of How To Grow platform  ',3,'','2011-09-15 08:00:00','2011-09-15 10:00:00','2011-07-22 08:34:26','2011-08-21 15:57:09',1,NULL),(171,'The Data of People, Place and Play',3,'The power of data is in its ability to reveal hidden stories, influence our decisions, and teach us about our environments and communities. Data comes in many shapes and forms and the analysis and communication of it is as important as the collection. The panelists have extensive experience in the collection and communication of city and community data - via personal story collection, city data harvesting and distribution, international mapping projects and game design.\r\n','2011-09-15 11:30:00','2011-09-15 13:00:00','2011-07-22 08:35:27','2011-08-21 15:59:30',1,NULL),(172,'Theanycitywhatever',2,'A festival within the festival, the anycitywhatever is a picnic table with local, regional and post-national protagonists of urban futurism. The mission of this 3-hour talk show is to find out how networked technologies are changing the way we understand, build and inhabit cities. \r\nIn the first part before the break, we take a panoramic view of global developments in networked urbanism. After the break, we zoom in on Amsterdam and present local actors already designing networked services that have an immediate impact on the daily lives of Amsterdammers.\r\nGuests include: Adam Greenfield (Urbanscale), Carlo Ratti (MIT Senseable City Lab), Nicola Villa (CISCO), Euro Beinat (CurrentCity Foundation), Katalin Gallyas (Economic Affairs Amsterdam), Michelle Kasprzak (V2), and James Burke (Urbanode).\r\n\r\nHosts include: Ben Hammersley (Editor-at-large Wired UK) and Juha van \'t Zelfde (Non-fiction)\r\n\r\nThe anycitywhatever is organised by Non-fiction, in collaboration with Dienst Ruimtelijke Ordening City of Amsterdam, Amsterdamse Innovatie Motor, Stad-Forum and VURB.\r\n','2011-09-15 11:30:00','2011-09-15 13:00:00','2011-07-22 08:36:46','2011-08-24 20:42:49',1,NULL),(173,'Theanycitywhatever',2,'A festival within the festival, the anycitywhatever is a picnic table with local, regional and post-national protagonists of urban futurism. The mission of this 3-hour talk show is to find out how networked technologies are changing the way we understand, build and inhabit cities. \r\n\r\nIn the first part before the break, we take a panoramic view of global developments in networked urbanism. After the break, we zoom in on Amsterdam and present local actors already designing networked services that have an immediate impact on the daily lives of Amsterdammers.\r\nGuests include: Adam Greenfield (Urbanscale), Carlo Ratti (MIT Senseable City Lab), Nicola Villa (CISCO), Euro Beinat (CurrentCity Foundation), Katalin Gallyas (Economic Affairs Amsterdam), Michelle Kasprzak (V2), and James Burke (Urbanode).\r\n\r\nHosts include: Ben Hammersley (Editor-at-large Wired UK) and Juha van \'t Zelfde (Non-fiction)\r\nThe anycitywhatever is organised by Non-fiction, in collaboration with Dienst Ruimtelijke Ordening City of Amsterdam, Amsterdamse Innovatie Motor, Stad-Forum and VURB.\r\n','2011-09-15 13:45:00','2011-09-15 15:15:00','2011-07-22 08:44:11','2011-08-24 20:43:59',1,NULL),(174,'Lunch break',4,'Lunch','2011-09-15 10:00:00','2011-09-15 11:30:00','2011-07-22 08:46:54','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(175,'Coffee break',3,'','2011-09-15 13:00:00','2011-09-15 13:45:00','2011-07-22 08:48:01','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(177,'I am urban; The green pillars of urbanisation',2,'For the first time in history, the majority of human beings live in urban areas. The numbers of city dwellers are especially high in developed countries. The United States, for instance, is 82 percent urbanized. The pace of urbanization is accelerating as people all over the world flee the countryside and flock to the crowded street. We will elaborate on urban developments and the impact on our behavior and that of our children and discuss  the role of green. We will present some innovative projects involving young scholars in the areas of urban food, urban leisure, urban sports, urban trade and urban ecology. We will also address the economic perspective of green cities. Furthermore we will discuss the concept of creative cities as described in our latest publication The Economy of Experiences (2011 Pearson).\r\n\r\nThis session will include three mini lectures and an interactive session with Kim van der Leest (Director, Triple E), Albert Boswijk (Founder, Centre for the Experience Economy) and Steven Olthof (Partner, ECEE)\r\nThe European Centre for the Experience Economy and Triple E (Ecology, Economy and Experience) will facilitate an interactive session about our green and urban futures\r\n','2011-09-16 08:00:00','2011-09-16 10:00:00','2011-07-22 09:11:10','2011-08-21 16:31:45',1,NULL),(178,'Transmedia Lab',6,'','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-07-22 09:13:30','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(179,'Frog Design Lunch session',12,'','2011-09-16 10:00:00','2011-09-16 11:30:00','2011-07-22 09:17:29','2011-08-21 16:20:01',1,NULL),(180,'Coffee break',12,'','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-07-22 09:18:01','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(181,'City Stories',1,'Herman Kossman','2011-09-14 09:20:00','2011-09-14 09:40:00','2011-08-03 13:05:35','2011-08-23 07:52:19',1,NULL),(182,'The Best City Never Seen',1,'It seems that history is full of cities thought up, imagined, and dreamed of, but that eventually never were realized. Admirable projects, magnificent places, utopian plans: human fantasy has built many more cities than what we see in reality on a map. \r\n\r\nThe Best City Never Seen will be a 20-minute tour into the ruins of these paleo-futuristic cities in the attempt to inspire a new way of thinking about cities and to discover the latent potential of the cities we now live in. \r\n\r\n','2011-09-14 08:10:00','2011-09-14 08:30:00','2011-08-03 13:06:24','2011-08-23 07:46:04',1,NULL),(183,'Rioting, Ballet, and Elvis\'s Hips',1,'\"Smart cities, ubicomp, and other technological wonders are all very well, but cities are made of people, and people are weird. Ben Hammersley will look at how cultures and society change, how technology can outpace good manners, and how designers and makers can change the world without getting into a fight, punching an artist, or taking off their ballet shoes. With music, silly jokes, some quantum physics, and no slides whatsoever.\"\r\n','2011-09-14 12:35:00','2011-09-14 13:00:00','2011-08-03 13:23:07','2011-08-23 08:17:46',1,NULL),(184,'Games in Informal Settlements',1,'How can a mobile game contribute to improving life in informal settlements around the world?\r\n\r\nWorldwide, 1 billion people live in informal settlements and their numbers are growing as migration to cities is increasing. GetH20 Mtaani is a fun game based on the complexity of life: such as the scarcity of water, crime and escalation of conflict but also community\r\ndevelopment. Co-designed with young people from Nairobi, it is spreading across Kenya and Uganda through mobile game websites, Nokia’s Ovi Store and special youth gatherings.\r\n\r\nEmer will share insight into engaging some of the poorest people in a city with a game about their issues, including the design process and the potentials for translation into real world action.\r\n','2011-09-14 14:35:00','2011-09-14 14:50:00','2011-08-03 13:31:55','2011-08-23 08:22:47',1,NULL),(186,'Mobility Scenarios: Let\'s design the future',1,'The world we live in is changing fast. Exploding populations and economic growth in emerging countries are impacting our environment in a serious way. Because of this, we need to think about mobility in a whole new way. It is essential to understand the context - assessing needs as well as addressing the right questions - in order to find the right answers. This will provide an opportunity for significant progress in car design.\r\n\r\nSo, how can we combine responsibility with the freedom to develop inspiring and attractive new mobility concepts for the future? \r\n','2011-09-15 08:35:00','2011-09-15 08:55:00','2011-08-03 14:02:03','2011-08-23 08:30:45',1,NULL),(188,'Imagine a Building That Grows Food!',1,'','2011-09-15 12:35:00','2011-09-15 13:00:00','2011-08-03 14:22:56','2011-08-24 15:55:49',1,'2011/08/24/08_55_49_307_Screen_shot_2011_08_24_at_3.21.46_PM.png'),(189,'The Creative City',1,'Charles Landry','2011-09-15 14:25:00','2011-09-15 14:45:00','2011-08-03 14:41:26','2011-08-23 13:21:16',1,NULL),(190,'Keynote Chairman Mobile Clicks',1,'','2011-09-16 13:45:00','2011-09-16 14:15:00','2011-08-03 16:31:51','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(191,'Lunch break',1,'Lunch','2011-09-15 11:00:00','2011-09-15 11:30:00','2011-08-15 14:55:42','2011-08-18 14:00:20',1,NULL),(192,'Visualising Music, Nature and the Universe',1,'','2011-09-16 12:35:00','2011-09-16 13:00:00','2011-08-15 15:28:30','2011-08-23 14:36:49',1,NULL),(193,'HyperMud Design and Construction',13,'Debate, design, listen, build, experiment and get your hands dirty: the Urban Future is Personal - Waag Society@PICNIC2011!\r\n\r\nHypercrafting the modern landscape - A three-day long experimental workshop in which architects, designers and craftsmen bring together historical crafts and digital fabrication through collaborative prototyping. Combining ancient earth building techniques with computer generated design and CNC fabrication creates life-size architectural structures.\r\n\r\nDigital fabrication in Architecture - It is now possible to transfer designs made on a computer to computer-controlled machinery that creates actual building components. This “file to factory” process enables architects to realize projects featuring complex or double-curved geometries. Digital fabrication offers not only great new technical possibilities, it also enables new ways of distribution, personalization and \r\nsharing. Online communities of creatives and a rising network of backyard industry \r\ngive new meaning to “think global act local”. Digital fabrication is ‘crafting the \r\n21st century way’; personal hypercraft\r\n\r\nThe impact of digital fabrication and new co-creation methodologies on architectural design and the changing roles of the designers, contractors and users will be discussed during these sessions.\r\n\r\nEvery afternoon, during the tgiteotd* drink we will discuss the experiences and workshop outcomes with the Picnic audience.\r\n\r\nParticipants:\r\nHyperb