INSERT INTO `content_flag_fields` VALUES (1,416,'forename','Sydney','2011-08-16 18:01:35','2011-08-16 18:01:35'),(2,416,'surname','Levinson','2011-08-16 18:01:35','2011-08-16 18:01:35'),(3,416,'bio','BabelFish Accountant','2011-08-16 18:01:35','2011-08-16 18:01:35'),(4,427,'forename','Alexandre','2011-08-16 18:15:39','2011-08-16 18:15:39'),(5,427,'surname','Bau','2011-08-16 18:15:39','2011-08-16 18:15:39'),(6,427,'bio','Alexandre Bau is Creative Director of Ralston & Bau, Head of Nordic Materials and partnerships in Transplant. He has a Master in Product & Furniture Design from the french Beaux Arts de Rennes with experience from the luxury and gourmet industry. Today he’s engaged in sustainability issues within design and architecture. Alexandre is the co-founder of Ralston & Bau designers and Transplant, design factory in Norway. \r\n\r\nTwitter @transplanteurs','2011-08-16 18:15:39','2011-08-16 18:15:39'),(7,445,'forename','Kunlé','2011-08-16 21:12:17','2011-08-16 21:12:17'),(8,445,'surname','Adeyemi','2011-08-16 21:12:17','2011-08-16 21:12:17'),(9,445,'bio','Kunlé Adeyemi is an architect, designer and \'urbanist\'. He is 2011 Callison Distinguished Visiting Lecturer of the University of Washington, teaching and researching ‘The Modern City in the Age of Globalization’ in Chandigarh-- India’s first planned modern city. \r\n\r\nHe was creative director for Lagos Photo 2010, Nigeria’s first contemporary public photography exhibition, with the African Artists\' Foundation. \r\n\r\nAdeyemi has a track record of conceiving and completing high-profile, high-quality projects in Europe, Asia, Africa and the Middle East. He carried out many of these projects as Senior Associate and Project Principal at the world renowned Office for Metropolitan Architecture (OMA), Netherlands. These include the award-winning Samsung Museum of Art, SNU Museum, NM Rothschild Bank London, Shenzhen Stock Exchange tower China, Prada Transformer Korea, Central Library, Strategic Studies Center, Headquarters for Qatar Foundation Doha and Lagos 4th Mainland bridge/masterplan. \r\n\r\nBorn and raised in Nigeria, Adeyemi studied architecture at the University of Lagos, where he began his early career before joining Rem Koolhaas/OMA. In 2010, after nearly a decade at OMA, he moved on to start his own practice NLÉ focusing on \'the architecture of developing cities\'.\r\n\r\nHe has always pursued this interest via a number of research papers and study opportunities, including a post-professional degree from Princeton University, where with Peter Eisenman he investigated rapid urbanization and the role of market economies in developing cities of the global South, focusing on Lagos. His hypothesis ‘Urban Crawl’ published in the Log Journal 2007.\r\n\r\nAdeyemi is frequently an invited speaker, lecturer and visiting critic at prestigious institutions such as the Guggenheim New York, Harvard University, the Cooper Union, School of Oriental and African Studies, Architectural Association in London, ETH in Zurich, Chandigarh College of Architecture India and TUDelft in the Netherlands.\r\n','2011-08-16 21:12:17','2011-08-16 21:12:17'),(10,413,'forename','Willempje','2011-08-16 21:58:42','2011-08-16 21:58:42'),(11,413,'surname','Vrins','2011-08-16 21:58:42','2011-08-16 21:58:42'),(12,413,'bio','FigureRunning princess and freelance project developer Media & Innovation','2011-08-16 21:58:42','2011-08-16 21:58:42'),(13,477,'forename','Micky','2011-08-17 07:43:46','2011-08-17 07:43:46'),(14,477,'surname','van Zeijl','2011-08-17 07:43:46','2011-08-17 07:43:46'),(15,477,'bio','I am the Program Coordinator at PICNIC','2011-08-17 07:43:46','2011-08-17 07:43:46'),(16,530,'forename','Matt','2011-08-17 20:06:20','2011-08-17 20:06:20'),(17,530,'surname','Atkins','2011-08-17 20:06:20','2011-08-17 20:06:20'),(18,530,'bio','Sheffield-based web developer, musician and tea-drinker.','2011-08-17 20:06:20','2011-08-17 20:06:20'),(19,565,'forename','Marcel','2011-08-17 20:08:36','2011-08-17 20:08:36'),(20,565,'surname','Kampman','2011-08-17 20:08:36','2011-08-17 20:08:36'),(21,565,'bio','I\'m the directive creator of PICNIC, amongst other things. And that is great, because it means creating stupidly ambitious ideas together as a part of a great team.','2011-08-17 20:08:36','2011-08-17 20:08:36'),(22,654,'forename','Kimberley','2011-08-18 06:28:21','2011-08-18 06:28:21'),(23,654,'surname','Crofts','2011-08-18 06:28:21','2011-08-18 06:28:21'),(24,654,'bio','Designer working for Sydney-based company Meld Studios in service, interaction and information design. Cyclist, eater of good food, sustainable thinker (and doer), music lover. ','2011-08-18 06:28:21','2011-08-18 06:28:21'),(25,444,'forename','Tracy','2011-08-18 07:28:07','2011-08-18 07:28:07'),(26,444,'surname','Metz','2011-08-18 07:28:07','2011-08-18 07:28:07'),(27,444,'bio','Tracy Metz, a native of California, is a journalist and author based in the Netherlands. She is a staff reporter at the Arts desk of the quality national newspaper NRC Handelsblad and an international correspondent for the New York-based magazine Architectural Record. At the Harvard Graduate School of Design Metz was a Loeb Fellow ’07 and is currently a visiting fellow. She is the author of a number of books, including \'FUN! Leisure and Landscape\', about the impact of leisure on the way we use and perceive our surroundings, and a collection of columns and esaays \'On the Ground: Observations from Harvard\'. She is currently working on a book on water in the Netherlands and an exhibition at the Kunsthal in Rotterdam, \'Sweet&Salt: Water and the Dutch\', to open in February 2012.','2011-08-18 07:28:07','2011-08-18 07:28:07'),(28,554,'forename','Melissa','2011-08-18 07:56:35','2011-08-18 07:56:35'),(29,554,'surname','Klunder','2011-08-18 07:56:35','2011-08-18 07:56:35'),(30,554,'bio',NULL,'2011-08-18 07:56:35','2011-08-18 07:56:35'),(31,512,'forename','Jim','2011-08-18 08:38:19','2011-08-18 08:38:19'),(32,512,'surname','Bowes','2011-08-18 08:38:19','2011-08-18 08:38:19'),(33,512,'bio','After 25 years in the advertising communication industry, I founded GreenGraffiti® a sustainable communications firm. Our core product uses an age old form of street are called reverse graffiti to literally clean a communication message out of the dirt. This alternative form of out of home advertising uses no ink, no paper and generates almost no waste. We have also established GreenAdsBlue a water Foundation that easy allows the communication industry to participate in contributing towards providing clean drinking water around the world. \nI deeply believe that the communication industry can play a positive role in making our world a little better place. Idealistic? You bet but it is about time for some idealism. Why am I writing about my company and not myself? Well they really are one in the same. I have chosen to use my business as a tool for environmental and social change.','2011-08-18 08:38:19','2011-08-18 08:38:19'),(34,669,'forename','Michiel','2011-08-18 10:24:56','2011-08-18 10:24:56'),(35,669,'surname','Zwerus','2011-08-18 10:24:56','2011-08-18 10:24:56'),(36,669,'bio','Owner, pursangroyal.com','2011-08-18 10:24:56','2011-08-18 10:24:56'),(37,508,'forename','Andy','2011-08-18 11:02:49','2011-08-18 11:02:49'),(38,508,'surname','Mayer','2011-08-18 11:02:49','2011-08-18 11:02:49'),(39,508,'bio','I\'m the founder of <a href=\"http://www.yoomee.com\" target=\"_new\">Yoomee</a>. We create bespoke social networks, tools and apps for online communities using Agile/Lean principles. We\'re helping PICNIC build this website - starting with a simple beta, and then continuously improving based on your feedback.\n\nAt Yoomee, we specialise in building social web technologies for social good. Typical projects involve creative ways of connecting people together online, solving specific problems that bring about positive social outcomes in the real-world. We work with nonprofit, social entrepreneurs, charity, third sector and advocacy groups to create bespoke custom social networking websites and social media tools.\n\nFeel free to get in touch if you have any questions about this site, or want to discuss developing a similar project. If you\'d like to find out more about what we do at <a href=\"http://www.yoomee.com\" target=\"_new\">Yoomee</a>, then please check out our website at <a href=\"http://www.yoomee.com\" target=\"_new\">yoomee.com</a>.\n\nWhen I am not doing Yoomee, then I am busy being a father, husband, petrolhead, Arduino and fencing fan - touché!','2011-08-18 11:02:49','2011-08-18 11:02:49'),(40,657,'forename','Bruni','2011-08-18 13:18:54','2011-08-18 13:18:54'),(41,657,'surname','Hofman','2011-08-18 13:18:54','2011-08-18 13:18:54'),(42,657,'bio','innovation consultant\nclustermanager\nat Syntens Amsterdam','2011-08-18 13:18:54','2011-08-18 13:18:54'),(43,785,'bio','Robbert Dijkgraaf (1960), Distinguished University Professor of Mathematical Physics at the University of Amsterdam and President of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences. Prof Dijkgraaf studied physics and mathematics at Utrecht University. He gained his PhD cum laude in 1989 with Nobel Prize-winner Gerard \'t Hooft. He held positions at Princeton University and Princeton\'s Institute for Advanced Study.\r\nHis current focus is on string theory, quantum gravity, and the interface between mathematics and particle physics. In 2003 his research was rewarded with the NWO Spinoza Prize, the highest scientific award in the Netherlands.\r\n\r\nMany of his activities are at the interface between science and society. He writes columns, is involved in a popular TV science programme and initiated www.proefjes.nl (science education).\r\n\r\nProf Dijkgraaf was member of the Innovation Platform, chaired by the Prime Minister. Since 2009 he is co-chair of the InterAcademy Council, a multinational organization of science academies, together with Professor Lu Yongxiang, President of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.\r\n','2011-08-18 14:21:42','2011-08-18 14:21:42'),(44,785,'bio','Robbert Dijkgraaf (1960), Distinguished University Professor of Mathematical Physics at the University of Amsterdam and President of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences. Prof Dijkgraaf studied physics and mathematics at Utrecht University. He gained his PhD c*m laude in 1989 with Nobel Prize-winner Gerard \'t Hooft. He held positions at Princeton University and Princeton\'s Institute for Advanced Study.\r\nHis current focus is on string theory, quantum gravity, and the interface between mathematics and particle physics. In 2003 his research was rewarded with the NWO Spinoza Prize, the highest scientific award in the Netherlands.\r\n\r\nMany of his activities are at the interface between science and society. He writes columns, is involved in a popular TV science programme and initiated www.proefjes.nl (science education).\r\n\r\nProf Dijkgraaf was member of the Innovation Platform, chaired by the Prime Minister. Since 2009 he is co-chair of the InterAcademy Council, a multinational organization of science academies, together with Professor Lu Yongxiang, President of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.\r\n','2011-08-18 14:21:42','2011-08-18 14:21:42'),(45,785,'forename','Robbert','2011-08-18 14:26:00','2011-08-18 14:26:00'),(46,785,'surname','Dijkgraaf','2011-08-18 14:26:00','2011-08-18 14:26:00'),(47,785,'bio','Robbert Dijkgraaf (1960), Distinguished University Professor of Mathematical Physics at the University of Amsterdam and President of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences. Prof Dijkgraaf studied physics and mathematics at Utrecht University. He gained his PhD cumlaude in 1989 with Nobel Prize-winner Gerard \'t Hooft. He held positions at Princeton University and Princeton\'s Institute for Advanced Study.\n\nHis current focus is on string theory, quantum gravity, and the interface between mathematics and particle physics. In 2003 his research was rewarded with the NWO Spinoza Prize, the highest scientific award in the Netherlands.\n\nMany of his activities are at the interface between science and society. He writes columns, is involved in a popular TV science programme and initiated www.proefjes.nl (science education).\n\nProf Dijkgraaf was member of the Innovation Platform, chaired by the Prime Minister. Since 2009 he is co-chair of the InterAcademy Council, a multinational organization of science academies, together with Professor Lu Yongxiang, President of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.\n','2011-08-18 14:28:43','2011-08-18 14:28:43'),(48,586,'forename','Kevin','2011-08-18 14:45:04','2011-08-18 14:45:04'),(49,586,'surname','DiVico','2011-08-18 14:45:04','2011-08-18 14:45:04'),(50,586,'bio','Hello everyone, as promised more bio: \n\nPast:  \"we make the magic\".  That was the mantra of the theater crew I was apart of in 1977, and it has stuck with me to this day.  I have worked in theater (technical, acting) , the heady pirate days of music in NYC in the eighties, served in my country\'s military,  studied numerous passions  , and have known success and failure in both life and business and I believe I am the richer for it. \n\nPresent: I am currently resetting my life to focus on applying my passion for art, science, technology and philosophy with my skills at problem solving to tackle the \'perfect storms\" that are quickly heading into humanity\'s path.\n \nI now play a positive sum game - always looking for the Win/Win.','2011-08-18 14:45:04','2011-08-18 14:45:04'),(51,521,'forename','Jonathan','2011-08-18 15:48:27','2011-08-18 15:48:27'),(52,521,'surname','Marks','2011-08-18 15:48:27','2011-08-18 15:48:27'),(53,521,'bio','Leader, Writer, Broadcaster, Strategist. My Mantra is \"Empowering Digital Storytellers\". I have a life-long passion for making great content and building audiences. I explore relevant technologies which I believe will have a fundamental impact on communication industries. I lead an international knowledge network specializing in building cross-media strategies for companies who are serious about building authentic conversations in society. I get the greatest kick out of working with young media entrepreneurs, like those who turn up at Picnic. Currently building collaborative platforms on Google+ and Pearltrees','2011-08-18 15:48:27','2011-08-18 15:48:27'),(54,639,'forename','Martine','2011-08-18 17:49:41','2011-08-18 17:49:41'),(55,639,'surname','Eyzenga','2011-08-18 17:49:41','2011-08-18 17:49:41'),(56,639,'bio','I\'m senior designer at PICNIC\'11','2011-08-18 17:49:42','2011-08-18 17:49:42'),(57,507,'forename','Kitty','2011-08-18 18:19:38','2011-08-18 18:19:38'),(58,507,'surname','Leering','2011-08-18 18:19:38','2011-08-18 18:19:38'),(59,507,'bio','I\'m the Program Director & interim General Manager of PICNIC. \n\nI have been involved with PICNIC from the very start. I have been responsible for project management of the whole Festival in 2006 and 2007. In 2008 I got more involved with the programming of the Specials and the Labs. As of 2009 I have been responsible for all of the PICNIC Festival programming. \n\nIn addition I develop, program, give advise on and manage professional events on a freelance basis (DutchBlend). I mostly work on events that focus on the crossroads between creativity, (media)technology, business and governance. A few examples of events that I have been working on are SpinAwards, ICT Delta, Mediapark Jaarcongres, Dutch Bloggies and TEDxWomen (as a volunteer project manager). \n\nUntil 2005 I worked as the Event Director Benelux for IT-research firm IDC, building their regional event business from the ground up. At Media Plaza (1997-2002) I got acquainted with the world of internet, ICT and new media. ','2011-08-18 18:19:38','2011-08-18 18:19:38'),(60,620,'forename','Juha','2011-08-19 08:16:49','2011-08-19 08:16:49'),(61,620,'surname','van ‘t Zelfde','2011-08-19 08:16:49','2011-08-19 08:16:49'),(62,620,'bio','As researcher, developer and radical user in the converging domains of art, heritage, network technology and urbanism, Juha works as a middleperson between those who mind the past and those who invent the future. With Michiel van Iersel he founded Non-fiction, an Amsterdam based interdisciplinary innovation agency working at the intersection of the arts, heritage, network technology and urban development. Non-fiction works with a.o. the Stedelijk Museum, Stadsherstel and the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra.\n\nWith Ben Cerveny and James Burke, Juha founded VURB, a European framework for policy and design research concerning urban computational systems. The VURB foundation provides direction and resources to a portfolio of projects investigating how our cultures might come to use networked digital resources to change the way we understand, build, and inhabit cities.\n\nLastly, Juha founded Viral Radio, a vehicle for discovery and distribution of electronic music. Viral Radio sets up site-specific performances for festivals and music venues in Europe, displaying new developments in computer music exploration and hyperrhythmic dance music. It a.o. works with Exit Festival, Appelsap, North Sea Jazz Festival and Bimhuis.','2011-08-19 08:16:49','2011-08-19 08:16:49'),(63,788,'forename','Thijs','2011-08-19 08:22:50','2011-08-19 08:22:50'),(64,788,'surname','Molhoek','2011-08-19 08:22:50','2011-08-19 08:22:50'),(65,788,'bio','Selling Consultant at A New Spring \n\nE-learning, Blended Learning, Social Learning, SaaS, Online Learning, Adaptive Learning, Personal, MemoTrainer, Goal Oriented, scorm certified. ','2011-08-19 08:22:50','2011-08-19 08:22:50'),(66,445,'bio','Kunlé Adeyemi is an architect, designer and \'urbanist\'. He is a 2011 Callison Distinguished Visiting Lecturer at the University of Washington, teaching and researching \"The Modern City in the Age of Globalization\" in Chandigarh -- India’s first planned modern city. \r\n\r\nRecently, he was creative director for Lagos Photo 2010, Nigeria’s first contemporary public photography exhibition, with the African Artists\' Foundation. \r\n\r\nAdeyemi has a track record of conceiving and completing high-profile, high-quality projects in Europe, Asia, Africa and the Middle East. He carried out many of these projects as Senior Associate and Project Principal at the world renowned Office for Metropolitan Architecture (OMA), Netherlands. These include the award-winning Samsung Museum of Art, SNU Museum, NM Rothschild Bank London, Shenzhen Stock Exchange tower China, Prada Transformer Korea, Central Library, Strategic Studies Center, Headquarters for Qatar Foundation Doha and Lagos 4th Mainland bridge/masterplan. \r\n\r\nBorn and raised in Nigeria, Adeyemi studied architecture at the University of Lagos, where he began his early career before joining Rem Koolhaas/OMA. In 2010, after nearly a decade at OMA, he moved on to start his own practice NLÉ focusing on \"the architecture of developing cities\".\r\n\r\nHe has always pursued this interest via a number of research papers and study opportunities, including a post-professional degree from Princeton University, where with Peter Eisenman he investigated rapid urbanization and the role of market economies in developing cities of the global South, focusing on Lagos. His hypothesis ‘Urban Crawl’ published in the Log Journal 2007.\r\n\r\nAdeyemi is frequently an invited speaker, lecturer and visiting critic at prestigious institutions such as the Guggenheim New York, Harvard University, the Cooper Union, School of Oriental and African Studies, Architectural Association in London, ETH in Zurich, Chandigarh College of Architecture India and TUDelft in the Netherlands.\r\n','2011-08-19 09:26:47','2011-08-19 09:26:47'),(67,587,'forename','Toby','2011-08-19 09:28:28','2011-08-19 09:28:28'),(68,587,'surname','Barnes','2011-08-19 09:28:28','2011-08-19 09:28:28'),(69,587,'bio','Principle, Mudlark\r\n\r\nToby has been delivering digital products and services since 1995, working in many roles in media and digital through publishing, production and development. He has worked for a number of key industry leaders such as Emap, Virgin, MTV Networks, and Two Way TV Games. And has worked with a number of global clients including Microsoft, SCEE, Electronic Arts, RSC, Channel 4 and Mattel.  As a founding member of Virgin Media’s Interactive Division launching Europe’s first commercial interactive TV service.  More recently he was responsible for interactive content across mobile, broadband and narrowband for MTV multiple European channels.\r\n\r\nCurrently one of the principals at the Mudlark Production Company: a multi platform production company \"Making Life Playable\". Toby is Executive Producer on Chromaroma, Mudlark\'s first major self published project. An online multiplayer game played out as you travel the city with your Oyster Card.\r\n\r\nHe has spoken at a large number of events such as Playful, SXSW, Games Developer Conference, and Interesting on playful design, cheating, cities, play and open data. He is an advisor to the Greater London Authority, and the Mayor of London on a range of digital issues. ','2011-08-19 09:28:28','2011-08-19 09:28:28'),(70,587,'bio','Principle, Mudlark\r\n\r\nToby has been delivering digital products and services since 1995, working in many roles in media and digital through publishing, production and development. He has worked for a number of key industry leaders such as Emap, Virgin, MTV Networks, and Two Way TV Games. And has worked with a number of global clients including Microsoft, SCEE, Electronic Arts, RSC, Channel 4 and Mattel.  As a founding member of Virgin Media’s Interactive Division, he helped launch Europe’s first commercial interactive TV service.  More recently he was responsible for interactive content across mobile, broadband and narrowband for MTV\'s multiple European channels.\r\n\r\nToby is currently one of the principals at the Mudlark Production Company: a multi platform production company \"Making Life Playable\". Toby is Executive Producer on Chromaroma, Mudlark\'s first major self-published project. It\'s an online multiplayer game played out as you travel the city with your Oyster Card.\r\n\r\nHe has spoken at a large number of events such as Playful, SXSW, Games Developer Conference, and Interesting on playful design, cheating, cities, play and open data. He is an advisor to the Greater London Authority and the Mayor of London on a range of digital issues. ','2011-08-19 09:41:31','2011-08-19 09:41:31'),(71,545,'forename','David','2011-08-19 10:11:52','2011-08-19 10:11:52'),(72,545,'surname','Barrie','2011-08-19 10:11:52','2011-08-19 10:11:52'),(73,545,'bio','David Barrie runs a creative and social project production company that enables capital growth in cities and the improvement of people\'s lives. \r\n\r\nThe company performs a wide range of consultancy and production roles for major clients in the real estate, urban renewal, housing, construction and entertainment industries. \r\n\r\nDavid has designed and delivered ventures valued at over £17m (€19m) that have created new bridges, buildings, public spaces, commercial and social businesses. They have won several major awards, such as the 2011 Observer Ethical Prize (for The People\'s Supermarket) and the 2009 Grand Prix, Regeneration & Renewal and RIBA CABE Public Space Awards (sister of the Stirling Prize) (for The Castleford Project) - and they  have been extensively featured by the national and international media, including the BBC, NHK, New York Times, China Daily and  Monocle.\r\n\r\nAn element of David\'s work is the production of projects and programmes for broadcast media, most recently an environmental initiative for Sky 1 HD and a drama documentary for Channel 4 Television on the life of the 1930s socialite Wallis Simpson.\r\n\r\nMore at http://about.me/davidbarrie & http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Barrie. ','2011-08-19 10:11:52','2011-08-19 10:11:52'),(74,523,'forename','Jake','2011-08-19 10:20:37','2011-08-19 10:20:37'),(75,523,'surname','Barton','2011-08-19 10:20:37','2011-08-19 10:20:37'),(76,523,'bio','Jake Barton is principal and Founder of Local Projects, which is the media designer for the 9/11 Memorial Museum, StoryCorps, Change By Us, and the Frank Gehry designed Eisenhower Presidential Memorial. Located in New York City, Local Projects is a three-time National Design Award finalist, and was named the second most innovative design firm by Fast Company in 2010 for its redefinition of emotional storytelling. Jake is recognized as a leader in the field of media design for physical spaces, and in the creation of collaborative storytelling projects where participants tell their own stories.  Current clients include the BMW Guggenheim Lab, Stone Barns Center for Food and Agriculture, Cleveland Museum of Art, Seaworld, and the National Museum of African-American History and Culture. While working with the American Museum of Natural History he was airlifted out of a Central African rainforest by diamond smugglers, but now happily lives on the edge by cycling to his studio in New York City.  \r\n\r\nYou can connect with him @jake_barton.','2011-08-19 10:20:37','2011-08-19 10:20:37'),(77,578,'forename','Alessandro ','2011-08-19 11:01:30','2011-08-19 11:01:30'),(78,578,'surname','Bassi','2011-08-19 11:01:30','2011-08-19 11:01:30'),(79,578,'bio','Despite being tempted by other disciplines, Alex decided to explore the\r\nesoteric world of computer science, mainly because of his tension between\r\ncreativity and mathematical rigour. He enjoyed his stay in Milan, where he\r\nattended its world famous University, and became passionate of artificial\r\nintelligence, soft computing and software engineering. After serving his\r\nduty in the army, as many of us, he lent his abilities to the private\r\nsector, and joined Amadeus in 1997, to become -against his will- an expert\r\nof Unisys OS 2200 assembler. He then managed to unchain his spirit again\r\nand joined the University of Tennessee in summer 2000, where he was\r\ninvolved in the seminal work and development of the Internet Backplane\r\nProtocol. After surviving \"Nax-vul\" for 18 months, he managed to get back\r\nto Europe, and in particular to Lyon, where he had a position as Research\r\nVisitor at the Ecole Normale Superieure. For two years, he developed the\r\nrelationship between the novel storage concepts and active networking. He\r\nthen worked for RIPE NCC, working on project regarding the whois database\r\nsuch as the AfriNIC creation, and after one year of rainy A\'dam in\r\nNovember 2004 he moved to the sunny south of France, to integrate the\r\nHitachi Sophia Antipolis Labs. There he got involved in various projects,\r\nregarding Grid and Cloud (with particular regards to data aspects),\r\nAutonomic Communications and RFID. In 2007 he became chair of the then\r\nRFID (now Internet of Things) Working Group of the EU Technological\r\nPlatform EPoSS, and from 2010 he started his own company, Alessandro Bassi\r\nConsulting, acting as a Technical Coordinator for the Internet of Things\r\nArchitecture (IoT-A) FP7 IP project for Hitachi, Ltd.','2011-08-19 11:01:30','2011-08-19 11:01:30'),(80,578,'bio','Despite being tempted by other disciplines, Alex decided to explore the esoteric world of computer science, mainly because of his personal conflict between creativity and mathematical rigour. He enjoyed his stay in Milan, where he\r\nattended its world famous University, and became passionate about artificial intelligence, soft computing and software engineering. \r\n\r\nAfter serving his term in the army, he lent his abilities to the private sector, and joined Amadeus in 1997, to become (against his will!) an expert in Unisys OS 2200 assembler. He then managed to unchain his spirit again and joined the University of Tennessee in 2000, where he was involved in the seminal work and development of the Internet Backplane\r\nProtocol. After surviving \"Nax-vul\" for 18 months, he managed to get back to Europe, specifically Lyon, where he had a position as Research Visitor at the Ecole Normale Superieure. For two years, he developed the relationship between novel storage concepts and active networking. He then worked for RIPE NCC, working on projects related to the \"whois\" database such as the AfriNIC creation. \r\n\r\nAfter one year in rainy Amsterdam, he moved to the sunny south of France in November 2004 to integrate the\r\nHitachi Sophia Antipolis Labs. There he got involved in various projects related to Grid and Cloud (with particular focus on data aspects), Autonomic Communications and RFID. In 2007, he became chair of the then RFID (now Internet of Things) Working Group of the EU Technological\r\nPlatform EPoSS, and from 2010 he started his own company Alessandro Bassi Consulting, acting as a Technical Coordinator for the Internet of Things Architecture (IoT-A) FP7 IP project for Hitachi, Ltd.','2011-08-19 11:10:32','2011-08-19 11:10:32'),(81,578,'bio','Despite being tempted by other disciplines, Alex decided to explore the esoteric world of computer science, mainly because of his personal conflict between creativity and mathematical rigour. He enjoyed his stay in Milan, where he\nattended its world famous University, and became passionate about artificial intelligence, soft computing and software engineering. \n\nAfter serving his term in the army, he lent his abilities to the private sector, and joined Amadeus in 1997, to become (against his will!) an expert in Unisys OS 2200 assembler. He then managed to unchain his spirit again and joined the University of Tennessee in 2000, where he was involved in the seminal work and development of the Internet Backplane\nProtocol. After surviving \"Nax-vul\" for 18 months, he managed to get back to Europe, specifically Lyon, where he had a position as Research Visitor at the Ecole Normale Superieure. For two years, he developed the relationship between novel storage concepts and active networking. He then worked for RIPE NCC, working on projects related to the \"whois\" database such as the AfriNIC creation. \n\nAfter one year in rainy Amsterdam, he moved to the sunny south of France in November 2004 to integrate the Hitachi Sophia Antipolis Labs. There he got involved in various projects related to Grid and Cloud (with particular focus on data aspects), Autonomic Communications and RFID. In 2007, he became chair of the then RFID (now Internet of Things) Working Group of the EU Technological\nPlatform EPoSS, and from 2010 he started his own company Alessandro Bassi Consulting, acting as a Technical Coordinator for the Internet of Things Architecture (IoT-A) FP7 IP project for Hitachi, Ltd.','2011-08-19 11:15:03','2011-08-19 11:15:03'),(82,427,'bio','Alexandre Bau is Creative Director of Ralston & Bau as well as Head of Nordic Materials and Partnerships at Transplant. He has a masters degree in product & furniture design from the Beaux Arts de Rennes (FR) and has a wide range of  experience in the luxury and gourmet industries. Today he’s engaged in sustainability issues within design and architecture. Alexandre co-founded both Ralston & Bau designers and Transplant, a design factory in Norway. \r\n\r\nTwitter @transplanteurs','2011-08-19 11:29:40','2011-08-19 11:29:40'),(83,434,'forename','David','2011-08-19 11:46:54','2011-08-19 11:46:54'),(84,434,'surname','Bausola','2011-08-19 11:46:54','2011-08-19 11:46:54'),(85,434,'bio','CEO Philter Phactory\r\n\r\nDavid Bausola has been inventing with software and media services for over a decade. From Virtual Nightclubs for Intel, delivering the first Sony PS1 online gaming, introducing Creative Commons to Channel 4 TV, to creating Ford’s social media sitcom “Where are the Joneses?” through to devising a digital agency for Adidas. \r\n\r\nAll this has led to asking: If the majority of projects are about converting people to users, surely it’s easier just to make the users?\r\n\r\nPhilter Phactory are exploring the post-human Internet, filtering social data with software agents so that they to find a voice, live an existence and raise questions that humans fail to ask. Currently on the Phactory workbench is Weavrs.com - your Alter Egos for the Social Web.','2011-08-19 11:46:54','2011-08-19 11:46:54'),(86,862,'forename','Emer','2011-08-19 12:01:43','2011-08-19 12:01:43'),(87,862,'surname','Beamer','2011-08-19 12:01:43','2011-08-19 12:01:43'),(88,862,'bio','Emer Beamer is co-founder of Butterfly Works, a design studio for social change.\r\n\r\nThe Amsterdam-based studio works globally with a core team of 11 designers and organizers. Butterfly Works has developed numerous concepts which contribute to greater equality in the world -- concepts which are currently used in 20 countries on 3 continents.\r\n\r\nEmer focusses on designing meaningful learning experiences for young people in countries such as Kenya, Nigeria, Cambodia and Afghanistan. She is currently investigating the potential of mobile games and apps\r\nto reach young people in informal settlements and (post)conflict states.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.butterflyworks.org\">www.butterflyworks.org </a>\r\nEmer tweets: @EmerBeamer and @ButterflyWorks','2011-08-19 12:01:43','2011-08-19 12:01:43'),(89,892,'forename','Janine','2011-08-19 12:03:33','2011-08-19 12:03:33'),(90,892,'surname','Huizenga','2011-08-19 12:03:33','2011-08-19 12:03:33'),(91,892,'bio',NULL,'2011-08-19 12:03:33','2011-08-19 12:03:33'),(92,916,'forename','Bas','2011-08-19 12:43:44','2011-08-19 12:43:44'),(93,916,'surname','van Abel','2011-08-19 12:43:44','2011-08-19 12:43:44'),(94,916,'bio','Bas is passionate about developing a wide variety of projects based on open design principles. As co- founder of Waag Society’s Fablab (a community fabrication laboratory) and the Instructables Restaurant (an open source restaurant), he is an active member of the international maker and digital fabrication community.\r\n\r\nBas has a background in interaction design and a personal interest in electronics and has been working on many projects both as a designer and technical engineer. As head of the Open Design Lab he currently researches the interface between production technologies and network cultures.\r\nSome of his current initiatives are: FairPhone – building world’s first fair mobile phone, Fablab Suriname – setting up a Fablab in Suriname, and the (Un)limited Design Contest – an open source design contest. \r\n\r\nBas is co-editor of the book “Open Design Now”, a book on the transformation of design into an open discipline, in which designs are shared and innovation of a large diversity of products is a collaborative and world spanning process.','2011-08-19 12:43:44','2011-08-19 12:43:44'),(95,633,'forename','Alissa','2011-08-19 12:45:20','2011-08-19 12:45:20'),(96,633,'surname','Black','2011-08-19 12:45:20','2011-08-19 12:45:20'),(97,633,'bio','Alissa is the Government Relations Director at Code for America. Code for America is a new non-profit fellowship program that recruits passionate technologist to public service to build light-weight creative technology that solves core government challenges. \r\n\r\nAlissa has extensive experience as a manager, policy analyst and leader in local government. In the New York City’s Mayor’s Office, she coordinated the policy portfolios of multiple departments to ensure progress and execution of the city’s agenda, and later she managed a development and design team that supported New York’s 311 Citizen Service Center — the most highly used 311 service in the country. After gaining experience in the private sector consulting, Alissa joined the San Francisco’s Emerging Technologies team in 2007, where she led the development and deployment of Open311, the leading national standard for citizen reporting. \r\n\r\nAlissa graduated from New York University in 2003 with a Master’s in Urban Planning.\r\n\r\n','2011-08-19 12:45:20','2011-08-19 12:45:20'),(98,456,'forename','Jan','2011-08-19 13:03:03','2011-08-19 13:03:03'),(99,456,'surname','Brauer','2011-08-19 13:03:03','2011-08-19 13:03:03'),(100,456,'bio','Jan Brauer is a designer, the coordinator of Ideal Lab and Manager of the Transplant model workshop. He has a Master\'s in industrial design from Burg Giebichenstein. \r\n\r\nJan\'s has a passion for product design and graphics, as well as illustrative art.','2011-08-19 13:03:03','2011-08-19 13:03:03'),(101,515,'forename','Lilet ','2011-08-19 13:05:57','2011-08-19 13:05:57'),(102,515,'surname','Breddels ','2011-08-19 13:05:57','2011-08-19 13:05:57'),(103,515,'bio','Lilet Breddels is an art historian living and working in Amsterdam. She is director of the Archis Foundation, a cultural think tank dealing with spatial reflexivity and urban urgencies and publisher of Volume Magazine. Archis initiates projects and debates all over the world. (www.archis.org)','2011-08-19 13:05:57','2011-08-19 13:05:57'),(104,772,'forename','Mark','2011-08-19 13:24:09','2011-08-19 13:24:09'),(105,772,'surname','Woerde','2011-08-19 13:24:09','2011-08-19 13:24:09'),(106,772,'bio','Founder, Letsheal.org\r\nCo-founder & Strategy Director, LEMZ\r\n\r\nMark Woerde is the founder of Letsheal.org and author of the book \"How Advertising Will Heal the World and Your Business\". He is also the co-founder and strategy director of the award-winning Dutch advertising agency LEMZ.\r\n\r\nLetsheal.org is an Amsterdam-based independent non-profit organization aimed at providing insights on how to transform brands into meaningful prosocial brands. \r\n','2011-08-19 13:24:09','2011-08-19 13:24:09'),(107,474,'forename','Lucy','2011-08-19 13:26:13','2011-08-19 13:26:13'),(108,474,'surname','Walker','2011-08-19 13:26:13','2011-08-19 13:26:13'),(109,474,'bio','Lucy Walker has directed four award-winning feature documentaries: DEVIL’S PLAYGROUND (premiered Sundance 2002), BLINDSIGHT (premiered Toronto 2006), WASTE LAND and COUNTDOWN TO ZERO (both premiered Sundance 2010). \r\n\r\nIn 2011, Lucy was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Documentary for directing WASTE LAND, which won over 30 other awards including the Audience Awards at Sundance and Berlin and the IDA’s Best Documentary Award. Recognition for DEVIL’S PLAYGROUND, about Amish teenagers, included nominations for three Emmys and an Independent Spirit Award. BLINDSIGHT won many festivals, including Berlin, and was longlisted for the Academy Award. \r\n\r\nLucy grew up in London, England, and studied English at Oxford University, where she started out directing theater before winning a Fulbright Scholarship to attend the MFA graduate film program at NYU’s Tisch School of the Arts. She was also a DJ and directed Nickelodeon’s BLUE’S CLUES, for which she was twice nominated for an Emmy. \r\n\r\nLucy has a new short documentary premiering at the Toronto Internationa Film Festival in September 2011about the recent tragic tsunami in Japan, and how the subsequent cherry blossom season brought some hope to the victims in the most hard-hit areas. ','2011-08-19 13:26:13','2011-08-19 13:26:13'),(110,891,'forename','Scott','2011-08-19 13:55:23','2011-08-19 13:55:23'),(111,891,'surname','Snibbe','2011-08-19 13:55:23','2011-08-19 13:55:23'),(112,891,'bio','Scott Snibbe is a media artist, filmmaker, and researcher in interactivity. Whether on mobile devices or in large public spaces, his interactive art spurs people to participate socially, emotionally, and physically. His works are strongly influenced by cinema: particularly animation, silent, and surrealist film; and often mix live and filmed performances with real-time interaction. Snibbe’s artwork is in the permanent collections of the Whitney Museum of American Art (New York) and The Museum of Modern Art (New York); and has been shown in several hundred solo and group exhibitions worldwide, including a solo retrospective at the Institute of Contemporary Arts in London. His large-scale interactive projects have been incorporated into concert tours, Olympics, science museums, airports, and other major public spaces and events, and he has collaborated on interactive projects with musicians and filmmakers including Björk and James Cameron.\r\n\r\nSnibbe has received grants and awards for his artwork from the National Science Foundation, Renew Media, the Rockefeller Foundation, the Ford Foundation, Prix Ars Electronica, and the National Endowment for the Arts. He is the founder of three organizations: Snibbe Interactive, creating interactive exhibits and events; Scott Snibbe Studio, producing apps for mobile devices; and Sona Research, engaging in educational and cultural research.\r\n\r\nSnibbe was born in 1969 in New York City. He holds Bachelor’s degrees in Computer Science and Fine Art, and a Master’s in Computer Science from Brown University. Snibbe studied experimental animation at the Rhode Island School of Design and his films have been widely shown internationally. He has taught media art and experimental film at Brown University, The San Francisco Art Institute, the California Institute of the Arts, the Rhode Island School of Design, and U.C. Berkeley. Early in his career, Snibbe worked at Adobe Systems where he helped to create the special effects software After Effects. Snibbe also worked at Interval Research, performing basic research in haptics, computer vision, and interactive cinema. As a researcher, Snibbe has published numerous articles and academic papers, and is an inventor on over a dozen patents.','2011-08-19 13:55:23','2011-08-19 13:55:23'),(113,642,'forename','Francesca','2011-08-19 14:07:54','2011-08-19 14:07:54'),(114,642,'surname','Bria','2011-08-19 14:07:54','2011-08-19 14:07:54'),(115,642,'bio','Francesca Bria is is currently a PhD Researcher and Teaching Associate in IInnovation and Entrepreneurship at Imperial College Business School London, in the digital economy laboratory (http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/digital-economy-lab). She is investigating issues ranging from Social Media platforms to Smart Cities. She is a consultant on Innovation policy for the  Province of Rome and she’s an expert evaluator for the European Commission on ICT, Future Internet and Smart Cities. Francesca has an Msc in E-business and Innovation from the University College of London, Birkbeck and she is has been working as Tutor in Business Strategy and Organisational Change at Queen Mary University in London. She is a member of the Internet of Things Council ','2011-08-19 14:07:54','2011-08-19 14:07:54'),(116,642,'bio','Francesca Bria is is currently a PhD Researcher and Teaching Associate in IInnovation and Entrepreneurship at Imperial College Business School London, in the digital economy laboratory (http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/digital-economy-lab). \r\n\r\nShe is investigating issues ranging from Social Media platforms to Smart Cities. She is a consultant on Innovation policy for the  Province of Rome and she’s an expert evaluator for the European Commission on ICT, Future Internet and Smart Cities. Francesca has an MSc in E-business and Innovation from the University College of London, Birkbeck and she is has been working as Tutor in Business Strategy and Organisational Change at Queen Mary University in London. She is a member of the Internet of Things Council. ','2011-08-19 14:12:38','2011-08-19 14:12:38'),(117,805,'forename','Cathy','2011-08-19 14:15:36','2011-08-19 14:15:36'),(118,805,'surname','Brickwood','2011-08-19 14:15:36','2011-08-19 14:15:36'),(119,805,'bio','I work as programme manager at Virtueel Platform, the sector institute for electronic culture in the Netherlands. \r\n\r\nRecently my work has focussed on documenting best practices in the Dutch e-culture scene, editing books and supporting international digital culture initiatives. For this year\'s PICNIC Festival, I\'ll be launching our new book \"Ownership in the Hybrid City\", a collaboration with The Mobile City. ','2011-08-19 14:15:36','2011-08-19 14:15:36'),(120,584,'forename','Heath','2011-08-19 15:31:34','2011-08-19 15:31:34'),(121,584,'surname','Bunting','2011-08-19 15:31:34','2011-08-19 15:31:34'),(122,584,'bio','Artist\nCo-founder net.art and sport-art\n\nHeath Bunting was born a Buddhist in Wood Green, London, UK and is able to make himself laugh. (currently, reduced to only smile)\n\nHe is a co-founder of both net.art and sport-art movements and is banned for life from entering the USA for his anti genetic work. His self-taught and authentically independent work is direct and uncomplicated and has never been awarded a prize. \n\nHe is both Britain\'s most important practicing artist and The World\'s most famous computer artist. He aspires to be a skillful member of the public and is producing an expert system for identity mutation.\n\n','2011-08-19 15:31:34','2011-08-19 15:31:34'),(123,584,'bio','Artist\r\nCo-founder net.art and sport-art\r\n\r\nHeath Bunting was born a Buddhist in Wood Green, London, UK and is able to make himself laugh. (currently, reduced to only smile)\r\n\r\nHe is a co-founder of both net.art and sport-art movements and is banned for life from entering the USA for his anti genetic work. His self-taught and authentically independent work is direct and uncomplicated and has never been awarded a prize. \r\n\r\nHe is both Britain\'s most important practicing artist and The World\'s most famous computer artist. He aspires to be a skillful member of the public and is producing an expert system for identity mutation.\r\n\r\n','2011-08-19 15:32:00','2011-08-19 15:32:00'),(124,450,'forename','Mirko','2011-08-19 15:42:10','2011-08-19 15:42:10'),(125,450,'surname','Lorentz','2011-08-19 15:42:10','2011-08-19 15:42:10'),(126,450,'bio','Mirko Lorenz is a journalist/information architect and trainer, based in Cologne, Germany. His main job is working on innovation projects for Deutsche Welle.\r\n\r\nHe started working on web projects in 1995 and as a result can tell a few rollercoaster stories from the past. For the future he hopes to put data to good use: Knitting together Open and not-so-open data for journalism and - ultimately - storytelling.\r\n\r\nMirko is active as a speaker and trainer for data-driven journalism. Together with the European Journalism Centre (ejc.net), Mirko helped organize one of the first international conferences on data journalism in Amsterdam in 2010. \r\n\r\nAt PICNIC Mirko is going to speak about trustable data services and stories, which could help us to live and survive, in cities or in the wild. One way to get there would be to move from attention to trust as the basis for such services. His article on how to turn media companies into trusted data-hubs, co-authored by Nicolas Kayser-Bril and Gheoff McGhee, was published by OWNI and Nieman Labs. \r\n\r\nMirko has spoken about possible uses of data-driven journalism at Stanford University (Innovation Journalism Conference, 2010), in Geneva (Investigative Journalism, 2010) and at OKCon in Berlin, 2011. \r\n\r\n','2011-08-19 15:42:10','2011-08-19 15:42:10'),(127,450,'surname','Lorenz','2011-08-19 15:42:27','2011-08-19 15:42:27'),(128,629,'forename','Anna','2011-08-19 16:19:08','2011-08-19 16:19:08'),(129,629,'surname','Kivilehto','2011-08-19 16:19:08','2011-08-19 16:19:08'),(130,629,'bio','Network Manager at European Network of Living Labs','2011-08-19 16:19:08','2011-08-19 16:19:08'),(131,656,'forename','Wendy','2011-08-19 21:05:09','2011-08-19 21:05:09'),(132,656,'surname','Brawer','2011-08-19 21:05:09','2011-08-19 21:05:09'),(133,656,'bio','Founding Director at Green Map System\nEco Designer & Innovator ','2011-08-19 21:05:09','2011-08-19 21:05:09'),(134,955,'forename','Isaac','2011-08-20 06:53:22','2011-08-20 06:53:22'),(135,955,'surname','Mao','2011-08-20 06:53:22','2011-08-20 06:53:22'),(136,955,'bio','from Sharism to Social God 从分享主义到社会性上帝','2011-08-20 06:53:22','2011-08-20 06:53:22'),(137,619,'forename','Sergio','2011-08-20 12:58:10','2011-08-20 12:58:10'),(138,619,'surname','Lopez-Figueroa','2011-08-20 12:58:10','2011-08-20 12:58:10'),(139,619,'bio',' Big Bang Lab, Founder and Director\n\nA Spanish composer, cultural -social entrepreneur and consultant, Sergio is the creator of the Cultural Social Responsibility framework. In 2008 he founded Big Bang Lab, a cultural-social enterprise and creative development agency based in London working internationally from consultancy  to production and informal learning across music, film, digital media and crowdsourced audiovisual production as a  powerful tool for advocacy and collective forms of expression. \n\nHe promotes media literacy and the creation of a new language of digital silent cinema with  music to engage communities worldwide beyond language barriers. Sergio is testing new models of ethical copyright, intergenerational knowledge transfer and collaborative partnerships, promoting  intangible cultural heritage and global citizenship as a means towards socio-economic development and social inclusion. \n\nShared Voices is a B2B consultancy and production service by Big Bang Lab delivering participatory and engaging video 2.0 production content for web and social media distribution.\n\nWe help organisations to achieve their research, communication, marketing and fundraising goals by humanizing the approach to audiovisual content production, facilitating collective testimonials and finding the true stories by interacting with you from within!\n\n','2011-08-20 12:58:10','2011-08-20 12:58:10'),(140,430,'forename','Liz','2011-08-20 17:08:54','2011-08-20 17:08:54'),(141,430,'surname','Keel','2011-08-20 17:08:54','2011-08-20 17:08:54'),(142,430,'bio','I am Communications & PR Manager at PICNIC.','2011-08-20 17:08:54','2011-08-20 17:08:54'),(143,479,'forename','Nerea','2011-08-20 17:18:28','2011-08-20 17:18:28'),(144,479,'surname','Calvillo','2011-08-20 17:18:28','2011-08-20 17:18:28'),(145,479,'bio','Nerea Calvillo qualified as an architect at the Madrid School of Architecture (ETSAM 1999). That year she was awarded the Fulbright grant to follow a Master’s degree course at Columbia University. She has worked in various practices, such as NO.MAD (Madrid 1999-2001) and FOA (London 2001-2003). In 2004 she founded her own firm -  C+, winning several national and international competitions. Her work and articles have been published in architecture magazines and general media.\r\n\r\nSpecialized in new technologies as a design tool, her research projects focused on data visualization and cartographies have been developed in several international universities and new technologies centers, including her recent project \"In the Air\". Invisible cities are revealed through collaborative process and multidisciplinary teams, by sensing, describing, interacting and changing behavioral patterns of the existing urban environment. This work was awarded the Poiesis Fellowship of the New York University, and has been exhibited at the Museo de Arte Contemporáneo de Chile (Santiago de Chile), Laboral (Gijón) and in Canadian Centre of Architecture (Montreal) next October, among others.\r\n\r\nShe is Design Studio Professor at the Universidad Europea de Madrid and the Universidad de Alicante, curated the Media Facades Festival 2010 in Madrid and is currently part of the working group of El Ranchito, a co-curated art project of Matadero, Madrid.\r\n','2011-08-20 17:18:28','2011-08-20 17:18:28'),(146,484,'forename','Scott','2011-08-20 17:32:49','2011-08-20 17:32:49'),(147,484,'surname','Burnham','2011-08-20 17:32:50','2011-08-20 17:32:50'),(148,484,'bio','Hi, I’m Scott. I am a writer, creative director and strategist for design and urban initiatives, working with a number of cities, institutions and publications worldwide.\r\n\r\nI created and directed Urban Play for Droog Design and the city of Amsterdam to launch a new generation of objects and areas for the city. Working with Stefan Sagmeister, Marti Guixe, NL Architects and others a series of objects and areas were created as public catalysts for further design interventions. Recently I created the Bairro Criativo project for Porto, Portugal to open idea generation, grass-roots innovation and creative processes to wider audiences in the city and create direct design responses to they city’s needs.\r\n\r\nWhen I’m not working on creative strategies for cities, I go after big ideas and issues facing design and cities. In this realm I am currently directing the Trust Design project for Premsela, the Netherlands Institute for Design in Amsterdam. Trust Design explores the relationship between trust and design in all areas of design, from our products to our shared urban spaces. As part of Trust Design, I am the Editor for a special 4-issue publication series in collaboration with Volume Magazine, and guest lecturer at Design Academy Eindhoven.\r\n\r\nIn addition to contributing to a number of publications, I am the author of “Finding the Truth in Systems: In Praise of Design Hacking”, an exploration of how hacking and open approaches are transforming design and cities everywhere. My speaking credits include addressing the International Conference on European Policy, the World Urban Development Congress, and guest lecturing at Central Saint Martin’s School of Art and Design, London, University of Quebec, Montreal, the School of the Art Institute of Chicago, and many others.\r\n\r\nIn years past I was Creative Director for the UK’s Urbis Centre for Urban Culture from 2003-2006, where I directed numerous large-scale urban projects including Will Alsop’s SuperCity to rethink the future of post-industrial cities, ‘Urban Oasis’ with Berlin’s Office for Subversive Architecture, ‘At Home’ with Peter Saville, and “The China Show”, an overview of contemporary Chinese design and architecture.','2011-08-20 17:32:50','2011-08-20 17:32:50'),(149,484,'bio','Hi, I’m Scott. I am a writer, creative director and strategist for design and urban initiatives, working with a number of cities, institutions and publications worldwide.\r\n\r\nI created and directed Urban Play for Droog Design and the city of Amsterdam to launch a new generation of objects and areas for the city. Working with Stefan Sagmeister, Marti Guixe, NL Architects and others, a series of objects and areas were created as public catalysts for further design interventions. Recently I created the Bairro Criativo project for Porto, Portugal to bring open idea generation, grass-roots innovation and creative processes to wider audiences in the city and create direct design responses to they city’s needs.\r\n\r\nWhen I’m not working on creative strategies for cities, I go after big ideas and issues facing design and cities. In this realm I am currently directing the Trust Design project for Premsela, the Netherlands Institute for Design in Amsterdam. Trust Design explores the relationship between trust and design in all areas of design, from our products to our shared urban spaces. As part of Trust Design, I am the Editor for a special 4-issue publication series in collaboration with Volume Magazine, and guest lecturer at Design Academy Eindhoven.\r\n\r\nIn addition to contributing to a number of publications, I am the author of “Finding the Truth in Systems: In Praise of Design Hacking”, an exploration of how hacking and open approaches are transforming design and cities everywhere. My speaking credits include addressing the International Conference on European Policy, the World Urban Development Congress, and guest lecturing at Central Saint Martin’s School of Art and Design, London, University of Quebec, Montreal, the School of the Art Institute of Chicago, and many others.\r\n\r\nIn years past I was Creative Director for the UK’s Urbis Centre for Urban Culture from 2003-2006, where I directed numerous large-scale urban projects including Will Alsop’s SuperCity to rethink the future of post-industrial cities, ‘Urban Oasis’ with Berlin’s Office for Subversive Architecture, ‘At Home’ with Peter Saville, and “The China Show”, an overview of contemporary Chinese design and architecture.','2011-08-20 17:35:47','2011-08-20 17:35:47'),(150,637,'forename','Robin','2011-08-20 17:38:32','2011-08-20 17:38:32'),(151,637,'surname','Chase','2011-08-20 17:38:32','2011-08-20 17:38:32'),(152,637,'bio','Founder and CEO Buzzcar\r\n\r\nRobin Chase is founder and CEO of Buzzcar, a service that brings together car owners and drivers in a carsharing marketplace.  Buzzcar.fr empowers individuals to take control of their mobility, without looking to governments or big businesses for solutions. Robin is also founder and former CEO of Zipcar, the largest carsharing company in the world, and GoLoco, an online ridesharing community.\r\n\r\nShe is on the Board of the World Resources Institute, the National Advisory Council for Innovation & Entrepreneurship for the US Department of Commerce, and the Intelligent Transportations Systems Program Advisory Committee for the US Department of Transportation. She also served on the Massachusetts Governor’s Transportation Transition Working Group, and Boston Mayor’s Wireless Task Force. Robin lectures widely, has been frequently featured in the major media, and has received many awards in the areas of innovation, design, and environment, including Time 100 Most Influential People, Fast Company Fast 50 Innovators, and BusinessWeek Top 10 Designers. Robin graduated from Wellesley College and MIT\'s Sloan School of Management, and was a Harvard University Loeb Fellow. \r\n','2011-08-20 17:38:32','2011-08-20 17:38:32'),(153,440,'forename','Roman','2011-08-20 17:54:04','2011-08-20 17:54:04'),(154,440,'surname','Gallo','2011-08-20 17:54:04','2011-08-20 17:54:04'),(155,440,'bio','Roman Gallo has been working in the Czech and international media and multimedia sector since 1989. His first media job was with the Czech News Agency where he worked as a reporter. Since the 1990s, Roman has occupied key positions and worked as Editor in Chief at the three most important Czech dailies (Hospodářské Noviny, MF Dnes, Deník). His primary responsibilities included a complete relaunch of their content and design. Roman was involved in the conception of two extremely successful news websites: www.idnes.cz and www.aktualne.cz. Both of them are at the forefront of online news developments in the Czech Republic up to this day. \r\n\r\nHis experience with regions and hyper-localization of media is also significant. He is author of the Naše adresa multimedia hyper-local project focused on the professional creation and distribution of verified local information.  \r\n\r\nRoman has worked as consultant for many media projects in a variety of countries (Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Slovakia, etc). In 2010 he founded the Gallo Multimedia, providing consulting services in different areas of multimedia operations. ','2011-08-20 17:54:04','2011-08-20 17:54:04'),(156,538,'forename','Jorge','2011-08-20 18:03:55','2011-08-20 18:03:55'),(157,538,'surname','Camil Starr','2011-08-20 18:03:55','2011-08-20 18:03:55'),(158,538,'bio','Co-founder Enova\r\n\r\nJorge Camil Starr (born September 7, 1980) is a Mexican-American social entreprenuer and business man specializing in technology, education and the environment. He is co-founder and Coordinator of Technology & Education at Enova, a social enterprise dedicated to creating innovative public solutions through the integration of technology and educational strategies. \r\n\r\nEnova’s principal project is the design, installation and operation of cost-effective learning centers called the RIA, Red de Innovación y Aprendizaje (Learning and Education Network) which it manages for the non-profit organization, Fundación Proacceso ECO A.C. (ECO). By the end of 2011 the RIA network will include 70 centers in the State of Mexico and provide services to more than 200,000 users. For these efforts Jorge was recognized as an Endeavor Entreprenuer in 2011 with the aim of improving the educational performance of five million low-income Mexicans by 2013. The RIA project was also recognized as a finalist in Initiativa México as one of the top 40 social projects in the country out of more than 47,000 applicants and by the OECD’s Compendium of Exemplary Educational Facilities. \r\n\r\nPrior to founding Enova, Camil served as Director of PLC Networks, S.A. de C.V, an innovative BPL (Broadband Over Powerline) start-up pioneering data, voice and video transmissions via electronic networks. They completed the first VOIP call through the electrical network in the world for former Mexican President Vicente Fox. \r\n\r\nIn 2005, Jorge co-founded LT Solutions S.A. de C.V, the exclusive distributor of Ncomputing for México and Central America, a company dedicated to the commercialization of thin clients where he served as Commercial Director.  In  2008 they were awarded “Best Solution for SMEs” by Expocom, one of the largest tech expos in LATAM.\r\n\r\nCamil has also worked towards the advancement of environmental projects and initiatives in Mexico, having served as coordinator for the movement “Time for Nature 2008” on behalf of Pronatura A.C. The movement was a series of events designed with the principal objective of inspiring consciousness and motivating people to care about the environment in Mexico. Jorge also serves as a respresentative volunteer for TCP, The Climate Change Project. \r\n\r\nHe completed a double Bachelor’s degree in Economics and Business Administration at Pepperdine University, Los Angeles California (2004), and also holds diplomas in Marketing from The London Imperial College (2003); Corporate Finance, Instituto Tecnológico Autónomo de México (ITAM), Mexico (2006); Digital Governance, Tecnológico de Monterrey (ITESM), Mexico  (2007); and Senior Management in Technology and Innovation, El Instituto Panamericano de Alta Dirección de Empresa (IPADE), Mexico (2008). ','2011-08-20 18:03:55','2011-08-20 18:03:55'),(159,718,'forename','Tim','2011-08-20 18:07:06','2011-08-20 18:07:06'),(160,718,'surname','Campbell','2011-08-20 18:07:06','2011-08-20 18:07:06'),(161,718,'bio','Chairman of the Board, Urban Age Institute\r\n\r\nTim Campbell has worked for more than 35 years in urban development with experience in scores of countries and hundreds of cities in Latin America, South and East Asia, Eastern Europe, and Africa.  He retired from the World Bank in December of 2005 after more than 17 years working in various capacities in the urban sector.  He was awarded a Senior Fellowship, Comparative Domestic Policy Program, The German Marshall Fund of the United States, 2009 for research on his forthcoming book Beyond Smart Cities—How Cities Network, Learn, and Innovate (Earthscan late 2011).  Previous books include The Quiet Revolution, which explores the rise of political participation in cities with the onset of decentralization in Latin America from 1983-1995 (University of Pittsburgh Press, 2003) published in Spanish by Alfaomega, Bogota.  Leadership and Innovation (World Bank, 2004) is a collection of case studies about the innovation process observed in leading local governments in Latin America. He holds a B.A. in Political Science from U. C. Berkeley (1966), a Masters in City and Regional Planning from U.C. Berkeley (1970), and a Ph.D. in Urban Studies and Planning from M.I.T. (1980).  ','2011-08-20 18:07:06','2011-08-20 18:07:06'),(162,718,'bio','Chairman of the Board, Urban Age Institute\n\nTim Campbell has worked for more than 35 years in urban development with experience in scores of countries and hundreds of cities in Latin America, South and East Asia, Eastern Europe, and Africa. He retired from the World Bank in December of 2005 after more than 17 years working in various capacities in the urban sector. \n\nHe was awarded a Senior Fellowship, Comparative Domestic Policy Program, The German Marshall Fund of the United States 2009 for research on his forthcoming book \"Beyond Smart Cities - How Cities Network, Learn, and Innovate\" (Earthscan, late 2011). Previous books include \"The Quiet Revolution\", which explores the rise of political participation in cities with the onset of decentralization in Latin America from 1983-1995 (University of Pittsburgh Press, 2003) published in Spanish by Alfaomega, Bogota.  \"Leadership and Innovation\" (World Bank, 2004) is a collection of case studies about the innovation process observed in leading local governments in Latin America. \n\nTim holds a B.A. in Political Science from U. C. Berkeley (1966), a Masters in City and Regional Planning from U.C. Berkeley (1970), and a Ph.D. in Urban Studies and Planning from M.I.T. (1980).  ','2011-08-20 18:12:57','2011-08-20 18:12:57'),(163,459,'forename','Rob','2011-08-20 18:17:35','2011-08-20 18:17:35'),(164,459,'surname','Carlson','2011-08-20 18:17:35','2011-08-20 18:17:35'),(165,459,'bio','I’m a Principal at Biodesic, an engineering, consulting, and design firm in Seattle. At the broadest level, I am interested in the future role of biology as a human technology. I have a habit of finding new metrics to measure the progress of technologies and businesses. I am organizing a session at PICNIC \'11 on re/designing the biology of cities.\r\n\r\nI advise businesses and governments around the world on the growing impact of biological technologies on economics and security issues.  My recent speaking and consulting engagements include several Fortune 100 companies, The Economist, the United Nations, and the OECD.\r\n\r\nI have worked to develop new biological technologies in both academic and commercial environments, focusing on molecular measurement and microfluidic systems. I authored the book Biology is Technology: The Promise, Peril, and New Business of Engineering Life, published in 2010 by Harvard University Press, which is on the \"best books of 2010\" list at both The Economist and ForeignPolicy.com. I earned adoctorate in Physics from Princeton University in 1997.\r\n\r\nFind out more about me at http://www.synthesis.cc','2011-08-20 18:17:35','2011-08-20 18:17:35'),(166,498,'forename','Ricardo','2011-08-20 18:20:52','2011-08-20 18:20:52'),(167,498,'surname','Celaya','2011-08-20 18:20:52','2011-08-20 18:20:52'),(168,498,'bio','Co-founder ARTO – Art Beyond Museums / www.arto.mx\r\nCo-founder PIECE - Business & Social Development Intelligence / www.piece-bsdi.com \r\nCo-Founder JOIN / www.join.org.mx \r\n\r\nRicardo is a young Mexican entrepreneur always looking for innovative ways to create a positive impact in the society. \r\n\r\nPassionate about music, arts, business and politics, Ricardo has started different creative ventures throughout his career. In 2009, he cofounded ARTO – Art Beyond Museums, a creative agency which aim is to take back ART TO THE PEOPLE. Using the arts as a disruptive element in society, ARTO’s intention is to create large-scale change in the world.\r\n\r\nBack in 2005, eager to implement positive changes in his country, Ricardo cofounded ConsensoUno, a non-profit organization committed to fostering a culture of citizen responsibility in Mexican youth. Two years later, he also co-founded JOIN, a web-based citizen journalism platform that works as a channel of communication for young Mexicans to give their opinion or propose solutions to different challenges in the country. In 2010, JOIN received the World Youth Summit Award in the category of “Pursuit of truth” at the United Nations in New York, for using technology to help achieve the Millennium Development Goals.\r\n\r\nMore recently, Ricardo co-founded PIECE – Business and Social Development Intelligence, a Mexican consulting firm focused on Social Innovation for Governments and Enterprises.\r\n\r\nRicardo holds a Master of Business Administration from the University of Oxford (2011), and holds a Bachelor’s degree in Industrial Engineering from the Technological Institute of Monterrey Mexico (2005). During his studies at Oxford, he served as president of the Social Entrepreneurship Oxford Business Network. In 2010, he was acknowledged as one of the Top 100 entrepreneurs of the Northeast of Mexico during the Monterrey Venture Capital Conference.\r\n\r\n','2011-08-20 18:20:52','2011-08-20 18:20:52'),(169,431,'forename','Victor','2011-08-20 18:21:53','2011-08-20 18:21:53'),(170,431,'surname','van der Chijs','2011-08-20 18:21:53','2011-08-20 18:21:53'),(171,431,'bio','Managing Director & Partner, OMA\r\n\r\nVictor van der Chijs is Managing Director and Partner of OMA. He joined the firm in 2005 with a\r\nmission to make OMA the most inventive creative company in the world.\r\nUnder the direction of Van der Chijs, OMA has tripled in size, to a staff of over 280 architects,\r\ntheorists and designers in offices on three continents with projects in over 30 countries worldwide.\r\nOMA’s work encompasses architecture and design, urbanism, cultural analysis, and advisory in\r\nmedia, politics, sociology, technology, fashion, curating, publishing, product design, branding, arts\r\nconsultancy and graphic design. In 2007, Van der Chijs was recognised for his success in\r\nexpanding OMA’s business abroad with the ABN AMRO Jan Huygen van Linschoten Award for\r\nbusiness excellence.\r\nBefore joining OMA, Van der Chijs held management positions at Schiphol Group and ING. He has\r\nworked in a number of different countries, including China and the United States. Van der Chijs\r\nholds a Master’s degree in Law from the University of Amsterdam, and has followed extensive postgraduate\r\neducation at the Amsterdam School of International Relations and at INSEAD, France.\r\nVan der Chijs’ particular specialism is turning creativity into commercially viable propositions.\r\nCurrently engaged ined the broader creative culture in the Netherlands, he is amongst others a\r\nmember of the Supervisory Board of Kennisland (‘Knowledgeland’), an independent think tank that\r\naims to strengthen the Dutch cultural, intellectual and economic spheres. Early 2011, the Dutch\r\ngovernment appointed Van der Chijs to lead a ‘top team’ charged with exploring ways of stimulating\r\ninnovation and creative entrepreneurship in the Netherlands. The team’s recommendations help\r\nindigenous creative practices to mature and better benefit from opportunities abroad.','2011-08-20 18:21:53','2011-08-20 18:21:53'),(172,638,'forename','Victor','2011-08-20 18:23:30','2011-08-20 18:23:30'),(173,638,'surname','Celaya','2011-08-20 18:23:30','2011-08-20 18:23:30'),(174,638,'bio','CEO of PIECE - Business & Social Development Intelligence / www.piece-bsdi.com \r\nCo-founder ARTO – Art Beyond Museums / www.arto.mx\r\nCo-Founder JOIN / www.join.org.mx \r\n\r\nVictor loves art, music, politics and design, and even though he´s no artist, musician, politician or designer, he likes to focus his efforts and channel his energies in these areas and make things happen.  \r\n\r\nHe is one of the founders of ARTO – Art Beyond Museums, which main objective is to take back ART TO THE PEOPLE. He is also CEO of PIECE – Business and Social Development Intelligence, a Mexican consulting firm focused on Social Innovation for Governments and Enterprises\r\n\r\nVictor has always been interested in working with the civil society in order make a social change. Since his time in college, he has participated in the creation and management of two NGO´s; he co-founded ConsensoUno with the primary intention of actively creating awareness in Mexico in the areas of Politics, Education, Culture and Social Responsibility.  \r\n\r\nHe also co-founded JOIN, a website that promotes citizen journalism in Mexico in order to create alternatives to the biased mass media that exists in his country. In 2010, JOIN received the World Youth Summit Award in the category of “Pursuit of truth” at the United Nations in New York, for using technology to help achieve the Millennium Development Goals.\r\n\r\nVictor holds a masters degree in Politics & Mass Media from the University of Liverpool (UK). As part of his studies, he worked to understand the relationship between mass media and politics in modern democracies, with special reference to Britain.  After completing his masters, he worked for the United Nations Non-Governmental Liaison Service at the New York Headquarters.\r\n\r\nPrior to his studies in the United Kingdom, Victor received a bachelor’s degree in Communication Science from the Technological Institute of Monterrey (Mexico).\r\n\r\n','2011-08-20 18:23:30','2011-08-20 18:23:30'),(175,510,'forename','Beth','2011-08-20 18:24:30','2011-08-20 18:24:30'),(176,510,'surname','Coleman','2011-08-20 18:24:30','2011-08-20 18:24:30'),(177,510,'bio','Co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy\r\n\r\nDr. Beth Coleman is the primary investigator of the Pervasive Media/City as\r\nPlatform research and design lab at MIT, where she is an assistant professor of\r\ncomparative media studies. She is a Berkman Center for Internet and Society\r\nFaculty Fellow at Harvard University and a Microsoft Research New England\r\nResearch Fellow. Coleman?s work focuses on the role of a human narrative in\r\nthe context of media and data engagement, with an emphasis on locative media\r\ndesign. As an artist, she has an extended history of international exhibition\r\nincluding venues such as the Whitney Museum of American Art, New Museum of\r\nContemporary Art, and Musée d\'Art moderne Paris. She is the co-founder of\r\nSoundLab Cultural Alchemy, an internationally acclaimed multimedia performance\r\nplatform Among her awards, she has received a Rockefeller Foundation award for\r\nNew Media Arts and was an artists in residence at the Waag Society, Amsterdam.\r\nHer book Hello Avatar is published by the MIT Press (fall 2011).','2011-08-20 18:24:30','2011-08-20 18:24:30'),(178,489,'forename','Peter ','2011-08-20 18:26:11','2011-08-20 18:26:11'),(179,489,'surname','Corbett','2011-08-20 18:26:11','2011-08-20 18:26:11'),(180,489,'bio','CEO, iStrategyLab\r\n\r\nPeter Corbett is the founder and CEO of iStrategyLabs – an interactive agency that develops creative solutions to clients’ challenges and brings them to life in the digital and physical world. He’s widely known for his creative marketing approaches coupled with a deep technical background, and a focus on civic innovation through community building.\r\nPeter has won multiple industry awards and accolades:\r\n\r\n•	6 Addy’s for digital and experiential campaigns\r\n•	2 Living Labs Global Innovation awards\r\n•	1 Pioneer Institute Better Government Award\r\n•	Power 30 Under 30™ 2010\r\n•	Named Technology Advisor to DC Mayor Vince Gray’s transition team\r\n•	3x named one of the most influential Washingtonians under 40 by WashingtonLife\r\n•	Named one of 100 Tech Titans by Washingtonian Magazine in 2010 and 2011\r\n•	Named one of 25 Doers, Dreamers and Drivers by Government Technology Magazine\r\n•	Won Great Washington DC Board of Trade’s “One To Watch” award for being “A rising entrepreneur who has a bright and sustainable future in Greater Washington”\r\n•	Organizer of the 1000+ monthly DC Tech Meetup\r\n\r\nIn Government 2.0 circles, Peter is widely known for co-creating Apps for Democracy with Vivek Kundra and DC’s Office of the CTO, and the Apps for the Army program for the US Army.\r\n\r\nHis focus on creating – rather than just talking about – smarter, better, faster, and cheaper ways of doing things has inspired initiatives in more than 25 countries around the world.\r\n\r\niStrategyLabs is currently working on the Apps for the Army program for the US Army. Peter is a highly sought after speaker on the topics of creativity, entrepreneurship, marketing, social media, Government 2.0, Civic Innovation, mobile and web application development for federal, state, local government and consumer use, application development contests, innovation contests, digital divide issues and crowdsourcing.\r\n\r\nYou can follow me on Twitter here: http://twitter.com/#!/corbett3000\r\n','2011-08-20 18:26:11','2011-08-20 18:26:11'),(181,561,'forename','Matt','2011-08-20 18:27:18','2011-08-20 18:27:18'),(182,561,'surname','Cottam','2011-08-20 18:27:18','2011-08-20 18:27:18'),(183,561,'bio','Founder Tellart\r\n\r\nMatt believes in learning by doing, in using sketching as a tool for exploration, and in throwing himself in the deep-end when it comes to understanding extreme contexts. Matt finds that client projects, academic research and teaching enrich each other in powerful ways. He works actively to bridge academia and industry in his personal work as well as the work of Tellart.\r\n\r\nMatt cofounded Tellart in 2000, a design consultancy specializing in experience design and engineering–connecting all kinds of physical things to the Web. Matt has provided inspiration and strategic direction for a diverse client list including Nokia Design, Humana Inc., Otis Elevator and Google. He uses information design, photography and filmmaking to explore design challenges and to create products, services & experiences ranging from medical simulations to marketing stunts.\r\n\r\nAn internationally renowned speaker on a wide range of design and technology topics, Matt’s recent appointments have included the Google Tech Talks series, LIFT, the d.school at Stanford University, O’Reilly Emerging Technologies conference (ETech), Intel’s Future Technologies Research Summit, PICNIC, SIGCHI, IDSA/ICSID, DEFCON, Designing User Experience (DUX), and the National Disaster Medical System (HHS/NDMS) conference.\r\n\r\nMatt has been teaching studio courses at Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) since 1999 on topics including emergency medicine, physical computing and service design. He is also an Adjunct Professor at Umeå Institute of Design (UID Sweden) leading core interaction design modules and contributing to ongoing curriculum development. He is a member of the Visiting Faculty at the Copenhagen Institute for Interaction Design (CIID, Denmark). Matt has also been a visiting teacher at a number of academic institutions including the Oslo School of Architecture and Design (AHO, Norway), Technical University Delft (TU/d) and at the Central Academy of Fine Arts, Beijing (CAFA).\r\n\r\nDuring his Masters of Interaction Design from the Umeå Institute of Design (Umeå University, Sweden), Matt investigated the relationship between texture, materials, aging and interaction in the context of physical computation. Matt also has a Bachelor of Industrial Design and a Bachelor of Fine Arts degree from RISD. His thesis work, conducted in partnership with the Habitability Design Division at NASA\'s Johnson Space Center, focused on designing for the physiological and psychological strains of long duration space missions.\r\n\r\nIn his free time Matt enjoys racing sailboats, skiing, scuba diving and working as an Advanced Life Support Paramedic for the US Department of Health and Human Service\'s National Disaster Medical Team or for the National Ski Patrol. Matt lives in Amsterdam with his wife Maia and their boats and bicycles.','2011-08-20 18:27:18','2011-08-20 18:27:18'),(184,785,'bio','Robbert Dijkgraaf (1960), Distinguished University Professor of Mathematical Physics at the University of Amsterdam and President of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences. Prof Dijkgraaf studied physics and mathematics at Utrecht University. He gained his PhD cumlaude in 1989 with Nobel Prize-winner Gerard \'t Hooft. He held positions at Princeton University and Princeton\'s Institute for Advanced Study.\r\n\r\nHis current focus is on string theory, quantum gravity, and the interface between mathematics and particle physics. In 2003 his research was rewarded with the NWO Spinoza Prize, the highest scientific award in the Netherlands.\r\n\r\nMany of his activities are at the interface between science and society. He writes columns, is involved in a popular TV science programme and initiated www.proefjes.nl (science education).\r\n\r\nProf Dijkgraaf was member of the Innovation Platform, chaired by the Prime Minister. Since 2009 he is co-chair of the InterAcademy Council, a multinational organization of science academies, together with Professor Lu Yongxiang, President of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.\r\n','2011-08-20 18:29:04','2011-08-20 18:29:04'),(185,641,'forename','Eva','2011-08-21 09:00:28','2011-08-21 09:00:28'),(186,641,'surname','Gladek','2011-08-21 09:00:28','2011-08-21 09:00:28'),(187,641,'bio','Director & Industrial Ecologist, Except Integrated Sustainability\r\n\r\nEva Gladek, a native of New York City, is an industrial ecologist passionate about sustainability. Her work integrates knowledge from across the natural and social sciences to develop innovative solutions in sectors as diverse as agriculture, electronics, and information management.\r\n\r\nEva began her scientific career as a molecular biologist, and continued on to work as a science journalist and television producer before developing her expertise in industrial ecology. She is an expert in technical environmental management techniques such as Life Cycle Assessment, Material Flow Analysis, and applying green design principles. \r\n\r\nSome of her recent projects include the conceptual development of Polydome, a high-yield greenhouse that functions like a natural ecosystem and offers the potential for net-zero impact food production. She also recently worked on optimizing the material flows in a social housing neighborhood in Rotterdam, developing guidelines for the production of greener chemicals for a large chemical manufacturer, and designing a financing platform for sustainable development. \r\n\r\nEva holds a Master’s in industrial environmental management from Yale University and a Bachelor’s in molecular biology from Amherst College. Since 2009, she has served as co-Director of Except: Integrated Sustainability.','2011-08-21 09:00:28','2011-08-21 09:00:28'),(188,441,'forename','Howard','2011-08-21 09:01:27','2011-08-21 09:01:27'),(189,441,'surname','Goldkrand','2011-08-21 09:01:27','2011-08-21 09:01:27'),(190,441,'bio','co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy\r\n\r\nHoward Goldkrand\'s innovative vision for new modes of media engagement stems\r\nfrom his rich history of work across genres. Howard Goldkrand is the\r\nInnovations Director for Modernista! (modernista.com) where he has provided\r\nvisionary direction on the future of storytelling and how brands communicate\r\nacross all media opportunities. He lead the team for the massively successful\r\nDexter/Showtime alternate reality game (summer-fall 2010). He has worked with\r\nJames Truman and architecture firm Diller, Scofidio, and Renfro (Big Night in\r\nTent), ARU Liden industrial designers, Neverstop engagement marketing on Nike\r\nfor Wieden and Kennedy, James Bernard (founder of Source  magazine),  The\r\nStandard Hotel, and architect/night life impresario Serge Becker. He is an\r\nartist whose work in sound, sculpture and software has been exhibited\r\ninternationally at venues such as the Whitney Museum of American Art,\r\nPS1/Museum of Modern Art, Contemporary Art Museum Houston, Vancouver Art\r\nMuseum, Castillo di Rivoli, Italy, Bildmuseet, Umea, Sweden. Howard has held\r\nart and new media residencies with the Chinati Foundation, PS1/Museum of Modern\r\nArt, the Waag, Amsterdam, and Recollets, Paris. He is the co-founder of SoundLab\r\nCultural Alchemy, an internationally acclaimed multimedia performance platform.\r\nHoward graduated from Wesleyan University, CT, and Oxford University, UK, with\r\na BA in philosophy.\r\n','2011-08-21 09:01:27','2011-08-21 09:01:27'),(191,579,'forename','Adam','2011-08-21 09:02:55','2011-08-21 09:02:55'),(192,579,'surname','Greenfield','2011-08-21 09:02:55','2011-08-21 09:02:55'),(193,579,'bio','Founder and managing director, Urbanscale.\r\n\r\nAdam Greenfield is founder and managing director of urban systems design practice Urbanscale LLC. Author of Everyware: The dawning age of ubiquitous computing (2006), the forthcoming The City Is Here For You To Use and, with Mark Shepard, co-author of the inaugural Situated Technologies pamphlet Urban Computing and its Discontents (2007), Adam was previously Nokia\'s head of design direction for service and user interface. He lives and works in New York City with his wife, artist Nurri Kim.','2011-08-21 09:02:55','2011-08-21 09:02:55'),(194,461,'forename','Matthias ','2011-08-21 09:04:45','2011-08-21 09:04:45'),(195,461,'surname','Hollwich ','2011-08-21 09:04:45','2011-08-21 09:04:45'),(196,461,'bio','Matthias Hollwich is a registered European Architect and cofounder or HOLLWICH KUSHNER LLC (HWKN) and ARCHITIZER. HWKN is a New York based group of architects, designers, social media experts and inventors operating within the field of architecture, urbanism, branding, digital media, and development. ARCHITIZER is the world largest social media site for architecture. Before cofounding HWKN and ARCHITIZER, Matthias worked at the Office for Metropolitan Architecture (OMA) in Rotterdam, and Diller + Scofidio in New York.  He is currently a visiting professor at the University of Pennsylvania, where he created the international conference on aging and architecture: New Aging in 2010. In 2004, Matthias finished editing his book at the Bauhaus: UmBauhaus – Updating Modernism. Currently he works on New Aging, a manifest on aging and architecture to be published in the fall of 2011. His work has been featured in the New York Times, Bauwelt, Architects Magazine, Dwell, and many other publications. He has been a speaker at TED_U, TED_X Atlanta, PICNIC in Amsterdam and many more. Matthias is an optimistic and driven to move architecture forward. ','2011-08-21 09:04:45','2011-08-21 09:04:45'),(197,749,'forename','Aaron','2011-08-21 09:06:44','2011-08-21 09:06:44'),(198,749,'surname','Wolf Baum','2011-08-21 09:06:44','2011-08-21 09:06:44'),(199,749,'bio','I am an artist, researcher, and programmer using biologically and culturally-inspired algorithms to create interactive, self-organizing visual & audio art systems. \r\n\r\nI program computers to create universes in which life-like, organic forms emerge spontaneously in live, sensual collaboration with the artist; I then create instrument systems with which I perform in collaboration with artificial image and sound life forms.\r\n\r\nThe self-organizing nature of the systems make it simple and intuitive to create a vast range of fascinating content. The beauty of the results arises from the aesthetic feedback loops between the artist and the system. The patterns emerge from the human-machine interplay and are unique to all the details of that play. \r\n\r\nPlaying the same art-game twice does obtain the same result; although it may have chaotic behavior, the system includes no random elements. The systems produce interesting content immediately, but as one learns the personalities of these life forms, it becomes possible to collaborate with a new sort of Alien. This is the essence of my art form -- transforming our relationship with technology and biology from mere control to enlightened symbiosis. \r\n','2011-08-21 09:06:44','2011-08-21 09:06:44'),(200,459,'bio','I’m a Principal at Biodesic, an engineering, consulting, and design firm in Seattle. At the broadest level, I am interested in the future role of biology as a human technology. I have a habit of finding new metrics to measure the progress of technologies and businesses. I am organizing a session at PICNIC Festival 2011 on (re)designing the biology of cities.\n\nI advise businesses and governments around the world on the growing impact of biological technologies on economics and security issues.  My recent speaking and consulting engagements include several Fortune 100 companies, The Economist, the United Nations, and the OECD.\n\nI have worked to develop new biological technologies in both academic and commercial environments, focusing on molecular measurement and microfluidic systems. I authored the book \"Biology is Technology: The Promise, Peril, and New Business of Engineering Life\", published in 2010 by Harvard University Press, which is on the \"best books of 2010\" list at both The Economist and ForeignPolicy.com. I earned a doctorate in Physics from Princeton University in 1997.\n\nFind out more about me at http://www.synthesis.cc','2011-08-21 09:09:44','2011-08-21 09:09:44'),(201,471,'forename','Maarten','2011-08-21 09:16:53','2011-08-21 09:16:53'),(202,471,'surname','Hajer','2011-08-21 09:16:53','2011-08-21 09:16:53'),(203,471,'bio','Maarten Hajer is professor of Public Policy at the University of Amsterdam since 1998. The Dutch Cabinet appointed him as Director of the Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency (PBL – Planbureau voor de Leefomgeving) in 2008. He continues his professorship part time.\r\n\r\nAs director of the Environmental Assessment Agency, Hajer is responsible for the strategic assessments and policy evaluations to facilitate political deliberation and decision making, ranging from environment, nature, land use to water and transport. While primarily focused on the Dutch political decision making PBL is also active for international bodies, such as the European Commission, OECD and UNEP. For more information on the role, tasks and responsibilities of the Agency, please refer to www.pbl.nl/en/. Hajer is also member of the UNEP Resource Panel concerned with strategic issues of resource scarcity, decoupling and resource-efficiency, cf. www.unep.fr/scp/rpanel/','2011-08-21 09:16:53','2011-08-21 09:16:53'),(204,471,'bio','Since 1998, Maarten Hajer has served as professor of Public Policy at the University of Amsterdam. In 2008, the Dutch Cabinet appointed him Director of the Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency (Planbureau voor de Leefomgeving, or PBL). He continues his professorship part time.\n\nAs Director of the Environmental Assessment Agency, Maarten is responsible for strategic assessment and policy evaluation to facilitate political deliberation and decision-making, ranging from environment, natural resources and land use to waterways and transportation. While primarily focused on Dutch political decision-making, PBL is also active in international bodies, such as the European Commission, OECD and UNEP. For more information on the role, tasks and responsibilities of the Agency, please refer to www.pbl.nl/en/. \n\nMaarten is also member of the UNEP Resource Panel concerned with strategic issues of resource scarcity, decoupling and resource efficiency. \nwww.unep.fr/scp/rpanel/','2011-08-21 09:31:26','2011-08-21 09:31:26'),(205,457,'forename','Ben','2011-08-21 09:33:59','2011-08-21 09:33:59'),(206,457,'surname','Hammersley','2011-08-21 09:33:59','2011-08-21 09:33:59'),(207,457,'bio','Ben is a writer, technologist, and advisor to governments and\r\ncorporations. He is also Editor at Large of WIRED magazine. Ben’s\r\ncareer has followed parallel paths. As a journalist and writer, he has\r\ncovered first technology, and then foreign affairs, for the majority\r\nof British broadsheet newspapers. He has reported from Afghanistan,\r\nIran, Burma, Lebanon, the Philippines, and other conflict zones, made\r\ndocumentaries for radio and TV for the BBC, and helped pioneer\r\nmultimedia journalism for The Guardian and the BBC.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, as a technologist, Ben has written four books, with a fifth\r\non the way in 2012. He speaks internationally on the effects of the\r\ninternet on modern society, and especially on the topics of\r\npost-digital geopolitics, and the demographic bubble.','2011-08-21 09:33:59','2011-08-21 09:33:59'),(208,620,'bio','As researcher, developer and radical user in the converging domains of art, heritage, network technology and urbanism, Juha works as a middleperson between those who mind the past and those who invent the future. With Michiel van Iersel he founded Non-fiction, an Amsterdam based interdisciplinary innovation agency working at the intersection of the arts, heritage, network technology and urban development. Non-fiction works with a.o. the Stedelijk Museum, Stadsherstel and the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra.\r\n\r\nWith Ben Cerveny and James Burke, Juha founded VURB, a European framework for policy and design research concerning urban computational systems. The VURB foundation provides direction and resources to a portfolio of projects investigating how our cultures might come to use networked digital resources to change the way we understand, build, and inhabit cities.\r\n\r\nLastly, Juha founded Viral Radio, a vehicle for discovery and distribution of electronic music. Viral Radio sets up site-specific performances for festivals and music venues in Europe, displaying new developments in computer music exploration and hyperrhythmic dance music. It a.o. works with Exit Festival, Appelsap, North Sea Jazz Festival and Bimhuis.','2011-08-21 09:35:43','2011-08-21 09:35:43'),(209,463,'forename','Johannes','2011-08-21 09:36:36','2011-08-21 09:36:36'),(210,463,'surname','Kleske','2011-08-21 09:36:36','2011-08-21 09:36:36'),(211,463,'bio','Co-founder & Managing Director Third Wave\r\n\r\nJohannes is a trend analyst and strategy consultant with a generalist\'s attitude. Before co-founding Third Wave, he was a social media strategist at Neue Digitale / Razorfish in Frankfurt, where he advised clients like Seat, Maggi, Melitta, Nintendo, Nike and Deutsche Telekom. He holds a diploma in Media System Design. Johannes is a regular speaker at web and marketing conferences. His opinion has been featured on TV, in print and on radio. You can best geek out with him about food, coffee and networked cities.','2011-08-21 09:36:36','2011-08-21 09:36:36'),(212,814,'forename','Mike','2011-08-21 09:38:04','2011-08-21 09:38:04'),(213,814,'surname','Lee','2011-08-21 09:38:05','2011-08-21 09:38:05'),(214,814,'bio','Legendary product engineer and World\'s Toughest Programmer Mike Lee (@bmf) has worked on apps for Alaska Airlines, Delicious Monster, Tapulous, United Lemur, Apple, and Nextive, producing such hits as Delicious Library, Tap Tap Revenge, Obama \'08, and Apple\'s Mobile Store. His goal is to save Madagascar, his blog is at mur.mu.rs, and he has the world\'s largest collection of plush prosimians. In his spare time he races cars, flies airplanes, plays guitar, drinks single-malt scotch, and surfs.','2011-08-21 09:38:05','2011-08-21 09:38:05'),(215,438,'forename','Ian','2011-08-21 09:40:15','2011-08-21 09:40:15'),(216,438,'surname','Schulte','2011-08-21 09:40:15','2011-08-21 09:40:15'),(217,438,'bio','Ian Schulte is Director of Technology & Business Development at Latitude, where he guides the company’s growth strategy, oversees the development of its leading-edge technology products, and cultivates industry, academic, and developer partnerships. \r\n\r\nResponsible for developing Latitude’s young technology practice, Ian is leading an exploration of “people-centric” possibilities for the Internet of Things, with an eye toward identifying opportunities for new connected products, services, and infrastructures that could transform the ways we live, work, and play. \r\n\r\nPrior to joining Latitude, Ian consulted with educational organizations around the world, ranging from primary and secondary schools to institutions of higher education. Maintaining his interest in next-generation learning technologies, Ian is spearheading a study on how children ages 8-12 envision robots as part of their school experiences. By PICNIC time, he should have some pretty interesting results to share.”','2011-08-21 09:40:15','2011-08-21 09:40:15'),(218,438,'bio','Ian Schulte is Director of Technology & Business Development at Latitude, where he guides the company’s growth strategy, oversees the development of its leading-edge technology products, and cultivates industry, academic, and developer partnerships. \r\n\r\nResponsible for developing Latitude’s young technology practice, Ian is leading an exploration of “people-centric” possibilities for the Internet of Things, with an eye toward identifying opportunities for new connected products, services, and infrastructures that could transform the ways we live, work, and play. \r\n\r\nPrior to joining Latitude, Ian consulted for educational organizations around the world, ranging from primary and secondary schools to institutions of higher education. Maintaining his interest in next-generation learning technologies, Ian is spearheading a study on how children ages 8-12 envision robots as part of their school experiences. By PICNIC time, he\'ll have some pretty interesting results to share.','2011-08-21 09:42:12','2011-08-21 09:42:12'),(219,468,'forename','Usman ','2011-08-21 09:45:28','2011-08-21 09:45:28'),(220,468,'surname','Haque','2011-08-21 09:45:29','2011-08-21 09:45:29'),(221,468,'bio','Usman Haque, is director Haque Design + Research Ltd (www.haque.co.uk), founder of Pachube.com and CEO of Connected Environments Ltd. He has created responsive environments, interactive installations, digital interface devices and mass-participation performances around the world. His skills include the design and engineering of both physical spaces and the software and systems that bring them to life. Trained as an architect, he received the 2008 Design of the Year Award (interactive) from the Design Museum, UK, a 2009 World Technology Award (art), a Wellcome Trust Sciart Award, a grant from the Daniel Langlois Foundation for Art, Science and Technology, the Swiss Creation Prize, Belluard Bollwerk International, the Japan Media Arts Festival Excellence prize and the Asia Digital Art Award Grand Prize.','2011-08-21 09:45:29','2011-08-21 09:45:29'),(222,635,'forename','Chris','2011-08-21 09:46:34','2011-08-21 09:46:34'),(223,635,'surname','Heathcote','2011-08-21 09:46:34','2011-08-21 09:46:34'),(224,635,'bio','Chris is a London-based designer, interested in how new technology changes people’s lives: mobiles, GPS, RFID, physical computing, and recently urban screens and interactive environments; and how this changes the way people interact with each other.\r\n\r\nHe has been designing for the Internet for 13 years, and for mobile phones for 7, and is currently Creative technologist at Dentsu London. He has spoken at Etech, Futuresonic, Interesting, Reboot, EuroOSCON, ISEA and MIT Emerging Technology.','2011-08-21 09:46:34','2011-08-21 09:46:34'),(225,947,'forename','Annette','2011-08-21 09:47:35','2011-08-21 09:47:35'),(226,947,'surname','Mees','2011-08-21 09:47:35','2011-08-21 09:47:35'),(227,947,'bio','Annette Mees makes immersive theatre, interactive experiences and adventures.\r\n\r\nShe is a co-director of Coney; an award-winning arts agency of adventure and play. Coney tells stories where the audience can become the heroes, and which are always live and responsive and an adventure. Coney\'s work mixes live performance and play with digital and online storytelling. Coney is also a community of artists, makers and players, operating as a Secret Society. Which is run by a Rabbit. Of course. Coney has recently been awarded an National Portfolio status by the Arts Council UK. \r\n\r\nWithin Coney Annette focusses on developing new interactive narratives and experiential models, developing new work with writers and actors, and the integration of digital technology and theatrical live events.\r\n\r\nShe is currently developing a new international interactive theatre show Early Days (of a better nation) in collaboration with the National Theatre of Wales, a large scale commission for Kensington Palace, an interactive sound piece for the iPhone for the Edinburgh Art Festival and the development of Art Heist, a piece for art institutions in which the audience gets to rob an contemporary art concept. \r\n\r\nConey has made work for and with The National Theatre, Tate Britain, BBC, Channel 4, The Dublin Fringe Festival, 01SJ San Jose Biennial, Bain Numerique in Paris, BAC London and many more.\r\n\r\nShe was awarded the Theatre Encouragement Award by the Writers Guild of Great Britain for her collaborative work with writers, was named an artist to watch by Courvoisier\'s Future 500 and holds a Masters in Theatre Directing and studied at the KABK in The Hague and the AHK in Amsterdam. She is now based in London. \r\n','2011-08-21 09:47:35','2011-08-21 09:47:35'),(228,483,'forename','Beeker','2011-08-21 09:49:10','2011-08-21 09:49:10'),(229,483,'surname','Northam','2011-08-21 09:49:10','2011-08-21 09:49:10'),(230,483,'bio','Executive Strategic Director, Dentsu London \r\n\r\nBeeker is interested in finding better models for advertising and creative communications, encompassing new forms of media, product, services and technology. Her work prioritises the magical and the human in this, as well as the making of real, popular things.\r\n\r\nBeeker co-founded Dentsu London last year. Their work includes iPad Light Painting, Canon Sound Sculptures and Suwappu, a new concept in AR toys and media.\r\n\r\nPreviously, Beeker ran creative strategy for Toyota and Google at glue London, including the launches of Toyota’s iQ and Google’s Chrome browser.\r\n\r\nBeeker has spoken at CAT London, PSFK, Interesting, Papercamp, OFFF Barcelona, Contagious Magazine’s \' Future of Advertising’, El Sol and Edit.\r\n\r\nShe is named after the muppet who was the brunt of Dr Bunsen’s most hapless experiments.','2011-08-21 09:49:10','2011-08-21 09:49:10'),(231,761,'forename','Mark','2011-08-21 09:52:44','2011-08-21 09:52:44'),(232,761,'surname','Rolston','2011-08-21 09:52:44','2011-08-21 09:52:44'),(233,761,'bio','Chief Creative Officer, frog\r\n\r\nAs Chief Creative Officer, Mark Rolston is responsible for driving frog’s global creative vision. Working closely with the creative leadership team, Mark orchestrates teams of strategists, technologists, designers, information architects, and analysts to produce groundbreaking work for Fortune 500 clientele. \r\n\r\nAn early web pioneer, Mark co-founded frog’s digital media group in 1996, working with clients to leverage emerging technologies and setting the tone for user interface design and e-commerce platforms. He drove the creation of dell.com, marking the birth of the most profitable website on the Internet, and crafted the digital experience for i2, Microsoft, SAP, and Sun Microsystems, among others. \r\n\r\nToday, Mark focuses on the intersection of product, digital, and strategic design, pushing clients to offer truly convergent user experiences. His client roster has featured many of the world’s largest brands, including Disney, Ford, GE, HP, Microsoft, and Yahoo. Mark is an internationally recognized expert on digital media, user interface design, e-commerce, and mobile applications, and has been widely quoted in the press, including Business Week, Fast Company, Forbes, The New York Times, Technology Review, PC Magazine, and The Wall Street Journal. Mark is a member of the advisory board of the Emerging Communications (eComm) conference network.','2011-08-21 09:52:44','2011-08-21 09:52:44'),(234,428,'forename','Jeff','2011-08-21 09:54:02','2011-08-21 09:54:02'),(235,428,'surname','Hull','2011-08-21 09:54:02','2011-08-21 09:54:02'),(236,428,'bio','Jeff Hull is Creative Director at Nonchalance, a Situational Design consultancy in San Francisco. Their mission is to provoke discovery through visceral experience and pervasive play.  As creators of the Jejune Institute, an award winning immersive narrative experience, Nonchalance was successfully able to re-engineer the way  audiences interact with media, the space around them, and each other.  Utilizing automated environments, pirate radio broadcasts, guerilla masonry, and lock boxes within lock boxes, Hull’s work represents a warp zone that transports audiences between hyper realized fantasy worlds.  Previously as a street artist with an ambition to infuse more variability and play into the civic realm Hull created Oaklandish; a decade strong community arts organization with 20 consecutive “Best of the East Bay” Awards to it’s credit.  He is also the founder of inner city playground activities such as the Urban Capture the Flag League, the Lake Merritt Radio Regatta, and the Liberation Drive-In which spawned an international movement of rogue parking lot movie screenings.  Hull began his career in the realm of interactive public arts in 1979, when he was a child performer at Oakland’s Children’s Fairyland, a storybook theme park which was the unsung prototype to Disneyland. Nascent time spent in this wonderland setting inspired much of his life & work since.  He also plays bass, makes an exquisite ceviche, and hosts wild parties neck-deep in kids & dogs.','2011-08-21 09:54:02','2011-08-21 09:54:02'),(237,436,'forename','Benoit','2011-08-21 09:57:54','2011-08-21 09:57:54'),(238,436,'surname','Jacob','2011-08-21 09:57:54','2011-08-21 09:57:54'),(239,436,'bio','02.01.1970 Born in Belfort (France)\r\n\r\n1990 – 1991 Ecole de Recherche Graphique, Brussles (Belgium) Visual Communication Cursus.\r\n\r\n1991 – 1992 Renault SA, Boulogne Billancourt (France)\r\nInternship Exterior Designer\r\n\r\n1992 – 1994 Art Center College of Design, Vevey (Switzerland) Degree in Automotive Design\r\n\r\n1994 – 2000 Renault SA, Boulogne Billancourt (France)\r\nAutomotive Exterior Designer\r\n\r\n2001– 2002 Volkswagen Group, Design Center Europe, Sitges (Spain) Supervisor Designer\r\n\r\n2002 – 2004 Audi Brand Group, Concept Design Studio, Munich Team Leader Automotive Advanced Design\r\n\r\n2004 – 2009 BMW AG, Munich\r\nTeam Leader Exterior Design BMW Automobile\r\n\r\nsince September 2009 Head of BMW i Design','2011-08-21 09:57:54','2011-08-21 09:57:54'),(240,433,'forename','Martijn de','2011-08-21 09:59:38','2011-08-21 09:59:38'),(241,433,'surname','Waal','2011-08-21 09:59:38','2011-08-21 09:59:38'),(242,433,'bio','Martijn de Waal runs an independent office for research, strategy and curation that keeps an eye out for the future of journalism, the future of storytelling and the future of urban culture. He is one the founders of DeNieuweReporter.nl, a leading Dutch blog on new media and journalism. Together with Michiel de Lange he also founded TheMobileCity.nl, a research group on mobile media and urban design. He teaches at the MA in Journalism program at the Media Studies department at the University of Amsterdam, and is also part of the New Media, Urban Culture and the Public Sphere research group at the Faculty of Philosophy at the University of Groningen. In 2009 he was a visiting scholar at MIT\'s Center for Future Civic Media. See www.martijndewaal.nl for more information','2011-08-21 09:59:38','2011-08-21 09:59:38'),(243,770,'forename','Mitchell ','2011-08-21 10:00:46','2011-08-21 10:00:46'),(244,770,'surname','Joachim','2011-08-21 10:00:46','2011-08-21 10:00:46'),(245,770,'bio','Co-founder Planetary ONE and Terreform ONE\r\n\r\nMiychell Joachim is a leader in ecological design and urbanism and co-founder at Planetary ONE and Terreform ONE.  Mitchell is an Associate Professor at NYU and EGS in Switzerland.  Previously he was the Frank Gehry Chair at University of Toronto and faculty at Pratt, Columbia, Syracuse, Washington, and Parsons. \r\n\r\nHe was formerly an architect at Gehry Partners, and Pei Cobb Freed. He is a 2011 TED Senior Fellow and has been awarded fellowships with Moshe Safdie and Martin Society for Sustainability, MIT. He won the Zumtobel Group Award for Sustainability and Humanity, History Channel and Infiniti Award for City of the Future, and Time Magazine Best Invention of 2007 with MIT Smart Cities Car. His project, Fab Tree Hab, has been exhibited at MoMA and widely published. \r\n\r\nHe was chosen by Wired magazine for \"The 2008 Smart List: 15 People the Next President Should Listen To\".  Rolling Stone magazine honored Mitchell in \"The 100 People Who Are Changing America\".  In 2009 he was interviewed on the Colbert Report.  Popular Science magazine has featured his work as a visionary for \"The Future of the Environment\" in 2010. He earned a Ph.D. at Massachusetts Institute of Technology, MAUD Harvard University, M.Arch. Columbia University, and BPS SUNY at Buffalo with Honors.','2011-08-21 10:00:46','2011-08-21 10:00:46'),(246,754,'forename','Marcus','2011-08-21 10:02:38','2011-08-21 10:02:38'),(247,754,'surname','Kirsch','2011-08-21 10:02:38','2011-08-21 10:02:38'),(248,754,'bio','Marcus Kirsch is a Creative Technologist, New Business Strategist and Consultant.\r\nHe puts RFID chips on pigeons and sends people all around the globe to find actual new friends whilst recording them doing silly kung-fu moves and eat their next appointment. Having a very mixed background somewhere between design, art and technology, he worked at Dublin\'s MIT Medialab Europe, London\'s Natural History Museum and Science Museum and is the award winning founder of ResonanceDesign, a London based creative service and consultancy. He has been speaker, teacher and writer about certain things digital around europe and beyond.\r\nCurrently he is working for Leo Burnett London, adding his expertise in strategy, processes, digital creative and consulting to the internationally renowned agency and he is part of Council, an international network of specialists on all things \'Internet of Things\'.\r\nHe believes in the amalgamation of physical and digital space, platform agnosticism and he likes to dance to funky music. His location based sound application Sounddropper, that he conceived with Hamburg based designer Tom Duscher will be launching some time 2011.','2011-08-21 10:02:38','2011-08-21 10:02:38'),(249,458,'forename','Rob','2011-08-21 10:04:29','2011-08-21 10:04:29'),(250,458,'surname','van Kranenburg','2011-08-21 10:04:29','2011-08-21 10:04:29'),(251,458,'bio','Rob van Kranenburg wrote ‘The Internet of Things’ and The Internet of People in a post oil world together with Christian Nold.  He is the Founder of Council.','2011-08-21 10:04:29','2011-08-21 10:04:29'),(252,623,'forename','Frank','2011-08-21 10:05:24','2011-08-21 10:05:24'),(253,623,'surname','Kresin','2011-08-21 10:05:24','2011-08-21 10:05:24'),(254,623,'bio','Research Director at Waag Society \r\n\r\nMy interest is the use of new technologies for societal goals, eg. empowerment of (disabled) users, enhancing education and development through the use of modern technology. I establish partnerships and collaborations that combine the knowledge, experience and passion of the participants, working towards shared goals, using Design Thinking and co-creation techniques,\r\n\r\nI have experience in the conception and development of several Public Internet Services. Next to this, I\'m an experienced project and programme manager, specialised in innovative usage of new technologies. I have a background in Artificial Intelligence and knowledge of e-learning standards, applications and practices, and ample experience in film and documentary making. Currently I\'m employed as Research Director for the Dutch independent Media Lab Waag Society, based in Amsterdam.\r\n\r\nI\'ve spoken, written and lectured on Open Innovation, Design Thinking, Living Labs, CineGrid, Sustainability, Fablabs, User Empowerment and related subjects. Furthermore I\'m a regular moderator at PICNIC cross media festival workshops, as well as a host for design and innovation workshops in the Netherlands and abroad. ','2011-08-21 10:05:24','2011-08-21 10:05:24'),(255,460,'forename','Igor','2011-08-21 10:07:06','2011-08-21 10:07:06'),(256,460,'surname','Schwarzmann','2011-08-21 10:07:06','2011-08-21 10:07:06'),(257,460,'bio','Co-founder & Managing Director Third Wave\r\nCo-founder Cognitive Cities Conference\r\n\r\nIgor is a strategist and analyst with a desire to constantly explore new topics. Before founding Third Wave, he worked for Ketchum Pleon Düsseldorf where he was instrumental in helping a number of DAX30 corporations adapt and leverage social and digital media. Born in the former Soviet Union, Igor lived in Israel before moving to Germany. Moving so much made him a bit restless, which is why he travels a lot. You will always find him digging into emerging topics like the future of cities, mobile payments or Quantified Self.','2011-08-21 10:07:06','2011-08-21 10:07:06'),(258,576,'forename','Carl','2011-08-21 10:08:40','2011-08-21 10:08:40'),(259,576,'surname','Lens','2011-08-21 10:08:40','2011-08-21 10:08:40'),(260,576,'bio','Carl is co-founder of Verbeterdebuurt, a prizewinning platform on which citizens are engaged to improving their neighborhood. With mobile apps, widgets and a website people can post problems and ideas to an interactive map. 70% of Dutch councils work together to actually solve the thousands of reports on the platform.\r\n\r\n','2011-08-21 10:08:40','2011-08-21 10:08:40'),(261,818,'forename','Richard','2011-08-21 11:07:27','2011-08-21 11:07:27'),(262,818,'surname','Taylor','2011-08-21 11:07:27','2011-08-21 11:07:27'),(263,818,'bio','Richard Taylor is a Professor of Physics, Psychology and Art.  Since gaining his Physics Ph.D. in 1988 (Nottingham University, UK), he has published over 220 research papers and has worked in the USA, UK, Canada, Japan, Australia and New Zealand.  In addition, he trained as a painter at the Manchester School of Art (U.K., 1995), and has a Masters Degree in Art Theory (The University of New South Wales, Australia, 2000). Taylor has studied nature’s patterns in a diverse range of research fields, including psychology, physiology, physics, geography, architecture and art, cumulating in his D.Sc. award in 2004. Taylor uses his interests in nature’s patterns to encourage collaborations between science and art and to promote public awareness of science. As an example, he has written panels for the Tate Modern describing scientific interpretations of paintings. His work has been the subject of television documentaries, including The Art of Science (ABC, 1998) and Hunting the Hidden Dimension (PBS, 2008). His work has also been the subject of popular press articles (for example, in The New York Times and The London Times), magazine articles (for example, in Scientific American, Time, The New Yorker, New Scientist and Discover) and ten popular science books. He regularly gives lectures around the world, commissioned by organizations as diverse as the Nobel Foundation, the Royal Society and national art galleries such as the Pompidou Centre in Paris. \r\n','2011-08-21 11:07:27','2011-08-21 11:07:27'),(264,432,'forename','Michiel','2011-08-21 11:08:45','2011-08-21 11:08:45'),(265,432,'surname','de Lange','2011-08-21 11:08:45','2011-08-21 11:08:45'),(266,432,'bio','Michiel de Lange (PhD) is a part-time Lecturer in New Media Studies at Utrecht University. He is the co-founder of The Mobile City (<a href=\"http://www.themobilecity.nl\">www.themobilecity.nl</a> ), an independent research group that investigates the influence of digital media technologies on urban life, and the implications for urban design. In 2010 Michiel finished his dissertation about mobile media, urban life and identity.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.bijt.org/wordpress/about/\">www.bijt.org/wordpress/about/</a>','2011-08-21 11:08:45','2011-08-21 11:08:45'),(267,414,'forename','David','2011-08-21 11:10:24','2011-08-21 11:10:24'),(268,414,'surname','Langley','2011-08-21 11:10:24','2011-08-21 11:10:24'),(269,414,'bio','David Langley has been an applied researcher in the Telecom / Internet sector since 2011. His research focuses on the changing interactions between end users, firms and government. David worked at British Telecom in the UK and KPN Research. Since 2003, David has led contract research at TNO for several sectors, such banking and utilities. David has a PhD in marketing science, and is an active member of the European Institute for Advanced Studies in Management. He published articles in popular media, such as NRC Handelslad, Trouw and Frankwatching, and in academic journals, such as Technological Forecasting and Social Change, International Journal of Innovation Management and Journal of Product Innovation Management. ','2011-08-21 11:10:24','2011-08-21 11:10:24'),(270,504,'forename','Åshild','2011-08-21 11:15:42','2011-08-21 11:15:42'),(271,504,'surname','Stav','2011-08-21 11:15:42','2011-08-21 11:15:42'),(272,504,'bio','Åshild Stav is Designer and Event Manager. She earned a Bachelor in Product Design from the Glasgow School of Art and ENCI-Les Ateliers, Paris. She grew up in Dale i Sunnfjord where Transplant is located and worked in Ralston & Bau already before her studies. \r\n\r\nÅshild is inspired by a user-centred research and design approach, leading her to design concepts and the strategic direction of services and products. ','2011-08-21 11:15:42','2011-08-21 11:15:42'),(273,591,'forename','Oliver','2011-08-21 11:19:46','2011-08-21 11:19:46'),(274,591,'surname','Medvedik','2011-08-21 11:19:46','2011-08-21 11:19:46'),(275,591,'bio','Co-founder, Genspace; Co-founder and Principal Investigator, Bioworks Institute\r\n\r\nOliver earned his Ph.D. from Harvard Medical School in the Biomedical and Biological Sciences program.  As part of his doctoral work he has used single-celled budding yeast as a genetic system to map pathways that underlie the processes of aging in more complex organisms, such as humans.\r\n\r\nPrior to arriving in Boston in 1999 for his doctoral studies, he has lived most of his life in New York City.  He obtained his bachelor\'s degree in biology from Hunter College, City University of New York, in 1998. Since graduating in 2006 from Harvard, he has worked as a biotech consultant and taught numerous undergraduate molecular biology courses at Harvard. He is a co-founder of Genspace, a non-profit community biolab that is focused on teaching and developing synthetic biology projects. He is also the principal investigator and co-founder of the Bioworks Institute laboratory for art and biology in Brooklyn New York.','2011-08-21 11:19:46','2011-08-21 11:19:46'),(276,469,'forename','Lawrence ','2011-08-21 11:22:14','2011-08-21 11:22:14'),(277,469,'surname','Lessig','2011-08-21 11:22:14','2011-08-21 11:22:14'),(278,469,'bio','Lawrence Lessig is the director of the Edmond J. Safra Center for Ethics, and a Professor of Law at Harvard Law School. Prior to returning to Harvard, he was a professor at Stanford Law School, where he founded the school’s Center for Internet and Society, and at the University of Chicago. He clerked for Judge Richard Posner on the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals and Justice Antonin Scalia on the United States Supreme Court.\r\n\r\nFor much of his career, Professor Lessig focused his work on law and technology, especially as it affects copyright. His current work addresses “institutional corruption” relationships which are legal, even currently ethical, but which weaken public trust in an institution.','2011-08-21 11:22:14','2011-08-21 11:22:14'),(279,812,'forename','Arthur','2011-08-21 11:24:19','2011-08-21 11:24:19'),(280,812,'surname','Molella','2011-08-21 11:24:19','2011-08-21 11:24:19'),(281,812,'bio','Arthur P. Molella is Jerome and Dorothy Lemelson Director of the Smithsonian’s Lemelson Center for the Study of Invention and Innovation at the National Museum of American History. As the Center’s founding director, he has led the development of an array of interdisciplinary programs, publications, and exhibitions on the role of invention and innovation in history. He received his Ph.D. in the history of science from Cornell University and an Honorary D.Sci. from Westminster University, London. His major exhibition work includes the Smithsonian’s “Science in American Life” and the international presentation, “Nobel Voices”. He has written widely on the relations among science, technology, and culture. He is the co-author (with Robert Kargon) of Invented Edens: Techno-Cities of the Twentieth Century (MIT, 2008) and is currently working on the history of Eco-cities','2011-08-21 11:24:19','2011-08-21 11:24:19'),(282,476,'forename','Steve','2011-08-21 11:26:45','2011-08-21 11:26:45'),(283,476,'surname','Mushkin','2011-08-21 11:26:45','2011-08-21 11:26:45'),(284,476,'bio','Steve Mushkin is the founder and president of Latitude. The company explores how people and the web evolve together, as well as how our connected lives create new possibilities for progress. Latitude\'s most current work focuses on social mobility, new forms of ownership and sharing, innovative city spaces, information-rich transport, and progressive education.\r\n\r\nSteve presently leads Latitude\'s initiatives with children around the world. These include projects that engage kids in collaborative design of groundbreaking future technologies, solutions to problems of global scope, the conception of new schools designed and run by children, and the integration of robots into individual and social learning.\r\n\r\nHe is particularly interested in how knowledge, imagination and play converge as kids grow up online and, relatedly, the ways in which children seamlessly integrate natural, learned and artificial intelligence as they navigate their world.\r\n\r\nSteve lives with his two kids and wife on the coast north of Boston and off the coast north of Marseille. He holds degrees from Stanford, NYU and the University of Geneva.','2011-08-21 11:26:45','2011-08-21 11:26:45'),(285,817,'forename','Ottilie','2011-08-21 11:29:32','2011-08-21 11:29:32'),(286,817,'surname','Nieuwenhuis','2011-08-21 11:29:32','2011-08-21 11:29:32'),(287,817,'bio','Since March 2011, Ottilie Nieuwenhuis is working as a researcher at TNO Strategies for the Information Society. Before, Ottilie worked at the Dutch Ministry of Education, Culture and Science, at the media policy department. Ottilie obtained a MSc degree in Communication Sciences from the Radboud University in Nijmegen, with a specialization in Culture & Media and Ethics. Her Master thesis focused on the framing of Pim Fortuyn in the election campaign of 2002. At TNO, Ottilie is conducting research on societal impact of ICT for consumers and the media content industry. Currently she is conducting national and European research for IPTS in the domain of the Creative Industry. ','2011-08-21 11:29:32','2011-08-21 11:29:32'),(288,739,'forename','Iskander','2011-08-21 11:30:49','2011-08-21 11:30:49'),(289,739,'surname','Smit','2011-08-21 11:30:49','2011-08-21 11:30:49'),(290,739,'bio','He works as strategy director Info.nl, one of the oldest Internet agencies in the Netherlands. Based in the heart of Amsterdam the agency is specialized in the creation and realization of online services. He is educated as Industrial Design Engineer and works since 1994 in digital media as interaction designer, concept developer and strategist. \r\n\r\nEnthusiastic of the added value of interactiveness and the social power of connected media, he advices clients how to transform their products and services into online service ecosystems. Within the management team of Info.nl he is responsible for the development and sharing of the agency\'s vision.\r\n\r\nIskander presented the ideas of virtual gated communities and the impulse shaped services on different international conferences like Mobile Monday, Reboot, The Next Web, The Web and Beyond and The Annual Internet of Things Europe.','2011-08-21 11:30:49','2011-08-21 11:30:49'),(291,797,'forename','Kelly','2011-08-21 11:31:47','2011-08-21 11:31:47'),(292,797,'surname','Ogilvie','2011-08-21 11:31:47','2011-08-21 11:31:47'),(293,797,'bio','CEO & President, Blue Marble Energy\r\n\r\nKelly Ogilvie has extensive planning, strategy and outreach experience from over a decade of work in politics and finance. Before founding Blue Marble, he worked with the Seattle Chamber of Commerce to promote business interests in Washington State. His work with Vulcan Inc. (founded by Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen) included marketing and strategy planning for capital and real estate market holdings. \r\n\r\nKelly also served as a Deputy Director in former Mayor of Seattle Gregory Nickels\' Office. There he led his staff to form and manage strategic partnerships for former Mayor Greg Nickels and his well-known environmental initiatives. Kelly began his career in the former Washington State Governor’s Office of Gary Locke\'s Office where he coordinated outreach efforts for the governor. \r\n\r\nKelly currently serves on the Board of Directors at Seafair and on the External Advisory Board of Washington State University’s Center for Environmental Research, Education and Outreach. He is also honored to have served as an advisor to the President’s Council of Advisors on Science and Technology (PCAST) on issues relating to Advanced Manufacturing.','2011-08-21 11:31:47','2011-08-21 11:31:47'),(294,813,'forename','Laurence ','2011-08-21 11:32:46','2011-08-21 11:32:46'),(295,813,'surname','Parkes ','2011-08-21 11:32:46','2011-08-21 11:32:46'),(296,813,'bio','Laurence Parkes is Strategy Director at AKQA Amsterdam. For years, he successfully helped brands interrupt people’s lives. Now he hopes to  help them improve people’s lives. He was chuffed to be involved in the London Cycling Safety campaign which used a moonwalking bear to  reduce severe cycling injuries by 7% in 2008 but trusts that, in the future, the responsibility for this sort of effect won’t be restricted to public bodies. He believes all brands that target city-dwellers have an business imperative to find ways to actively improve people’s lives. He believes that technology will help them do this.','2011-08-21 11:32:46','2011-08-21 11:32:46'),(297,813,'bio','Laurence Parkes is Strategy Director at AKQA Amsterdam. For years, he successfully helped brands interrupt people’s lives. Now he hopes to  help them improve people’s lives. \r\n\r\nHe was chuffed to be involved in the London Cycling Safety campaign which used a moonwalking bear to reduce severe cycling injuries by 7% in 2008, but trusts that, in the future, the responsibility for this sort of effect won’t be restricted to public bodies. He believes all brands that target city-dwellers have an business imperative to find ways to actively improve people’s lives. He believes that technology will help them do this.','2011-08-21 11:39:08','2011-08-21 11:39:08'),(298,573,'forename','Birgitta','2011-08-21 11:41:53','2011-08-21 11:41:53'),(299,573,'surname','Ralston ','2011-08-21 11:41:53','2011-08-21 11:41:53'),(300,573,'bio','Birgitta Ralston is Creative Director of Ralston & Bau and Head of Ideal Lab’ in Transplant. She has a broad design and concept development experience from interior to profiling projects. A creative entrepreneur since 19 years old, she worked as a photographer and graduated in graphic design from RMI Berghs in Sweden, then worked as an Art Director in Paris for 10 years before co-founding Ralston & Bau designers and Transplant, design factory in Norway. ','2011-08-21 11:41:53','2011-08-21 11:41:53'),(301,804,'forename','Carlo','2011-08-21 11:43:21','2011-08-21 11:43:21'),(302,804,'surname','Ratti','2011-08-21 11:43:21','2011-08-21 11:43:21'),(303,804,'bio','An architect and engineer by training, Carlo Ratti practices in Italy and\r\nteaches at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he directs\r\nthe Senseable City Lab. He graduated from the Politecnico di Torino and\r\nthe École Nationale des Ponts et Chaussées in Paris, and later earned his\r\nMPhil and PhD at the University of Cambridge, UK. Ratti has co-authored\r\nover 200 publications and holds several patents. His work has been\r\nexhibited worldwide at venues such as the Venice Biennale, the Design\r\nMuseum Barcelona, the Science Museum in London, GAFTA in San\r\nFrancisco and The Museum of Modern Art in New York. His Digital Water\r\nPavilion at the 2008 World Expo was hailed by Time Magazine as one of\r\nthe Best Inventions of the Year.\r\n\r\nIn June 2007 the Italian Minister of Culture named Carlo Ratti as a\r\nmember of the Italian Design Council - an advisory board to the Italian\r\nGovernment that includes 25 leaders of design in Italy. He was also\r\nnamed 2009 Inaugural Innovator in Residence by the Queensland\r\nGovernment, included in Esquire Magazine’s ‘2008 Best & Brightest’ list\r\nand in Thames&Hudson’s selection of ‘60 innovators’ shaping our creative\r\nfuture. In 2010 Blueprint Magazine selected him as one of the ‘25 People\r\nWho Will Change the World of Design’ and Forbes listed him as one of\r\nthe ‘Names You Need To Know’ in 2011. He was recently a presenter at\r\nTED 2011 and is serving as a member of the World Economic Forum\r\nGlobal Agenda Council for Urban Management.\r\n\r\nFor further information on Carlo’s projects, visit <a href=\"http://www.carloratti.com\"> www.carloratti.com </a> and\r\n<a href=\"http://senseable.mit.edu\"> senseable.mit.edu </a>','2011-08-21 11:43:21','2011-08-21 11:43:21'),(304,449,'forename','Lorenzo','2011-08-21 11:44:43','2011-08-21 11:44:43'),(305,449,'surname','de Rita','2011-08-21 11:44:43','2011-08-21 11:44:43'),(306,449,'bio','Head of Research and Inventor in Residence\r\n\r\nLorenzo De Rita is 43. He was born in Rome, Italy. He is currently the Director of The Soon Institute, a collective of inventors experimenting new forms of communication. He designed the longest water pipe in the World. He opened the first travel agency for mind travelers. He convinced David Beckham to clean the streets of Manchester for one night and made the drawing of the tattoo Chris Martin of Coldplay has on his hand. He told the biggest lie ever in the history of advertising (the one of a little village in Sweden containing around 1.000 people, where supposedly 54 people bought the same car on the very same day). He founded a Football Club in Tokyo with over 3.000 players. He published an issue of Colors magazine made solely of white pages. He produced the first fashion collection that you cannot buy with money (not even for a million Euro, he says). He designed the first navigational system for the kitchen. He asked a guy called Xan to walk from Amsterdam to Majorca in Spain to deliver a shoe box to a shoe company. He has cultivated a garden of digital “forget-me-nots”. He hates all those people who call him “creative”. He loves all those people, whom like him, think in a phosphorescent way.','2011-08-21 11:44:43','2011-08-21 11:44:43'),(307,741,'forename','Saskia','2011-08-21 11:46:48','2011-08-21 11:46:48'),(308,741,'surname','Sassen','2011-08-21 11:46:48','2011-08-21 11:46:48'),(309,741,'bio','Saskia Sassen is the Robert S. Lynd Professor of Sociology and Co-Chair, The Committee on Global Thought, Columbia University (<a href=\"http://www.saskiasassen.com\"> www.saskiasassen.com </a>). Her recent books are Territory, Authority, Rights: From Medieval to Global Assemblages ( Princeton University Press 2008) and A Sociology of Globalization (W.W.Norton 2007). Forthcoming is the 4th fully updated edition of Cities in a World Economy (Sage 2011). \r\n\r\nRecent edited books are Deciphering the Global: Its Spaces, Scales and Subjects (Routledge 2007), and Digital Formations: New Architectures for Global Order (Princeton University Press 2005). The Global City came out in a new fully updated edition in 2001.For UNESCO she organized a five-year project on sustainable human settlement with a network of researchers and activists in over 30 countries; it is published as one of the volumes of the Encyclopedia of Life Support Systems (Oxford, UK: EOLSS Publishers) [<a href=\"http://www.eolss.net\"> www.eolss.net </a>]. Her books are translated into twenty-one languages. \r\n\r\nShe has received several honors and awards, most recently a doctor honoris causa from each Delft University (Netherlands), DePaul University (USA), and Universite de Poitiers (France). She serves on several editorial boards and is an advisor to several international bodies. She is a Member of the Council on Foreign Relations, a member of the National Academy of Sciences Panel on Cities, and chaired the Information Technology and International Cooperation Committee of the Social Science Research Council (USA). She has written for The Guardian, The New York Times, Le Monde, Newsweek International, among others, and contributes regularly to <a href=\"http://www.OpenDemocracy.net\">www.OpenDemocracy.net</a>  and <a href=\"http://www.HuffingtonPost.com\">www.HuffingtonPost.com</a> .\r\n','2011-08-21 11:46:48','2011-08-21 11:46:48'),(310,737,'forename','Pep','2011-08-21 11:49:26','2011-08-21 11:49:26'),(311,737,'surname','Rosenfeld','2011-08-21 11:49:27','2011-08-21 11:49:27'),(312,737,'bio','Pep Rosenfeld is one of the founders of Boom Chicago, Artistic Director and co-creator of their current production Social Media Circus. He writes tailored presentations and campaigns for companies as well as hosts events like\r\nTEDx, Picnic and Spin Awards. He is a political junkie, interested in current events in America, the Netherlands and Europe.\r\n\r\nRosenfeld with fellow comedian (Comedy Central News anchor) Greg Shapiro and director Andrew Moskos, have created hit political comedy shows like Yankee Go Home: Americans and Why You Love to Hate Us (2002), Mr.\r\nAmerica Contest: A Comedy Show about the U.S. Presidential Race (2004), Bye Bye Bush (2008), Political Party (2010) with Maurice De Hond and the brand new show 9/11 Forever, about the 10 year memorial of the attacks in\r\nNew York and Washington DC to premiere September 1, 2011.\r\n\r\nHe is co-owner of Chicago Social Club, the night club, late night bar and theater on Amsterdam’s Leidseplein with Casper Reinders (Jimmy Woo, Lion Noir) and Joris Bakker and Pieter de Kroon (creators of Bitterzoet).','2011-08-21 11:49:27','2011-08-21 11:49:27'),(313,464,'forename','Ben','2011-08-21 11:51:34','2011-08-21 11:51:34'),(314,464,'surname','Schouten','2011-08-21 11:51:34','2011-08-21 11:51:34'),(315,464,'bio','Ben Schouten graduated from the Rietveld Art Academy in 1983 and workes as a professional artist. He found himself interested in patterns and iconography, and after travelling in the Magreb and studying number theory he rediscovered his fascination for mathematics. He received his master\'s degree in mathematics, specializing in chaos theory, in August 1995.  In 1996 Ben Schouten founded Desk.nl, an Application Software Provider, providing  innovative internet related solutions to a wide range of customers. He received a PhD in visual information retrieval in 2001. Currently he is Lector Serious Game Design at Fontys Hogescholen, Eindhoven and full Professor at Eindhoven University of Technology, Faculty Industrial design, Playful Interaction. His group focuses on  ambient game design, open ended play and playful interaction.','2011-08-21 11:51:34','2011-08-21 11:51:34'),(316,464,'bio','Ben Schouten graduated from the Rietveld Art Academy in 1983 and works as a professional artist. \r\n\r\nHe found himself interested in patterns and iconography, and after travelling in the Magreb and studying number theory he rediscovered his fascination for mathematics. He received his master\'s degree in mathematics, specializing in chaos theory, in August 1995.  \r\n\r\nIn 1996, Ben founded Desk.nl, an Application Software Provider, providing  innovative internet-related solutions to a wide range of customers. He received a PhD in visual information retrieval in 2001. \r\n\r\nCurrently he is Lector Serious Game Design at Fontys Hogescholen, Eindhoven and full Professor at Eindhoven University of Technology, Faculty Industrial design, Playful Interaction. His group focuses on  ambient game design, open ended play and playful interaction.','2011-08-21 11:54:37','2011-08-21 11:54:37'),(317,798,'forename','Bonnie','2011-08-21 11:56:24','2011-08-21 11:56:24'),(318,798,'surname','Shaw','2011-08-21 11:56:25','2011-08-21 11:56:25'),(319,798,'bio','Director of Social Innovation at @iStrategyLabs\r\n\r\nBonnie is an expert at making meaningful connection between people, place, technology and play to catalyze massively collaborative civic innovations for tangible real world impact.\r\n\r\nAs the Director of Social Innovation at iStrategyLabs, Bonnie brings a delightfully playful perspective with a background in city design and participatory planning, game and adventure design and online organizing and community building. \r\n\r\nShe offers almost 10 years of international experience in design and strategy, campaign implementation and events, and project management in local grounded and global online engagement projects.\r\n\r\nBonnie is the founder of global photographic treasure hunt and community engagement game Snap-Shot-City.com – a ground breaking integrated technology event played by 1000’s of people in 100’s cities around the world. She is the Dean of the DC chapter of The Awesome Foundation, providing $1000 micro-grants every month for awesome projects, and co-creator of the 24 Hour City project - an experiment in hacking the city and temporary urbanism.\r\n\r\nShe regularly presents on civic innovation, intelligent cities, online/offline community engagement, serious gaming, and digital storytelling at conferences around the world.\r\n','2011-08-21 11:56:25','2011-08-21 11:56:25'),(320,470,'forename','Mark','2011-08-21 12:01:03','2011-08-21 12:01:03'),(321,470,'surname','Shepard','2011-08-21 12:01:03','2011-08-21 12:01:03'),(322,470,'bio','Mark Shepard is an artist, architect and researcher whose post-disciplinary practice addresses new social spaces and signifying structures of contemporary network cultures. His current research investigates the implications of mobile and pervasive media, communication and information technologies on architecture and urbanism. \r\n\r\nMark\'s recent work includes the Sentient City Survival Kit, a collection of artifacts for survival in the near-future sentient city; and the Tactical Sound Garden [TSG], an open source software platform for cultivating virtual sound gardens in urban public space, both of which have been presented at museums, festivals and arts events internationally. \r\n\r\nIn 2006, Mark organized Architecture and Situated Technologies (with Omar Khan and Trebor Scholz), a symposium bringing together researchers and practitioners from art, architecture, technology and sociology to explore the emerging role of \"situated\" technologies in the design and inhabitation of the contemporary city. In 2009, he curated Toward the Sentient City, an exhibition of commissioned projects that critically explored the evolving relationship between ubiquitous computing and the city. He is the editor of \"Sentient City: Ubiquitous Computing, Architecture and the Future of Urban Space\", published by the Architectural League of New York and MIT Press. \r\n\r\nMark is an Associate Professor of Architecture and Media Study at the University at Buffalo, State University of New York.','2011-08-21 12:01:03','2011-08-21 12:01:03'),(323,498,'bio','Co-founder ARTO: Art Beyond Museums (www.arto.mx)\nCo-founder PIECE: Business & Social Development Intelligence (www.piece-bsdi.com) \nCo-Founder JOIN (www.join.org.mx) \n\nRicardo is a young Mexican entrepreneur always looking for innovative ways to create a positive impact in the society. \n\nPassionate about music, business, politics and the arts, Ricardo has started different creative ventures throughout his career. In 2009, he cofounded ARTO – Art Beyond Museums, a creative agency which aims to take ART TO THE PEOPLE. Using the arts as a disruptive element in society, ARTO’s intention is to create large-scale change in the world.\n\nBack in 2005, eager to implement positive changes in his country, Ricardo co-founded ConsensoUno, a non-profit organization committed to fostering a culture of citizen responsibility in Mexican youth. Two years later, he also co-founded JOIN, a web-based citizen journalism platform that works as a channel of communication for young Mexicans to give their opinion or propose solutions to different challenges in the country. In 2010, JOIN received the World Youth Summit Award in the category of “Pursuit of truth” at the United Nations in New York, for using technology to help achieve the Millennium Development Goals.\n\nMore recently, Ricardo co-founded PIECE – Business and Social Development Intelligence, a Mexican consulting firm focused on Social Innovation for Governments and Enterprises.\n\nRicardo holds a Master of Business Administration from the University of Oxford (2011), and holds a Bachelor’s in Industrial Engineering from the Technological Institute of Monterrey, Mexico (2005). During his studies at Oxford, he served as president of the Social Entrepreneurship Oxford Business Network. In 2010, he was recognized as one of the Top 100 entrepreneurs of the Northeast of Mexico during the Monterrey Venture Capital Conference.','2011-08-21 12:30:20','2011-08-21 12:30:20'),(324,638,'bio','CEO, PIECE: Business & Social Development Intelligence (www.piece-bsdi.com) \nCo-founder, ARTO: Art Beyond Museums (www.arto.mx)\nCo-founder, JOIN (www.join.org.mx)\n\nVictor loves art, music, politics and design, and even though he´s no artist, musician, politician or designer, he likes to focus his efforts and channel his energies in these areas and make things happen.  \n\nHe is one of the founders of ARTO – Art Beyond Museums, which main objective is to take ART TO THE PEOPLE. He is also CEO of PIECE – Business and Social Development Intelligence, a Mexican consulting firm focused on Social Innovation for Governments and Enterprises.\n\nVictor has always been interested in working with the civil society in order make a social change. Since his time in college, he has participated in the creation and management of two NGOs: he co-founded ConsensoUno with the primary intention of actively creating awareness in Mexico in the areas of politics, education, culture and social responsibility.  \n\nHe also co-founded JOIN, a website that promotes citizen journalism in Mexico in order to create alternatives to the biased mass media that exists in his country. In 2010, JOIN received the World Youth Summit Award in the category of “Pursuit of truth” at the United Nations in New York, for using technology to help achieve the Millennium Development Goals.\n\nVictor holds a masters degree in Politics & Mass Media from the University of Liverpool (UK). As part of his studies, he worked to understand the relationship between mass media and politics in modern democracies, with special reference to Britain.  After completing his masters, he worked for the United Nations Non-Governmental Liaison Service at the New York Headquarters.\n\nPrior to his studies in the United Kingdom, Victor received a bachelor’s degree in Communication Science from the Technological Institute of Monterrey, Mexico.','2011-08-21 12:35:53','2011-08-21 12:35:53'),(325,620,'bio','Co-founder, Non-fiction\n\nAs researcher, developer and radical user in the converging domains of art, heritage, network technology and urbanism, Juha works as a middleman between those who oversee the past and those who invent the future. With Michiel van Iersel he founded Non-fiction, an Amsterdam-based interdisciplinary innovation agency working at the intersection of the arts, heritage, network technology and urban development. Non-fiction works with the Stedelijk Museum, Stadsherstel and the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra, among other organizations.\n\nWith Ben Cerveny and James Burke, Juha co-founded VURB, a European framework for policy and design research concerning urban computational systems. The VURB foundation provides direction and resources to a portfolio of projects investigating how our cultures might come to use networked digital resources to change the way we understand, build, and inhabit cities.\n\nLastly, Juha founded Viral Radio, a vehicle for discovery and distribution of electronic music. Viral Radio sets up site-specific performances for festivals and music venues in Europe, displaying new developments in computer music exploration and hyperrhythmic dance music. It works with Exit Festival, Appelsap, North Sea Jazz Festival, Bimhuis and more.','2011-08-21 12:45:00','2011-08-21 12:45:00'),(326,749,'bio','I am an artist, researcher, and programmer using biologically and culturally-inspired algorithms to create interactive, self-organizing visual and audio art systems. \n\nI program computers to create universes in which life-like, organic forms emerge spontaneously in live, sensual collaboration with the artist; I then create instrument systems with which I perform in collaboration with artificial image and sound life forms.\n\nThe self-organizing nature of the systems make it simple and intuitive to create a vast range of fascinating content. The beauty of the results arises from the aesthetic feedback loops between the artist and the system. The patterns emerge from the human-machine interplay and are unique to all the details of that play. \n\nPlaying the same art-game twice does obtain the same result; although it may have chaotic behavior, the system includes no random elements. The systems produce interesting content immediately, but as one learns the personalities of these life forms, it becomes possible to collaborate with a new sort of Alien. This is the essence of my art form -- transforming our relationship with technology and biology from mere control to enlightened symbiosis. ','2011-08-21 12:53:12','2011-08-21 12:53:12'),(327,431,'bio','Managing Director & Partner, OMA\n\nVictor van der Chijs is Managing Director and Partner of OMA. He joined the firm in 2005 with a mission to make OMA the most inventive creative company in the world.\nUnder the direction of Van der Chijs, OMA has tripled in size, to a staff of over 280 architects, theorists and designers in offices on three continents with projects in over 30 countries worldwide.\n\nOMA’s work encompasses architecture and design, urbanism, cultural analysis, and advisory in media, politics, sociology, technology, fashion, curation, publishing, product design, branding, artsbconsultancy and graphic design. In 2007, Van der Chijs was recognized for his success in\nexpanding OMA’s business abroad with the ABN AMRO Jan Huygen van Linschoten Award for business excellence.\n\nBefore joining OMA, Van der Chijs held management positions at Schiphol Group and ING. He has worked in a number of different countries, including China and the United States. Van der Chijs holds a Master’s degree in Law from the University of Amsterdam, and has followed extensive postgraduate education at the Amsterdam School of International Relations and at INSEAD, France.\n\nVan der Chijs’ particular speciality is turning creativity into commercially viable propositions. Currently engaged in the broader creative culture in the Netherlands. Amongst other responsibilities, he is a member of the Supervisory Board of Kennisland (\"Knowledgeland\"), an independent think tank that aims to strengthen the Dutch cultural, intellectual and economic spheres. Early 2011, the Dutch government appointed Van der Chijs to lead a \"top team\" charged with exploring ways of stimulating innovation and creative entrepreneurship in the Netherlands. The team’s recommendations help indigenous creative practices to mature and better benefit from opportunities abroad.','2011-08-21 13:17:00','2011-08-21 13:17:00'),(328,510,'bio','Co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy\n\nDr. Beth Coleman is the primary investigator of the Pervasive Media/City as Platform research and design lab at MIT, where she is an assistant professor of comparative media studies. She is a Berkman Center for Internet and Society Faculty Fellow at Harvard University and a Microsoft Research New England Research Fellow. \n\nColeman\'s work focuses on the role of a human narrative in\nthe context of media and data engagement, with an emphasis on locative media design. As an artist, she has an extended history of international exhibition including venues such as the Whitney Museum of American Art, New Museum of Contemporary Art, and Musée d\'Art Moderne Paris. She is the co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy, an internationally acclaimed multimedia performance platform.\n\nAmong her awards, she has received a Rockefeller Foundation award for New Media Arts and was an artist in residence at the Waag Society, Amsterdam.\n\nHer book \"Hello Avatar\" is published by the MIT Press (fall 2011).','2011-08-21 13:26:16','2011-08-21 13:26:16'),(329,510,'bio','Co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy\n\nDr. Beth Coleman is the primary investigator of the Pervasive Media/City as Platform research and design lab at MIT, where she is an assistant professor of comparative media studies. She is a Berkman Center for Internet and Society Faculty Fellow at Harvard University and a Microsoft Research New England Research Fellow. \n\nColeman\'s work focuses on the role of a human narrative in the context of media and data engagement, with an emphasis on locative media design. As an artist, she has an extended history of international exhibition including venues such as the Whitney Museum of American Art, New Museum of Contemporary Art, and Musée d\'Art Moderne Paris. She is the co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy, an internationally acclaimed multimedia performance platform.\n\nAmong her awards, she has received a Rockefeller Foundation award for New Media Arts and was an artist in residence at the Waag Society, Amsterdam.\n\nHer book \"Hello Avatar\" is published by the MIT Press (fall 2011).','2011-08-21 13:26:36','2011-08-21 13:26:36'),(330,579,'bio','Founder and managing director, Urbanscale.\n\nAdam Greenfield is founder and managing director of urban systems design practice Urbanscale LLC. He is author of \"Everyware: The dawning age of ubiquitous computing\" (2006), the forthcoming \"The City Is Here For You To Use\" and, with Mark Shepard, co-author of the inaugural Situated Technologies pamphlet \"Urban Computing and its Discontents\" (2007). \n\nAdam was previously Nokia\'s head of design direction for service and user interface. He lives and works in New York City with his wife, artist Nurri Kim.','2011-08-21 13:39:54','2011-08-21 13:39:54'),(331,489,'bio','CEO, iStrategyLab\r\n\r\nPeter Corbett is the founder and CEO of iStrategyLabs – an interactive agency that develops creative solutions to clients’ challenges and brings them to life in the digital and physical world. He’s widely known for his creative marketing approaches coupled with a deep technical background, and a focus on civic innovation through community building.\r\nPeter has won multiple industry awards and accolades:\r\n\r\n•	6 Addy’s for digital and experiential campaigns\r\n•	2 Living Labs Global Innovation awards\r\n•	1 Pioneer Institute Better Government Award\r\n•	Power 30 Under 30™ 2010\r\n•	Named Technology Advisor to DC Mayor Vince Gray’s transition team\r\n•	3x named one of the most influential Washingtonians under 40 by WashingtonLife\r\n•	Named one of 100 Tech Titans by Washingtonian Magazine in 2010 and 2011\r\n•	Named one of 25 Doers, Dreamers and Drivers by Government Technology Magazine\r\n•	Won Great Washington DC Board of Trade’s “One To Watch” award for being “A rising entrepreneur who has a bright and sustainable future in Greater Washington”\r\n•	Organizer of the 1000+ monthly DC Tech Meetup\r\n\r\nIn Government 2.0 circles, Peter is widely known for co-creating Apps for Democracy with Vivek Kundra and DC’s Office of the CTO, and the Apps for the Army program for the US Army.\r\n\r\nHis focus on creating – rather than just talking about – smarter, better, faster, and cheaper ways of doing things has inspired initiatives in more than 25 countries around the world.\r\n\r\niStrategyLabs is currently working on the Apps for the Army program for the US Army. Peter is a highly sought after speaker on the topics of creativity, entrepreneurship, marketing, social media, Government 2.0, Civic Innovation, mobile and web application development for federal, state, local government and consumer use, application development contests, innovation contests, digital divide issues and crowdsourcing.\r\n\r\nYou can follow me on Twitter here: http://twitter.com/corbett3000\r\n','2011-08-21 13:49:04','2011-08-21 13:49:04'),(332,561,'bio','Founder Tellart\r\n\r\nMatt believes in learning by doing, in using sketching as a tool for exploration, and in throwing himself in the deep-end when it comes to understanding extreme contexts. Matt finds that client projects, academic research and teaching enrich each other in powerful ways. He works actively to bridge academia and industry in his personal work as well as the work of Tellart.\r\n\r\nMatt co-founded Tellart in 2000, a design consultancy specializing in experience design and engineering–connecting all kinds of physical things to the Web. Matt has provided inspiration and strategic direction for a diverse client list including Nokia Design, Humana Inc., Otis Elevator and Google. He uses information design, photography and filmmaking to explore design challenges and to create products, services and experiences ranging from medical simulations to marketing stunts.\r\n\r\nAn internationally renowned speaker on a wide range of design and technology topics, Matt’s recent appointments have included the Google Tech Talks series, LIFT, the d.school at Stanford University, O’Reilly Emerging Technologies conference (ETech), Intel’s Future Technologies Research Summit, PICNIC, SIGCHI, IDSA/ICSID, DEFCON, Designing User Experience (DUX), and the National Disaster Medical System (HHS/NDMS) conference.\r\n\r\nMatt has been teaching studio courses at Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) since 1999 on topics including emergency medicine, physical computing and service design. He is also an Adjunct Professor at Umeå Institute of Design (UID Sweden) leading core interaction design modules and contributing to ongoing curriculum development. He is a member of the Visiting Faculty at the Copenhagen Institute for Interaction Design (CIID, Denmark). Matt has also been a visiting teacher at a number of academic institutions including the Oslo School of Architecture and Design (AHO, Norway), Technical University Delft (TU/d) and at the Central Academy of Fine Arts, Beijing (CAFA).\r\n\r\nDuring his Masters of Interaction Design from the Umeå Institute of Design (Umeå University, Sweden), Matt investigated the relationship between texture, materials, aging and interaction in the context of physical computation. Matt also has a Bachelor of Industrial Design and a Bachelor of Fine Arts degree from RISD. His thesis work, conducted in partnership with the Habitability Design Division at NASA\'s Johnson Space Center, focused on designing for the physiological and psychological strains of long duration space missions.\r\n\r\nIn his free time Matt enjoys racing sailboats, skiing, scuba diving and working as an Advanced Life Support Paramedic for the US Department of Health and Human Service\'s National Disaster Medical Team or for the National Ski Patrol. Matt lives in Amsterdam with his wife Maia and their boats and bicycles.','2011-08-21 13:58:20','2011-08-21 13:58:20'),(333,785,'bio','Robbert Dijkgraaf (1960) is a Distinguished University Professor of Mathematical Physics at the University of Amsterdam (UvA) and President of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences. \n\nProf Dijkgraaf studied physics and mathematics at Utrecht University. He gained his PhD cumlaude in 1989 with Nobel Prize-winner Gerard \'t Hooft. He held positions at Princeton University and Princeton\'s Institute for Advanced Study.\n\nHis current focus is on string theory, quantum gravity, and the interface between mathematics and particle physics. In 2003 his research was rewarded with the NWO Spinoza Prize, the highest scientific award in the Netherlands.\n\nMany of his activities are at the interface between science and society. He writes columns, is involved in a popular TV science programme and initiated www.proefjes.nl (science education).\n\nProf Dijkgraaf was member of the Innovation Platform, chaired by the Prime Minister. Since 2009 he is co-chair of the InterAcademy Council, a multinational organization of science academies, together with Professor Lu Yongxiang, President of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.','2011-08-21 14:01:14','2011-08-21 14:01:14'),(334,433,'bio','Co-founder DeNieuweReporter.nl & TheMobileCity.nl\r\n\r\nMartijn de Waal runs an independent office for research, strategy and curation that keeps an eye on the future of journalism, the future of storytelling and the future of urban culture. \r\n\r\nHe is one the founders of DeNieuweReporter.nl, a leading Dutch blog on new media and journalism. Together with Michiel de Lange he also founded TheMobileCity.nl, a research group on mobile media and urban design. \r\n\r\nHe teaches for the Journalism MA program in the Media Studies department at the University of Amsterdam, and is also part of the New Media, Urban Culture and the Public Sphere research group in the Faculty of Philosophy at the University of Groningen. In 2009 he was a visiting scholar at MIT\'s Center for Future Civic Media. \r\n\r\nSee www.martijndewaal.nl for more information.','2011-08-21 18:02:24','2011-08-21 18:02:24'),(335,641,'bio','Director & Industrial Ecologist, Except Integrated Sustainability\n\nEva Gladek, a native of New York City, is an industrial ecologist passionate about sustainability. Her work integrates knowledge from across the natural and social sciences to develop innovative solutions in sectors as diverse as agriculture, electronics and information management.\n\nEva began her scientific career as a molecular biologist, and continued on to work as a science journalist and television producer before developing her expertise in industrial ecology. She is an expert in technical environmental management techniques such as Life Cycle Assessment, Material Flow Analysis, and applying green design principles. \n\nSome of her recent projects include the conceptual development of Polydome, a high-yield greenhouse that functions like a natural ecosystem and offers the potential for net-zero impact food production. She also recently worked on optimizing the material flows in a social housing neighborhood in Rotterdam, developing guidelines for the production of greener chemicals for a large chemical manufacturer, and designing a financing platform for sustainable development. \n\nEva holds a Master’s in industrial environmental management from Yale University and a Bachelor’s in molecular biology from Amherst College. Since 2009, she has served as Co-Director of Except Integrated Sustainability.','2011-08-21 18:07:55','2011-08-21 18:07:55'),(336,441,'bio','Co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy\r\n\r\nHoward Goldkrand\'s innovative vision for new modes of media engagement stems from his rich history of work across a variety of genres. Howard Goldkrand is the Innovations Director for Modernista! (modernista.com) where he has provided visionary direction on the future of storytelling and how brands communicate across all media opportunities. He lead the team for the massively successful\r\nDexter/Showtime alternate reality game (summer-fall 2010). \r\n\r\nHe has worked with James Truman and architecture firm Diller, Scofidio, and Renfro (Big Night in Tent), ARU Liden industrial designers, Neverstop engagement marketing on Nike for Wieden and Kennedy, James Bernard (founder of Source  magazine), The Standard Hotel, and architect/nightlife impresario Serge Becker. \r\n\r\nHe is an artist whose work in sound, sculpture and software has been exhibited internationally at venues such as the Whitney Museum of American Art, PS1/Museum of Modern Art, Contemporary Art Museum Houston, Vancouver Art\r\nMuseum, Castillo di Rivoli, Italy, Bildmuseet, Umea, Sweden. \r\n\r\nHoward has held art and new media residencies with the Chinati Foundation, PS1/Museum of Modern Art, Waag Society, Amsterdam, and Recollets, Paris. He is the co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy, an internationally acclaimed multimedia performance platform.\r\n\r\nHoward graduated from Wesleyan University, CT, and Oxford University, UK, with a BA in philosophy.','2011-08-21 18:18:54','2011-08-21 18:18:54'),(337,441,'bio','Co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy\n\nHoward Goldkrand\'s innovative vision for new modes of media engagement stems from his rich history of work across a variety of genres. Howard Goldkrand is the Innovations Director for Modernista! (modernista.com) where he has provided visionary direction on the future of storytelling and how brands communicate across all media opportunities. He lead the team for the massively successful\nDexter/Showtime alternate reality game (summer-fall 2010). \n\nHe has worked with James Truman and architecture firm Diller, Scofidio, and Renfro (Big Night in Tent), ARU Liden industrial designers, Neverstop engagement marketing on Nike for Wieden and Kennedy, James Bernard (founder of Source  magazine), The Standard Hotel, and architect/nightlife impresario Serge Becker. \n\nHe is an artist whose work in sound, sculpture and software has been exhibited internationally at venues such as the Whitney Museum of American Art, PS1/Museum of Modern Art, Contemporary Art Museum Houston, Vancouver Art Museum, Castillo di Rivoli, Italy, Bildmuseet, Umea, Sweden. \n\nHoward has held art and new media residencies with the Chinati Foundation, PS1/Museum of Modern Art, Waag Society, Amsterdam, and Recollets, Paris. He is the co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy, an internationally acclaimed multimedia performance platform.\n\nHoward graduated from Wesleyan University, CT, and Oxford University, UK, with a BA in philosophy.','2011-08-21 18:20:32','2011-08-21 18:20:32'),(338,441,'bio','Co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy\n\nHoward Goldkrand\'s innovative vision for new modes of media engagement stems from his rich history of work across a variety of genres. Howard Goldkrand is the Innovations Director for Modernista! (modernista.com) where he has provided visionary direction on the future of storytelling and how brands communicate across all media opportunities. He lead the team for the massively successful Dexter/Showtime alternate reality game (summer-fall 2010). \n\nHe has worked with James Truman and architecture firm Diller, Scofidio, and Renfro (Big Night in Tent), ARU Liden industrial designers, Neverstop engagement marketing on Nike for Wieden and Kennedy, James Bernard (founder of Source  magazine), The Standard Hotel, and architect/nightlife impresario Serge Becker. \n\nHe is an artist whose work in sound, sculpture and software has been exhibited internationally at venues such as the Whitney Museum of American Art, PS1/Museum of Modern Art, Contemporary Art Museum Houston, Vancouver Art Museum, Castillo di Rivoli, Italy, Bildmuseet, Umea, Sweden. \n\nHoward has held art and new media residencies with the Chinati Foundation, PS1/Museum of Modern Art, Waag Society, Amsterdam, and Recollets, Paris. He is the co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy, an internationally acclaimed multimedia performance platform.\n\nHoward graduated from Wesleyan University, CT, and Oxford University, UK, with a BA in philosophy.','2011-08-21 18:21:02','2011-08-21 18:21:02'),(339,457,'bio','Ben is a writer, technologist, and advisor to governments and corporations. He is also Editor at Large of WIRED magazine. \n\nBen’s career has followed parallel paths. As a journalist and writer, he has covered first technology, and then foreign affairs, for the majority of British broadsheet newspapers. He has reported from Afghanistan, Iran, Burma, Lebanon, the Philippines, and other conflict zones, made documentaries for radio and TV for the BBC, and helped pioneer multimedia journalism for The Guardian and the BBC.\n\nMeanwhile, as a technologist, Ben has written four books, with a fifth on the way in 2012. He speaks internationally on the effects of the internet on modern society, and especially on the topics of post-digital geopolitics, and the demographic bubble.','2011-08-21 18:37:24','2011-08-21 18:37:24'),(340,468,'bio','Usman Haque is Director of Haque Design + Research Ltd (www.haque.co.uk), founder of Pachube.com and CEO of Connected Environments Ltd. \n\nHe has created responsive environments, interactive installations, digital interface devices and mass-participation performances around the world. His skills include the design and engineering of both physical spaces and the software and systems that bring them to life. \n\nTrained as an architect, he received the 2008 Design of the Year Award (interactive) from the Design Museum, UK, a 2009 World Technology Award (art), a Wellcome Trust Sciart Award, a grant from the Daniel Langlois Foundation for Art, Science and Technology, the Swiss Creation Prize, Belluard Bollwerk International, the Japan Media Arts Festival Excellence prize and the Asia Digital Art Award Grand Prize.','2011-08-21 18:41:36','2011-08-21 18:41:36'),(341,818,'bio','Richard Taylor is a Professor of Physics, Psychology and Art.  Since gaining his Physics Ph.D. in 1988 (Nottingham University, UK), he has published over 220 research papers and has worked in the USA, UK, Canada, Japan, Australia and New Zealand.  In addition, he trained as a painter at the Manchester School of Art (U.K., 1995), and has a Masters Degree in Art Theory (The University of New South Wales, Australia, 2000). Richard has studied nature’s patterns in a diverse range of research fields, including psychology, physiology, physics, geography, architecture and art, cumulating in his D.Sc. award in 2004. \n\nRichard uses his interests in nature’s patterns to encourage collaborations between science and art and to promote public awareness of science. As an example, he has written panels for the Tate Modern describing scientific interpretations of paintings. His work has been the subject of television documentaries, including The Art of Science (ABC, 1998) and Hunting the Hidden Dimension (PBS, 2008). His work has also been the subject of popular press articles (for example, in The New York Times and The London Times), magazine articles (for example, in Scientific American, Time, The New Yorker, New Scientist and Discover) and ten popular science books. \n\nHe regularly gives lectures around the world, commissioned by organizations as diverse as the Nobel Foundation, the Royal Society and national art galleries such as the Pompidou Centre in Paris. ','2011-08-21 19:39:20','2011-08-21 19:39:20'),(342,818,'bio','Richard Taylor is a Professor of Physics, Psychology and Art.  Since gaining his Physics Ph.D. in 1988 (Nottingham University, UK), he has published over 220 research papers and has worked in the USA, UK, Canada, Japan, Australia and New Zealand.  In addition, he trained as a painter at the Manchester School of Art (U.K., 1995), and has a Masters Degree in Art Theory (The University of New South Wales, Australia, 2000). Richard has studied nature’s patterns in a diverse range of research fields, including psychology, physiology, physics, geography, architecture and art, cumulating in his D.Sc. award in 2004. \n\nRichard uses his interests in nature’s patterns to encourage collaborations between science and art and to promote public awareness of science. As an example, he has written panels for the Tate Modern describing scientific interpretations of paintings. His work has been the subject of television documentaries, including The Art of Science (ABC, 1998) and Hunting the Hidden Dimension (PBS, 2008). His work has also been the subject of popular press articles (for example, in The New York Times and The London Times), magazine articles (for example, in Scientific American, Time, The New Yorker, New Scientist and Discover) and ten popular science books. \n\nHe regularly gives lectures around the world, commissioned by organizations as diverse as the Nobel Foundation, the Royal Society and national art galleries such as the Pompidou Centre in Paris. ','2011-08-21 19:39:20','2011-08-21 19:39:20'),(343,635,'bio','Creative Technologist at Dentsu London\n\nChris is a London-based designer, interested in how new technology changes people’s lives: mobiles, GPS, RFID, physical computing, and recently urban screens and interactive environments; and how this changes the way people interact with each other.\n\nHe has been designing for the Internet for 13 years, and for mobile phones for 7, and is currently Creative Technologist at Dentsu London. He has spoken at Etech, Futuresonic, Interesting, Reboot, EuroOSCON, ISEA and MIT Emerging Technology.','2011-08-21 19:42:43','2011-08-21 19:42:43'),(344,483,'bio','Executive Strategic Director, Dentsu London \n\nBeeker is interested in finding better models for advertising and creative communications, encompassing new forms of media, product, services and technology. Her work prioritizes the magical and the human in this, as well as the making of real, popular things.\n\nBeeker co-founded Dentsu London last year. Their work includes iPad Light Painting, Canon Sound Sculptures and Suwappu, a new concept in AR toys and media.\n\nPreviously, Beeker ran creative strategy for Toyota and Google at glue London, including the launches of Toyota’s iQ and Google’s Chrome browser.\n\nBeeker has spoken at CAT London, PSFK, Interesting, Papercamp, OFFF Barcelona, Contagious Magazine’s \' Future of Advertising’, El Sol and Edit.\n\nShe is named after the muppet who was the brunt of Dr. Bunsen’s most hapless experiments.','2011-08-21 19:48:40','2011-08-21 19:48:40'),(345,461,'bio','Matthias Hollwich is a registered European Architect and co-founder or HOLLWICH KUSHNER LLC (HWKN) and ARCHITIZER. \n\nHWKN is a New York-based group of architects, designers, social media experts and inventors operating within the field of architecture, urbanism, branding, digital media, and development. ARCHITIZER is the world\'s largest social media site for architecture. \n\nBefore cofounding HWKN and ARCHITIZER, Matthias worked at the Office for Metropolitan Architecture (OMA) in Rotterdam, and Diller + Scofidio in New York.  He is currently a visiting professor at the University of Pennsylvania, where he created the international conference on aging and architecture: New Aging in 2010. \n\nIn 2004, Matthias finished editing his book at the Bauhaus: UmBauhaus – Updating Modernism. Currently he works on New Aging, a manifest on aging and architecture to be published in the fall of 2011. His work has been featured in the New York Times, Bauwelt, Architects Magazine, Dwell, and many other publications. He has been a speaker at TED_U, TED_X Atlanta, PICNIC in Amsterdam and many more. Matthias is an optimistic and driven to move architecture forward. ','2011-08-21 19:53:25','2011-08-21 19:53:25'),(346,428,'bio','Jeff Hull is Creative Director at Nonchalance, a Situational Design consultancy in San Francisco. Their mission is to provoke discovery through visceral experience and pervasive play.  As creators of the Jejune Institute, an award-winning immersive narrative experience, Nonchalance was successfully able to re-engineer the way  audiences interact with media, the space around them, and each other.  Utilizing automated environments, pirate radio broadcasts, guerilla masonry, and lock boxes within lock boxes, Hull’s work represents a warp zone that transports audiences between hyper realized fantasy worlds.  \n\nPreviously as a street artist with an ambition to infuse more variability and play into the civic realm, Jeff created Oaklandish; a decade-strong community arts organization with 20 consecutive “Best of the East Bay” Awards to it’s credit.  He is also the founder of inner city playground activities such as the Urban Capture the Flag League, the Lake Merritt Radio Regatta, and the Liberation Drive-In which spawned an international movement of rogue parking lot movie screenings.  \n\nJeff began his career in the realm of interactive public arts in 1979, when he was a child performer at Oakland’s Children’s Fairyland, a storybook theme park which was the unsung prototype to Disneyland. Nascent time spent in this wonderland setting inspired much of his life & work since.  He also plays bass, makes an exquisite ceviche, and hosts wild parties neck-deep in kids & dogs.','2011-08-21 20:02:50','2011-08-21 20:02:50'),(347,739,'bio','Iskander Smit works as strategy director at Info.nl, one of the oldest Internet agencies in the Netherlands. Based in the heart of Amsterdam, the agency is specialized in the creation and realization of online services. \n\nIskander was educated as an Industrial Design Engineer and since 1994 has worked in digital media as an interaction designer, concept developer and strategist. \n\nEnthusiastic about the added value of interactivity and the social power of connected media, he advises clients on how to transform their products and services into online service ecosystems. Within the management team of Info.nl he is responsible for the development and sharing of the agency\'s vision.\n\nIskander presented the ideas of virtual gated communities and the impulse shaped services on different international conferences like Mobile Monday, Reboot, The Next Web, The Web and Beyond and The Annual Internet of Things Europe.','2011-08-21 20:14:25','2011-08-21 20:14:25'),(348,739,'bio','Iskander Smit works as strategy director at Info.nl, one of the oldest Internet agencies in the Netherlands. Based in the heart of Amsterdam, the agency is specialized in the creation and realization of online services. \n\nIskander was educated as an Industrial Design Engineer and since 1994 has worked in digital media as an interaction designer, concept developer and strategist. \n\nEnthusiastic about the added value of interactivity and the social power of connected media, he advises clients on how to transform their products and services into online service ecosystems. Within the management team of Info.nl he is responsible for the development and sharing of the agency\'s vision.\n\nIskander has presented the ideas of virtual gated communities and the impulse shaped services at international conferences like Mobile Monday, Reboot, The Next Web, The Web and Beyond and The Annual Internet of Things Europe.','2011-08-21 20:15:14','2011-08-21 20:15:14'),(349,770,'bio','Co-founder Planetary ONE and Terreform ONE\n\nMitchell Joachim is a leader in ecological design and urbanism and co-founder of Planetary ONE and Terreform ONE. Mitchell is an Associate Professor at NYU and EGS in Switzerland. Previously, he was the Frank Gehry Chair at University of Toronto and faculty at Pratt, Columbia, Syracuse, Washington, and Parsons. \n\nMitchell was formerly an architect at Gehry Partners, and Pei Cobb Freed. He is a 2011 TED Senior Fellow and has been awarded fellowships with Moshe Safdie and Martin Society for Sustainability, MIT. He won the Zumtobel Group Award for Sustainability and Humanity, History Channel and Infiniti Award for City of the Future, and Time Magazine Best Invention of 2007 with MIT Smart Cities Car. His project, Fab Tree Hab, has been exhibited at MoMA and widely published. \n\nHe was chosen by Wired magazine for \"The 2008 Smart List: 15 People the Next President Should Listen To\".  Rolling Stone magazine honored Mitchell in \"The 100 People Who Are Changing America\". In 2009 he was interviewed on the Colbert Report. Popular Science magazine has featured his work as a visionary for \"The Future of the Environment\" in 2010. He earned a Ph.D. at Massachusetts Institute of Technology, MAUD Harvard University, M.Arch. Columbia University, and BPS SUNY at Buffalo with Honors.','2011-08-21 20:24:24','2011-08-21 20:24:24'),(350,798,'bio','Director of Social Innovation at @iStrategyLabs\n\nBonnie is an expert at making meaningful connections between people, place, technology and play to catalyze massively collaborative civic innovations for tangible real world impact.\n\nAs the Director of Social Innovation at iStrategyLabs, Bonnie brings a delightfully playful perspective with a background in city design and participatory planning, game and adventure design and online organizing and community building. \n\nShe offers almost 10 years of international experience in design and strategy, campaign implementation and events, and project management in local grounded and global online engagement projects.\n\nBonnie is the founder of global photographic treasure hunt and community engagement game Snap-Shot-City.com – a ground breaking integrated technology event played by 1000’s of people in 100’s cities around the world. She is the Dean of the DC chapter of The Awesome Foundation, providing $1000 micro-grants every month for awesome projects, and co-creator of the 24 Hour City project - an experiment in hacking the city and temporary urbanism.\n\nShe regularly presents on civic innovation, intelligent cities, online/offline community engagement, serious gaming, and digital storytelling at conferences around the world.','2011-08-21 20:27:44','2011-08-21 20:27:44'),(351,798,'bio','Director of Social Innovation at iStrategyLabs\n\nBonnie is an expert at making meaningful connections between people, place, technology and play to catalyze massively collaborative civic innovations for tangible real world impact.\n\nAs the Director of Social Innovation at iStrategyLabs, Bonnie brings a delightfully playful perspective with a background in city design and participatory planning, game and adventure design and online organizing and community building. \n\nShe offers almost 10 years of international experience in design and strategy, campaign implementation and events, and project management in local grounded and global online engagement projects.\n\nBonnie is the founder of global photographic treasure hunt and community engagement game Snap-Shot-City.com – a ground breaking integrated technology event played by 1000’s of people in 100’s cities around the world. She is the Dean of the DC chapter of The Awesome Foundation, providing $1000 micro-grants every month for awesome projects, and co-creator of the 24 Hour City project - an experiment in hacking the city and temporary urbanism.\n\nShe regularly presents on civic innovation, intelligent cities, online/offline community engagement, serious gaming, and digital storytelling at conferences around the world.','2011-08-21 20:29:09','2011-08-21 20:29:09'),(352,460,'bio','Co-founder & Managing Director, Third Wave\nCo-founder, Cognitive Cities Conference\n\nIgor is a strategist and analyst with a desire to constantly explore new topics. Before founding Third Wave, he worked for Ketchum Pleon Düsseldorf where he was instrumental in helping a number of DAX30 corporations adapt and leverage social and digital media. \n\nBorn in the former Soviet Union, Igor lived in Israel before moving to Germany. Moving so much made him a bit restless, which is why he travels a lot. You will always find him digging into emerging topics like the future of cities, mobile payments or Quantified Self.','2011-08-21 20:32:04','2011-08-21 20:32:04'),(353,754,'bio','Marcus Kirsch is a Creative Technologist, New Business Strategist and Consultant.\n\nHe puts RFID chips on pigeons and sends people all around the globe to find actual new friends whilst recording them doing silly kung-fu moves and eating their next appointment. \n\nHaving a very mixed background somewhere between design, art and technology, he worked at Dublin\'s MIT Medialab Europe, London\'s Natural History Museum and Science Museum and is the award-winning founder of ResonanceDesign, a London based creative service and consultancy. He has been speaker, teacher and writer about certain things digital around Europe and beyond.\n\nCurrently he is working for Leo Burnett London, contributing his expertise in strategy, processes, digital creative and consulting to the internationally renowned agency. He is also part of Council, an international network of specialists on all things \"Internet of Things\".\n\nHe believes in the amalgamation of physical and digital space, platform agnosticism and he likes to dance to funky music. His location-based sound application Sounddropper, that he conceived with Hamburg based designer Tom Duscher will be launching some time 2011.','2011-08-21 20:36:57','2011-08-21 20:36:57'),(354,463,'bio','Co-founder & Managing Director, Third Wave\n\nJohannes is a trend analyst and strategy consultant with a generalist\'s attitude. Before co-founding Third Wave, he was a social media strategist at Neue Digitale / Razorfish in Frankfurt, where he advised clients like Seat, Maggi, Melitta, Nintendo, Nike and Deutsche Telekom. He holds a diploma in Media System Design. Johannes is a regular speaker at web and marketing conferences. His opinion has been featured on TV, in print and on radio. You can best geek out with him about food, coffee and networked cities.','2011-08-22 06:49:17','2011-08-22 06:49:17'),(355,458,'bio','Rob van Kranenburg wrote \"The Internet of Things\" and \"The Internet of People in a Post Oil World\" together with Christian Nold.  He is the founder of Council.','2011-08-22 06:52:28','2011-08-22 06:52:28'),(356,623,'bio','Research Director at Waag Society \n\nI\'m interested in the use of new technologies for societal goals, like the empowerment of (disabled) users, and enhancing education and development through the use of modern technology. I establish partnerships and collaborations that combine the knowledge, experience and passion of the participants, working towards shared goals, using Design Thinking and co-creation techniques.\n\nI have experience in the conception and development of several public internet services. In addition, I\'m an experienced project and programme manager, specialized in innovative usage of new technologies. I have a background in artificial intelligence and knowledge of e-learning standards, applications and practices, and ample experience in film and documentary making. Currently I\'m employed as Research Director for the Dutch independent Media Lab Waag Society, based in Amsterdam.\n\nI\'ve spoken, written and lectured on open innovation, Design Thinking, Living Labs, CineGrid, sustainability, Fablabs, user empowerment and related subjects. Furthermore I\'m a regular moderator at PICNIC Festival workshops, as well as a host for design and innovation workshops in the Netherlands and abroad. ','2011-08-22 06:56:56','2011-08-22 06:56:56'),(357,432,'bio','Michiel de Lange (PhD) is a part-time Lecturer in New Media Studies at Utrecht University. He is the co-founder of The Mobile City (www.themobilecity.nl), an independent research group that investigates the influence of digital media technologies on urban life, and the implications for urban design. In 2010 Michiel finished his dissertation about mobile media, urban life and identity.\n\nFind out more at www.bijt.org/wordpress/about/','2011-08-22 07:09:17','2011-08-22 07:09:17'),(358,414,'bio','David Langley has been an applied researcher in the telecom / internet sector since 2011. His research focuses on the changing interactions between end users, firms and government. David worked at British Telecom in the UK and KPN Research. Since 2003, David has led contract research at TNO for several sectors, such banking and utilities. David has a PhD in marketing science, and is an active member of the European Institute for Advanced Studies in Management. \n\nDavid has published articles in popular media such as NRC Handelslad, Trouw and Frankwatching, and in academic journals, such as Technological Forecasting and Social Change, International Journal of Innovation Management and Journal of Product Innovation Management. ','2011-08-22 07:12:18','2011-08-22 07:12:18'),(359,576,'bio','Carl is co-founder of Verbeterdebuurt, a prizewinning platform for engaging citizens to improve their neighborhood. With mobile apps, widgets and a website people can post problems and ideas on an interactive map. 70% of Dutch city councils work together to actually solve the thousands of reported issues on the platform.\n\n','2011-08-22 07:15:39','2011-08-22 07:15:39'),(360,450,'bio','Mirko Lorenz is a journalist, information architect and trainer, based in Cologne, Germany. His main job is working on innovation projects for Deutsche Welle.\n\nHe started working on web projects in 1995 and as a result can tell a few rollercoaster stories from the past. For the future he hopes to put data to good use: Knitting together Open and not-so-open data for journalism and - ultimately - storytelling.\n\nMirko is active as a speaker and trainer for data-driven journalism. Together with the European Journalism Centre (ejc.net), Mirko helped organize one of the first international conferences on data journalism in Amsterdam in 2010. \n\nAt PICNIC Mirko is going to speak about trustable data services and stories, which could help us to live and survive, in cities or in the wild. One way to get there would be to move from attention to trust as the basis for such services. His article on how to turn media companies into trusted data-hubs, co-authored by Nicolas Kayser-Bril and Gheoff McGhee, was published by OWNI and Nieman Labs. \n\nMirko has spoken about possible uses of data-driven journalism at Stanford University (Innovation Journalism Conference, 2010), in Geneva (Investigative Journalism, 2010) and at OKCon in Berlin, 2011. ','2011-08-22 07:27:15','2011-08-22 07:27:15'),(361,947,'bio','Annette Mees makes immersive theater, interactive experiences and adventures.\n\nShe is a co-director of Coney, an award-winning arts agency of adventure and play. Coney tells stories where the audience can become the heroes, and which are always live and responsive and an adventure. Coney\'s work mixes live performance and play with digital and online storytelling. Coney is also a community of artists, makers and players, operating as a Secret Society. Which is run by a Rabbit. Of course. Coney has recently been awarded an National Portfolio status by the Arts Council UK. \n\nWithin Coney, Annette focuses on developing new interactive narratives and experiential models, developing new work with writers and actors, and the integration of digital technology and theatrical live events.\n\nShe is currently developing a new international interactive theater show Early Days (of a better nation) in collaboration with the National Theatre of Wales, a large scale commission for Kensington Palace, an interactive sound piece for the iPhone for the Edinburgh Art Festival and creating Art Heist, a piece for art institutions in which the audience gets to rob an contemporary art concept. \n\nConey has made work for and with The National Theatre, Tate Britain, BBC, Channel 4, The Dublin Fringe Festival, 01SJ San Jose Biennial, Bain Numerique in Paris, BAC London and many more.\n\nShe was awarded the Theatre Encouragement Award by the Writers Guild of Great Britain for her collaborative work with writers, was named an artist to watch by Courvoisier\'s Future 500 and holds a Masters in Theatre Directing and studied at the KABK in The Hague and the AHK in Amsterdam. She is now based in London. ','2011-08-22 07:32:43','2011-08-22 07:32:43'),(362,444,'bio','Tracy Metz, a native of California, is a journalist and author based in the Netherlands. She is a staff reporter at the Arts desk of the quality national newspaper NRC Handelsblad and an international correspondent for the New York-based magazine Architectural Record. \n\nAt the Harvard Graduate School of Design Metz was a Loeb Fellow ’07 and is currently a visiting fellow. She is the author of a number of books, including \"FUN! Leisure and Landscape\", about the impact of leisure on the way we use and perceive our surroundings, and a collection of columns and esaays \"On the Ground: Observations from Harvard\". She is currently working on a book on water in the Netherlands and an exhibition at the Kunsthal in Rotterdam, \"Sweet&Salt: Water and the Dutch\", to open in February 2012.','2011-08-22 07:34:11','2011-08-22 07:34:11'),(363,812,'bio','Arthur P. Molella is Jerome and Dorothy Lemelson Director of the Smithsonian’s Lemelson Center for the Study of Invention and Innovation at the National Museum of American History. \n\nAs the Center’s founding director, he has led the development of an array of interdisciplinary programs, publications, and exhibitions on the role of invention and innovation in history. He received his Ph.D. in the history of science from Cornell University and an Honorary D.Sc. from Westminster University, London. His major exhibition work includes the Smithsonian’s “Science in American Life” and the international presentation, “Nobel Voices”. He has written widely on the relationships between science, technology, and culture. He is the co-author (with Robert Kargon) of Invented Edens: Techno-Cities of the Twentieth Century (MIT, 2008) and is currently working on the history of eco-cities.','2011-08-22 07:38:18','2011-08-22 07:38:18'),(364,817,'bio','Since March 2011, Ottilie Nieuwenhuis has been working as a researcher at TNO Strategies for the Information Society. \n\nPreviously, Ottilie worked at the Dutch Ministry of Education, Culture and Science, at the media policy department. Ottilie obtained a MSc degree in Communication Sciences from the Radboud University in Nijmegen, with a specialization in Culture & Media and Ethics. Her Master thesis focused on the framing of Pim Fortuyn in the election campaign of 2002. \n\nAt TNO, Ottilie is conducting research on societal impact of ICT for consumers and the media content industry. Currently she is conducting national and European research for IPTS in the domain of the Creative Industry. ','2011-08-22 07:40:39','2011-08-22 07:40:39'),(365,573,'bio','Birgitta Ralston is Creative Director of Ralston & Bau and Head of Ideal Lab at Transplant. \n\nShe has a broad design and concept development experience from interior to profiling projects. A creative entrepreneur since 19 years old, she worked as a photographer and graduated in graphic design from RMI Berghs in Sweden, then worked as an Art Director in Paris for 10 years before co-founding Ralston & Bau designers and Transplant, a design factory in Norway. ','2011-08-22 07:44:51','2011-08-22 07:44:51'),(366,804,'bio','An architect and engineer by training, Carlo Ratti practices in Italy and teaches at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he directs the Senseable City Lab. \n\nHe graduated from the Politecnico di Torino and the École Nationale des Ponts et Chaussées in Paris, and later earned his MPhil and PhD at the University of Cambridge, UK. \n\nCarlo has co-authored over 200 publications and holds several patents. His work has been exhibited worldwide at venues such as the Venice Biennale, the Design Museum Barcelona, the Science Museum in London, GAFTA in San\nFrancisco and The Museum of Modern Art in New York. His Digital Water Pavilion at the 2008 World Expo was hailed by Time Magazine as one of the Best Inventions of the Year.\n\nIn June 2007, the Italian Minister of Culture named Carlo a member of the Italian Design Council - an advisory board to the Italian Government that includes 25 leaders of design in Italy. He was also named 2009 Inaugural Innovator in Residence by the Queensland Government. Carlo was included in Esquire Magazine’s \"2008 Best & Brightest\" list\nand in Thames&Hudson’s selection of \"60 innovators\" shaping our creative future. In 2010 Blueprint Magazine selected him as one of the \"25 People Who Will Change the World of Design\" and Forbes listed him as one of the \"Names You Need To Know\" in 2011. \n\nHe was recently a presenter at TED 2011 and is serving as a member of the World Economic Forum Global Agenda Council for Urban Management.\n\nFor further information on Carlo’s projects, visit http://www.carloratti.com and http://senseable.mit.edu','2011-08-22 07:51:31','2011-08-22 07:51:31'),(367,449,'bio','Head of Research and Inventor in Residence\r\n\r\nLorenzo De Rita is 43. He was born in Rome, Italy. He is currently the Director of The Soon Institute, a collective of inventors experimenting with new forms of communication. \r\n\r\nLorenzo designed the longest water pipe in the world. He opened the first travel agency for mind travelers. He convinced David Beckham to clean the streets of Manchester for one night and made the drawing of the tattoo Chris Martin of Coldplay has on his hand. He told the biggest lie ever in the history of advertising (the one of a little village in Sweden containing around 1.000 people, where supposedly 54 people bought the same car on the very same day). He founded a Football Club in Tokyo with over 3.000 players. He published an issue of Colors magazine made solely of white pages. He produced the first fashion collection that you cannot buy with money (not even for a million Euros, he says). He designed the first navigational system for the kitchen. He asked a guy called Xan to walk from Amsterdam to Majorca in Spain to deliver a shoe box to a shoe company. He has cultivated a garden of digital “forget-me-nots”. He hates all those people who call him “creative”. He loves all the people, whom like him, think in a phosphorescent way.','2011-08-22 08:00:28','2011-08-22 08:00:28'),(368,449,'bio','Head of Research and Inventor in Residence\n\nLorenzo De Rita is 43. He was born in Rome, Italy. He is currently the Director of The Soon Institute, a collective of inventors experimenting with new forms of communication. \n\nLorenzo designed the longest water pipe in the world. He opened the first travel agency for mind travelers. He convinced David Beckham to clean the streets of Manchester for one night and made the drawing of the tattoo Chris Martin of Coldplay has on his hand. He told the biggest lie ever in the history of advertising (the one of a little village in Sweden containing around 1.000 people, where supposedly 54 people bought the same car on the very same day). He founded a Football Club in Tokyo with over 3.000 players. He published an issue of Colors magazine made solely of white pages. He produced the first fashion collection that you cannot buy with money (not even for a million Euros, he says). He designed the first navigational system for the kitchen. He asked a guy called Xan to walk from Amsterdam to Majorca in Spain to deliver a shoe box to a shoe company. He has cultivated a garden of digital “forget-me-nots”. He hates all those people who call him “creative”. He loves all the people, whom like him, think in a phosphorescent way.','2011-08-22 08:00:58','2011-08-22 08:00:58'),(369,737,'bio','Pep Rosenfeld is one of the founders of Boom Chicago, Artistic Director and co-creator of their current production Social Media Circus. \n\nHe writes tailored presentations and campaigns for companies as well as hosts events like TEDx, PICNIC and Spin Awards. He is a political junkie, interested in current events in America, the Netherlands and Europe.\n\nPep, with fellow comedian (and Comedy Central News anchor) Greg Shapiro and director Andrew Moskos, have created hit political comedy shows like Yankee Go Home: Americans and Why You Love to Hate Us (2002), Mr.\nAmerica Contest: A Comedy Show about the U.S. Presidential Race (2004), Bye Bye Bush (2008), Political Party (2010) with Maurice De Hond and the brand new show 9/11 Forever, about the 10 year memorial of the attacks in\nNew York and Washington DC to premiere September 1, 2011.\n\nHe is co-owner of Chicago Social Club, the night club, late night bar and theater on Amsterdam’s Leidseplein with Casper Reinders (Jimmy Woo, Lion Noir) and Joris Bakker and 