Enova, a social enterprise dedicated to creating innovative public solutions through the integration of technology and educational strategies. \r\n\r\nEnova’s principal project is the design, installation and operation of cost-effective learning centers called the RIA, Red de Innovación y Aprendizaje (Learning and Education Network) which it manages for the non-profit organization, Fundación Proacceso ECO A.C. (ECO). By the end of 2011 the RIA network will include 70 centers in the State of Mexico and provide services to more than 200,000 users. For these efforts Jorge was recognized as an Endeavor Entreprenuer in 2011 with the aim of improving the educational performance of five million low-income Mexicans by 2013. The RIA project was also recognized as a finalist in Initiativa México as one of the top 40 social projects in the country out of more than 47,000 applicants and by the OECD’s Compendium of Exemplary Educational Facilities. \r\n\r\nPrior to founding Enova, Camil served as Director of PLC Networks, S.A. de C.V, an innovative BPL (Broadband Over Powerline) start-up pioneering data, voice and video transmissions via electronic networks. They completed the first VOIP call through the electrical network in the world for former Mexican President Vicente Fox. \r\n\r\nIn 2005, Jorge co-founded LT Solutions S.A. de C.V, the exclusive distributor of Ncomputing for México and Central America, a company dedicated to the commercialization of thin clients where he served as Commercial Director.  In  2008 they were awarded “Best Solution for SMEs” by Expocom, one of the largest tech expos in LATAM.\r\n\r\nCamil has also worked towards the advancement of environmental projects and initiatives in Mexico, having served as coordinator for the movement “Time for Nature 2008” on behalf of Pronatura A.C. The movement was a series of events designed with the principal objective of inspiring consciousness and motivating people to care about the environment in Mexico. Jorge also serves as a respresentative volunteer for TCP, The Climate Change Project. \r\n\r\nHe completed a double Bachelor’s degree in Economics and Business Administration at Pepperdine University, Los Angeles California (2004), and also holds diplomas in Marketing from The London Imperial College (2003); Corporate Finance, Instituto Tecnológico Autónomo de México (ITAM), Mexico (2006); Digital Governance, Tecnológico de Monterrey (ITESM), Mexico  (2007); and Senior Management in Technology and Innovation, El Instituto Panamericano de Alta Dirección de Empresa (IPADE), Mexico (2008). ','2011-07-04 12:34:14','2011-08-23 21:36:53','2011/07/12/04_13_51_73_Jorge_CamilPhotoWeb.jpg',1,0,'201.156.226.168','646837617',75199935,124,'energy to the design, building, and operation of schools in low income communities.','Wyu6TxZObk','eliyahustarr','Co-founder, Enova','75199935-DETXvETn2XaRJAM7dPsQYYsasVjnEnRdEYRoHCgdq','nCWUimpVqgHzx1MmZYpeAh6j42TqqrZ11QEV5XBJjA',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(581,'bcoleman@mit.edu','','bcPICNIC11','Beth','Coleman',0,'','Co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy\n\nDr. Beth Coleman is the primary investigator of the Pervasive Media/City as Platform research and design lab at MIT, where she is an assistant professor of comparative media studies. She is a Berkman Center for Internet and Society Faculty Fellow at Harvard University and a Microsoft Research New England Research Fellow. \n\nColeman\'s work focuses on the role of a human narrative in the context of media and data engagement, with an emphasis on locative media design. As an artist, she has an extended history of international exhibition including venues such as the Whitney Museum of American Art, New Museum of Contemporary Art, and Musée d\'Art Moderne Paris. She is the co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy, an internationally acclaimed multimedia performance platform.\n\nAmong her awards, she has received a Rockefeller Foundation award for New Media Arts and was an artist in residence at the Waag Society, Amsterdam.\n\nHer book \"Hello Avatar\" is published by the MIT Press (fall 2011).','2011-07-04 13:37:59','2011-08-21 13:26:36','2011/07/20/07_00_14_566_coleman_photo.jpeg',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Co-founder, SoundLab Cultural Alchemy',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(582,'how2@soundlab.org','','hgPICNIC11','Howard','Goldkrand',0,'','Co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy\n\nHoward Goldkrand\'s innovative vision for new modes of media engagement stems from his rich history of work across a variety of genres. Howard Goldkrand is the Innovations Director for Modernista! (modernista.com) where he has provided visionary direction on the future of storytelling and how brands communicate across all media opportunities. He lead the team for the massively successful Dexter/Showtime alternate reality game (summer-fall 2010). \n\nHe has worked with James Truman and architecture firm Diller, Scofidio, and Renfro (Big Night in Tent), ARU Liden industrial designers, Neverstop engagement marketing on Nike for Wieden and Kennedy, James Bernard (founder of Source  magazine), The Standard Hotel, and architect/nightlife impresario Serge Becker. \n\nHe is an artist whose work in sound, sculpture and software has been exhibited internationally at venues such as the Whitney Museum of American Art, PS1/Museum of Modern Art, Contemporary Art Museum Houston, Vancouver Art Museum, Castillo di Rivoli, Italy, Bildmuseet, Umea, Sweden. \n\nHoward has held art and new media residencies with the Chinati Foundation, PS1/Museum of Modern Art, Waag Society, Amsterdam, and Recollets, Paris. He is the co-founder of SoundLab Cultural Alchemy, an internationally acclaimed multimedia performance platform.\n\nHoward graduated from Wesleyan University, CT, and Oxford University, UK, with a BA in philosophy.','2011-07-04 13:41:04','2011-08-21 18:21:02','2011/07/20/07_02_50_59_hsg_picture.jpeg',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Co-founder, SoundLab Cultural Alchemy',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(583,'matt@tellart.com','','shredder','Matt','Cottam',0,'','Founder Tellart\r\n\r\nMatt believes in learning by doing, in using sketching as a tool for exploration, and in throwing himself in the deep-end when it comes to understanding extreme contexts. Matt finds that client projects, academic research and teaching enrich each other in powerful ways. He works actively to bridge academia and industry in his personal work as well as the work of Tellart.\r\n\r\nMatt co-founded Tellart in 2000, a design consultancy specializing in experience design and engineering–connecting all kinds of physical things to the Web. Matt has provided inspiration and strategic direction for a diverse client list including Nokia Design, Humana Inc., Otis Elevator and Google. He uses information design, photography and filmmaking to explore design challenges and to create products, services and experiences ranging from medical simulations to marketing stunts.\r\n\r\nAn internationally renowned speaker on a wide range of design and technology topics, Matt’s recent appointments have included the Google Tech Talks series, LIFT, the d.school at Stanford University, O’Reilly Emerging Technologies conference (ETech), Intel’s Future Technologies Research Summit, PICNIC, SIGCHI, IDSA/ICSID, DEFCON, Designing User Experience (DUX), and the National Disaster Medical System (HHS/NDMS) conference.\r\n\r\nMatt has been teaching studio courses at Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) since 1999 on topics including emergency medicine, physical computing and service design. He is also an Adjunct Professor at Umeå Institute of Design (UID Sweden) leading core interaction design modules and contributing to ongoing curriculum development. He is a member of the Visiting Faculty at the Copenhagen Institute for Interaction Design (CIID, Denmark). Matt has also been a visiting teacher at a number of academic institutions including the Oslo School of Architecture and Design (AHO, Norway), Technical University Delft (TU/d) and at the Central Academy of Fine Arts, Beijing (CAFA).\r\n\r\nDuring his Masters of Interaction Design from the Umeå Institute of Design (Umeå University, Sweden), Matt investigated the relationship between texture, materials, aging and interaction in the context of physical computation. Matt also has a Bachelor of Industrial Design and a Bachelor of Fine Arts degree from RISD. His thesis work, conducted in partnership with the Habitability Design Division at NASA\'s Johnson Space Center, focused on designing for the physiological and psychological strains of long duration space missions.\r\n\r\nIn his free time Matt enjoys racing sailboats, skiing, scuba diving and working as an Advanced Life Support Paramedic for the US Department of Health and Human Service\'s National Disaster Medical Team or for the National Ski Patrol. Matt lives in Amsterdam with his wife Maia and their boats and bicycles.','2011-07-04 14:00:45','2011-08-21 13:58:20','2011/07/04/07_02_25_497_offMattCottam.jpg',1,0,'70.168.11.113','',NULL,22,'my own boat',NULL,NULL,'Founder, Tellart',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(584,'gil@giantstep.ca','','redblue38','Gil','Katz',0,'','Managing Partner, Business Development, Giant Step Inc.','2011-07-04 14:02:31','2011-08-01 13:05:12','2011/07/04/07_02_31_163_file',0,1,'76.67.59.142',NULL,NULL,23,'ideas for new types of user-generated content that will bring more fun online.','wsYQmoy0Ek',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,'9e633c5a-6034-4c07-97ee-554f07257efc','3f7b5f1b-50af-476a-92ef-99818670e6ed','http://www.linkedin.com/in/gilkatz',0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(585,'peter@pinc.nl','','breukelen','Peter','van Lindonk',0,'',NULL,'2011-07-04 14:16:56','2011-07-04 14:18:52',NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,6,'a curious individual',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(586,'flor.konings@vodafone.com','','goldzebra67','Flor','Konings',0,'','Market