based magazine Architectural Record. \n\nAt the Harvard Graduate School of Design Metz was a Loeb Fellow ’07 and is currently a visiting fellow. She is the author of a number of books, including \"FUN! Leisure and Landscape\", about the impact of leisure on the way we use and perceive our surroundings, and a collection of columns and esaays \"On the Ground: Observations from Harvard\". She is currently working on a book on water in the Netherlands and an exhibition at the Kunsthal in Rotterdam, \"Sweet&Salt: Water and the Dutch\", to open in February 2012.','2011-08-11 12:16:01','2011-08-22 07:34:11','2011/08/11/05_17_01_266_Tracy_Metz_door_Martine_Sprangers.jpg',1,0,'77.167.54.210','549109126',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Author & Journalist, NRC Handelsblad',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(869,'ldr@thesooninstitute.com','','ldrPICNIC11','Lorenzo','de Rita',0,'','Head of Research and Inventor in Residence\n\nLorenzo De Rita is 43. He was born in Rome, Italy. He is currently the Director of The Soon Institute, a collective of inventors experimenting with new forms of communication. \n\nLorenzo designed the longest water pipe in the world. He opened the first travel agency for mind travelers. He convinced David Beckham to clean the streets of Manchester for one night and made the drawing of the tattoo Chris Martin of Coldplay has on his hand. He told the biggest lie ever in the history of advertising (the one of a little village in Sweden containing around 1.000 people, where supposedly 54 people bought the same car on the very same day). He founded a Football Club in Tokyo with over 3.000 players. He published an issue of Colors magazine made solely of white pages. He produced the first fashion collection that you cannot buy with money (not even for a million Euros, he says). He designed the first navigational system for the kitchen. He asked a guy called Xan to walk from Amsterdam to Majorca in Spain to deliver a shoe box to a shoe company. He has cultivated a garden of digital “forget-me-nots”. He hates all those people who call him “creative”. He loves all the people, whom like him, think in a phosphorescent way.','2011-08-11 12:26:40','2011-08-22 08:00:58','2011/08/11/05_33_58_322_Lorenzo_de_rita.jpg',1,0,'86.95.171.202','',NULL,12,'a torch working with phosphorescent light, a portable aqueduct & digital ants to eat the leftovers',NULL,NULL,'Inventor & Director, The Soon Institute',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(870,'nc@cmasarquitectos.net','','ncPICNIC11','Nerea','Calvillo',0,'','Nerea Calvillo qualified as an architect at the Madrid School of Architecture (ETSAM 1999). That year she was awarded the Fulbright grant to follow a Master’s degree course at Columbia University. She has worked in various practices, such as NO.MAD (Madrid 1999-2001) and FOA (London 2001-2003). In 2004 she founded her own firm -  C+, winning several national and international competitions. Her work and articles have been published in architecture magazines and general media.\r\n\r\nSpecialized in new technologies as a design tool, her research projects focused on data visualization and cartographies have been developed in several international universities and new technologies centers, including her recent project \"In the Air\". Invisible cities are revealed through collaborative process and multidisciplinary teams, by sensing, describing, interacting and changing behavioral patterns of the existing urban environment. This work was awarded the Poiesis Fellowship of the New York University, and has been exhibited at the Museo de Arte Contemporáneo de Chile (Santiago de Chile), Laboral (Gijón) and in Canadian Centre of Architecture (Montreal) next October, among others.\r\n\r\nShe is Design Studio Professor at the Universidad Europea de Madrid and the Universidad de Alicante, curated the Media Facades Festival 2010 in Madrid and is currently part of the working group of El Ranchito, a co-curated art project of Matadero, Madrid.\r\n','2011-08-11 12:39:04','2011-08-20 17:18:28','2011/08/11/05_39_36_550_nerea_calvillo_pic.jpg',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Architect & Design Studio Professor',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(871,'carl@verbeterdebuurt.nl','','clPICNIC11','Carl','Lens',0,'','Carl is co-founder of Verbeterdebuurt, a prizewinning platform for engaging citizens to improve their neighborhood. With mobile apps, widgets and a website people can post problems and ideas on an interactive map. 70% of Dutch city councils work together to actually solve the thousands of reported issues on the platform.\n\n','2011-08-11 13:24:01','2011-08-22 07:15:39','2011/08/11/06_25_09_383_carl.jpg',1,0,'80.113.5.247','564158167',7268952,14,'experience in engaging people to society through internet',NULL,'carlaltdelete','Co-founder, Verbeterdebuurt','7268952-syNXo2FTPQv54v5WlPDjceVVsdmA4xzTEu7Mx144Kw','8VPsRkjB6PVd3PO1H2AV8EkFNoRZE1wwzxa8LiJsOtg',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(872,'bra@transplant.nu','','brPICNIC11','Birgitta','Ralston ',0,'','Birgitta Ralston is Creative Director of Ralston & Bau and Head of Ideal Lab at Transplant. \n\nShe has a broad design and concept development experience from interior to profiling projects. A creative entrepreneur since 19 years old, she worked as a photographer and graduated in graphic design from RMI Berghs in Sweden, then worked as an Art Director in Paris for 10 years before co-founding Ralston & Bau designers and Transplant, a design factory in Norway. ','2011-08-11 13:45:20','2011-08-22 07:44:51','2011/08/11/06_45_57_949_Birgitta_Ralston.jpg',1,0,'81.191.113.96','',38041434,11,'human friendly food rituals',NULL,'birgittaralston','Creative Director, Ralston & Bau','38041434-W0YPetXZXAWO6pk8ijsoUOATdHCPrcHU0MZaTStFp','U6haqqaNIqF1Qw7iUwt7THEd8Jj4RZk00oMvG1pCag0',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(873,'aba@transplant.nu','','abPICNIC11','Alexandre','Bau',0,'','Alexandre Bau is Creative Director of Ralston & Bau as well as Head of Nordic Materials and Partnerships at Transplant. He has a masters degree in product & furniture design from the Beaux Arts de Rennes (FR) and has a wide range of  experience in the luxury and gourmet industries. Today he’s engaged in sustainability issues within design and architecture. Alexandre co-founded both Ralston & Bau designers and Transplant, a design factory in Norway. \r\n\r\nTwitter @transplanteurs','2011-08-11 13:47:37','2011-08-19 11:29:40','2011/08/11/06_48_37_208_Alexandre_Bau.jpg',1,0,'81.191.113.96','',39461599,8,'human friendly food rituals',NULL,'transplanteurs','Creative Director, Ralston & Bau','39461599-yP7j9LOyQQP0dzm3PQYjZDDAEPZDPLCVolY5tiWwU','5SfKOYzp3jJERYJVXb6IrFCxfx1ZltW4D8YCT74',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(874,'show@transplant.nu','','jbPICNIC11','Jan','Brauer',0,'','Jan Brauer is a designer, the coordinator of Ideal Lab and Manager of the Transplant model workshop. He has a Master\'s in industrial design from Burg Giebichenstein. \r\n\r\nJan\'s has a passion for product design and graphics, as well as illustrative art.','2011-08-11 13:50:23','2011-08-19 13:03:03','2011/08/11/06_50_47_560_Jan_Brauer.jpg',1,0,'81.191.113.96','',NULL,6,'human friendly food rituals',NULL,NULL,'Coordinator, Ideal Lab',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(875,'about@transplant.nu','','asPICNIC11','Åshild','Stav',0,'','Åshild Stav is Designer and Event Manager. She earned a Bachelor in Product Design from the Glasgow School of Art and ENCI-Les Ateliers, Paris. She grew up in Dale i Sunnfjord where Transplant is located and worked in Ralston & Bau already before her studies. \r\n\r\nÅshild is inspired by a user-centred research and design approach, leading her to design concepts and the strategic direction of services and products. ','2011-08-11 13:56:10','2011-08-21 11:15:42','2011/08/11/06_57_09_129_Aashild_Stav.jpg',1,0,'81.191.113.96','',NULL,6,'human friendly food rituals',NULL,NULL,'Designer & Event Manager, Transplant',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(876,'Hiddo.Huitzing@pbl.nl','','mhPICNIC11','Maarten','Hajer',0,'','Maarten Hajer is a political scientist and urban planner. His most recent books are \'Strong Stories - How the Dutch are Revinventing their Planning Practice\' (2010) and \'Authoritative Governance - Policy Making in an Age of Mediatization\' (2009). He is professor at the University of Amsterdam. In 2008, the Dutch Cabinet appointed him Director of the Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency (Planbureau voor de Leefomgeving, or PBL, cf www.pbl.nl/en/). Maarten is also member of the UNEP Resource Panel where he contributes to a report on new urban infrastructures. The Panel is concerned with strategic issues of resource scarcity, decoupling and resource efficiency. \nwww.unep.fr/scp/rpanel/','2011-08-11 14:16:39','2011-08-24 10:11:24','2011/08/11/07_17_18_82_Foto_Maarten.jpg',1,0,'131.224.251.103','',NULL,6,'that for sustainability, society is the innovative force, but states should create new incentives.',NULL,NULL,'Director, Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency (PBL) ',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(877,'lucyjanewalker@gmail.com','','lwPICNIC11','Lucy','Walker',0,'','Lucy Walker has directed four award-winning feature documentaries: DEVIL’S PLAYGROUND (premiered Sundance 2002), BLINDSIGHT (premiered Toronto 2006), WASTE LAND and COUNTDOWN TO ZERO (both premiered Sundance 2010). \r\n\r\nIn 2011, Lucy was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Documentary for directing WASTE LAND, which won over 30 other awards including the Audience Awards at Sundance and Berlin and the IDA’s Best Documentary Award. Recognition for DEVIL’S PLAYGROUND, about Amish teenagers, included nominations for three Emmys and an Independent Spirit Award. BLINDSIGHT won many festivals, including Berlin, and was longlisted for the Academy Award. \r\n\r\nLucy grew up in London, England, and studied English at Oxford University, where she started out directing theater before winning a Fulbright Scholarship to attend the MFA graduate film program at NYU’s Tisch School of the Arts. She was also a DJ and directed Nickelodeon’s BLUE’S CLUES, for which she was twice nominated for an Emmy. \r\n\r\nLucy has a new short documentary premiering at the Toronto Internationa Film Festival in September 2011about the recent tragic tsunami in Japan, and how the subsequent cherry blossom season brought some hope to the victims in the most hard-hit areas. ','2011-08-11 14:38:13','2011-08-19 13:26:13','2011/08/11/07_41_42_529_ctz_lucy_walker_605x412.jpg',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Documentary filmmaker',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(878,'jeff@nonchalance.com','','jhPICNIC11','Jeff','Hull',0,'','Jeff Hull is Creative Director at Nonchalance, a Situational Design consultancy in San Francisco. Their mission is to provoke discovery through visceral experience and pervasive play.  As creators of the Jejune Institute, an award-winning immersive narrative experience, Nonchalance was successfully able to re-engineer the way  audiences interact with media, the space around them, and each other.  Utilizing automated environments, pirate radio broadcasts, guerilla masonry, and lock boxes within lock boxes, Hull’s work represents a warp zone that transports audiences between hyper realized fantasy worlds.  \n\nPreviously as a street artist with an ambition to infuse more variability and play into the civic realm, Jeff created Oaklandish; a decade-strong community arts organization with 20 consecutive “Best of the East Bay” Awards to it’s credit.  He is also the founder of inner city playground activities such as the Urban Capture the Flag League, the Lake Merritt Radio Regatta, and the Liberation Drive-In which spawned an international movement of rogue parking lot movie screenings.  \n\nJeff began his career in the realm of interactive public arts in 1979, when he was a child performer at Oakland’s Children’s Fairyland, a storybook theme park which was the unsung prototype to Disneyland. Nascent time spent in this wonderland setting inspired much of his life & work since.  He also plays bass, makes an exquisite ceviche, and hosts wild parties neck-deep in kids & dogs.','2011-08-11 15:01:27','2011-08-21 20:02:50','2011/08/11/08_02_59_67_JeffHull.jpg',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Creative Director, Nonchalance',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(879,'david.langley@tno.nl','','dlPICNIC11','David','Langley',0,'','David Langley has been an applied researcher in the telecom / internet sector since 2011. His research focuses on the changing interactions between end users, firms and government. David worked at British Telecom in the UK and KPN Research. Since 2003, David has led contract research at TNO for several sectors, such banking and utilities. David has a PhD in marketing science, and is an active member of the European Institute for Advanced Studies in Management. \n\nDavid has published articles in popular media such as NRC Handelslad, Trouw and Frankwatching, and in academic journals, such as Technological Forecasting and Social Change, International Journal of Innovation Management and Journal of Product Innovation Management. ','2011-08-11 15:23:14','2011-08-22 07:12:18','2011/08/11/08_23_34_298_david_langley.jpg',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Applied Researcher, Telecom / Internet ',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(880,'gokhanseckin@gmail.com','','xrayjune89','Gokhan','Seckin',0,'',NULL,'2011-08-11 20:27:54','2011-08-11 20:28:28',NULL,1,1,NULL,'514098014',NULL,2,'social media applications.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(881,'mpizao@gmail.com','','moneywin59','Matheus','Pizão',0,'',NULL,'2011-08-12 00:03:53','2011-08-12 00:03:53',NULL,1,1,NULL,'1220391446',NULL,2,'...',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NU