sity of Cambridge, UK. \n\nCarlo has co-authored over 200 publications and holds several patents. His work has been exhibited worldwide at venues such as the Venice Biennale, the Design Museum Barcelona, the Science Museum in London, GAFTA in San\nFrancisco and The Museum of Modern Art in New York. His Digital Water Pavilion at the 2008 World Expo was hailed by Time Magazine as one of the Best Inventions of the Year.\n\nIn June 2007, the Italian Minister of Culture named Carlo a member of the Italian Design Council - an advisory board to the Italian Government that includes 25 leaders of design in Italy. He was also named 2009 Inaugural Innovator in Residence by the Queensland Government. Carlo was included in Esquire Magazine’s \"2008 Best & Brightest\" list\nand in Thames&Hudson’s selection of \"60 innovators\" shaping our creative future. In 2010 Blueprint Magazine selected him as one of the \"25 People Who Will Change the World of Design\" and Forbes listed him as one of the \"Names You Need To Know\" in 2011. \n\nHe was recently a presenter at TED 2011 and is serving as a member of the World Economic Forum Global Agenda Council for Urban Management.\n\nFor further information on Carlo’s projects, visit http://www.carloratti.com and http://senseable.mit.edu','2011-08-18 13:37:44','2011-08-22 07:51:31','2011/08/18/06_40_51_805_carlo_headshot.jpg',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Director, Senseable City Lab, MIT',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(919,'euroshop@chello.nl','RoyDuf','roller4414','Roy','Duffels',0,'','Innovationmanager Rabobank, CEO Co-founder D-sign, advisor TafMedia, One Click. Goes for Mobile, Mobility, Mashup, Open data, Social media, Leffe and fun','2011-08-18 14:20:15','2011-08-18 18:16:35','2011/08/18/07_20_15_673_file',1,0,'77.249.61.230','',6819592,4,'Innovation, a Leffe and fun',NULL,'RoyDuf',NULL,'6819592-8WiZzNoM371PFbG4i7KJSOhU0UiZXPiVa7Vl7vC8mu','igRG3b26Pq8xTZ5q0ms3ZJ8ABmUrdo1noV8SBEkbx4',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(920,'c.r.deboer@uva.nl','','rdPICNIC11','Robbert','Dijkgraaf',0,'','Robbert Dijkgraaf (1960) is a Distinguished University Professor of Mathematical Physics at the University of Amsterdam (UvA) and President of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences. \n\nProf Dijkgraaf studied physics and mathematics at Utrecht University. He gained his PhD cumlaude in 1989 with Nobel Prize-winner Gerard \'t Hooft. He held positions at Princeton University and Princeton\'s Institute for Advanced Study.\n\nHis current focus is on string theory, quantum gravity, and the interface between mathematics and particle physics. In 2003 his research was rewarded with the NWO Spinoza Prize, the highest scientific award in the Netherlands.\n\nMany of his activities are at the interface between science and society. He writes columns, is involved in a popular TV science programme and initiated www.proefjes.nl (science education).\n\nProf Dijkgraaf was member of the Innovation Platform, chaired by the Prime Minister. Since 2009 he is co-chair of the InterAcademy Council, a multinational organization of science academies, together with Professor Lu Yongxiang, President of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.','2011-08-18 14:21:42','2011-08-21 14:01:14','2011/08/18/07_25_59_983_robbert_dijkgraaf_1.jpg',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Distinguished Professor of Mathematical Physics, UvA',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(921,'molellaa@si.edu','','amPICNIC11','Arthur','Molella',0,'','Arthur P. Molella is Jerome and Dorothy Lemelson Director of the Smithsonian’s Lemelson Center for the Study of Invention and Innovation at the National Museum of American History. \n\nAs the Center’s founding director, he has led the development of an array of interdisciplinary programs, publications, and exhibitions on the role of invention and innovation in history. He received his Ph.D. in the history of science from Cornell University and an Honorary D.Sc. from Westminster University, London. His major exhibition work includes the Smithsonian’s “Science in American Life” and the international presentation, “Nobel Voices”. He has written widely on the relationships between science, technology, and culture. He is the co-author (with Robert Kargon) of Invented Edens: Techno-Cities of the Twentieth Century (MIT, 2008) and is currently working on the history of eco-cities.','2011-08-18 14:39:36','2011-08-22 07:38:18','2011/08/18/07_40_07_108_Arthur_Molella_speaker.JPG',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Director, Smithsonian’s Lemelson Center',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(922,'judy.i.chen@gmail.com','','mlPICNIC11','Mike','Lee',0,'','Legendary product engineer and World\'s Toughest Programmer Mike Lee (@bmf) has worked on apps for Alaska Airlines, Delicious Monster, Tapulous, United Lemur, Apple, and Nextive, producing such hits as Delicious Library, Tap Tap Revenge, Obama \'08, and Apple\'s Mobile Store. His goal is to save Madagascar, his blog is at mur.mu.rs, and he has the world\'s largest collection of plush prosimians. In his spare time he races cars, flies airplanes, plays guitar, drinks single-malt scotch, and surfs.','2011-08-18 14:43:22','2011-08-21 09:39:05','2011/08/18/07_43_50_811_Mike_Lee_speaker_video_presentation.JPG',1,0,NULL,'',NULL,6,'...',NULL,NULL,'Product Engineer & Programmer ',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,1,1,1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(923,'sarah@finchfactor.com','','lpPICNIC11','Laurence ','Parkes ',0,'','Laurence Parkes is Strategy Director at AKQA Amsterdam. For years, he successfully helped brands interrupt people’s lives. Now he hopes to  help them improve people’s lives. \r\n\r\nHe was chuffed to be involved in the London Cycling Safety campaign which used a moonwalking bear to reduce severe cycling injuries by 7% in 2008, but trusts that, in the future, the responsibility for this sort of effect won’t be restricted to public bodies. He believes all brands that target city-dwellers 