gureRunning. We will be doing some fun running around PICNIC11!',1,'2011-08-15 07:33:31','2011-08-15 07:33:31','Member',510,NULL,NULL,NULL),(271,856,NULL,NULL,'Welcome to my blanket! Looking forward to meeting you too. I have recently moved to Berlin indeed. Did you just move to Amsterdam or to Berlin? Ciao!!',1,'2011-08-15 17:56:18','2011-08-15 17:56:18','Member',618,NULL,NULL,NULL),(272,11,NULL,NULL,'Too much to do, and too little time. The mantra of today, I guess. But..... I really feel the program is getting better and better. More online this week. ',1,'2011-08-15 18:09:38','2011-08-15 18:09:38','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(273,154,300,'Photo','How do I get badges? I\'m attending PICNIC11 but the badge doesn\'t show up on my profile.',1,'2011-08-16 07:02:20','2011-08-16 07:02:20','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(275,856,NULL,NULL,'Bibliotaxi, a Sao Paulo base project enables you to read and borrow books from your taxi driver\nhttp://bibliotaxi.wordpress.com/',1,'2011-08-16 07:28:04','2011-08-16 07:28:04','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(276,7,68,'Link','I\'m afraid I won\'t be there at the festival, but Andy Mayer, the director of Yoomee will be there so you can catch up with him.',1,'2011-08-16 13:59:15','2011-08-16 13:59:15','Member',108,NULL,NULL,NULL),(277,693,69,'Link','I hope Kunle will explain what we can learn from urban planning in developing countries to help make our cities more efficient. Was fascinated by a recent talk by Geoffrey B West but that is very US focussed.',1,'2011-08-16 15:03:15','2011-08-16 15:03:15','Member',248,NULL,NULL,NULL),(278,693,NULL,NULL,'Have enjoyed browsing through the festival speakers this year. Is there any way you can click on your \"dont-miss\" talks and have the website compile that into a personalised programme? You could make an app for that and share your list of don\'t miss talks through existing social networks. \n\nI also miss a way to send a request to one of the speakers to include something in their talk instead of waiting for a twitter stream at the festival.  But please, if it\'s already here, please show me how to do it.',1,'2011-08-16 15:10:25','2011-08-16 15:10:25','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(279,693,41,'Video','I am curious to know whether Amsterdam is ahead or falling behind the open data experiments in Helsinki or Rennes. Made this video last year at Fing in Marseilles as a way of starting a discussion as to what needs to happen next.',1,'2011-08-16 15:45:23','2011-08-16 15:45:23','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(280,693,70,'Link','Recently I see many funds like the Knight News Foundation or the Columbia School of Journalism publishing reviews of what\'s working and not working. I am very curious to learn more of the lessons learned after a few years of the Green Challenge. What has worked and what lessons do we need to learn in Europe?',1,'2011-08-16 15:50:53','2011-08-16 15:50:53','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(281,693,42,'Video','Fablabs seem to be turning into the public science labs that government never built. Born in MIT and Northern Norway, the Fab Lab concept seems to be blossoming. I think it works because you can clearly make just about anything in a Fablab and what happens is relevant to local circumstances. At school one of the reasons for not liking Physics was that all the experiments had been worked out by others, and I couldn\'t see the practical application of what was being taught. These public access science labs work the other way round - you share an idea and they look to see what\'s possible. It is a great place to prototype. Check http://www.fablab.no/ and this list http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fab_lab#Lab_Locations for  one of the nearly 50 labs near you. There are several in the Netherlands. It would be great to know more about how they are getting on in 2011, what with government cutbacks and everything.',1,'2011-08-16 15:55:22','2011-08-16 15:55:22','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(282,693,43,'Video','I am intrigued about the wisdom of the crowds and the experiments going on with the crowd funding of features. Although David Cohn from Spot.us has got quite a bit of publicity in the print world, I actually believe that public broadcasters like NPR should be looking at what he has done as a way to discover what audiences would like investigated. Imagine instead of just paying a licence fee or donating money to an organisation you could indicate what you\'d like them to do with it. Will it work if you just give the audience a blank piece of paper? No. But people like pick lists like the one on spot.us.',1,'2011-08-16 15:59:03','2011-08-16 15:59:03','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(283,693,44,'Video','And when it comes to funding the arts in a creative city, is Australia ahead of the Netherlands in its thinking? ',1,'2011-08-16 16:01:18','2011-08-16 16:01:18','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(284,46,NULL,NULL,'Great to read that you have learned from me!',1,'2011-08-16 17:54:16','2011-08-16 17:54:16','Member',99,NULL,NULL,NULL),(285,693,71,'Link','Hope there\'s a sesssion somewhere in Picnic where we can talk about how schools in the creative cities will integrate their brightest and best. Picnic\'s Marcel Kampman had some great ideas a few months back at LIFT in Geneva.',1,'2011-08-16 18:39:19','2011-08-16 18:39:19','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(286,510,45,'Video','Singapore live ! I came across this recently - created by the SENSEable City Lab at MIT.  best viewed in full screen it gives a glimpse of the future made manifest today.\n\nThe real-time city is now real! The digital revolution has layered a vast system of cameras, communication devices, microcontrollers and sensors over our environment, enabling entirely new ways to imagine, monitor, and understand our cities. These systems have a value that goes beyond their original purpose: the digital exhaust of cellular networks reveals social and economic patterns, tracking systems highlight global material flows, and digitally managed transportation fleets address a city\'s mobility. Taken together, the impact of digital networks on cities will be as significant as any past human undertaking.\n\nLIVE Singapore!, an ongoing initiative by the SENSEable City Lab at MIT, closes the feedback loop between people moving in the city and the digital data generated by their actions. The project\'s platform allows for the collection and combination of multiple data streams and provides access to data through dynamic visualizations that offer new insights into Singapore\'s urban dynamics.\n\nLIVE Singapore! provides people with access to a range of useful real-time information about their city by developing an open platform for the collection, elaboration and distribution of real-time data that reflect urban activity. Giving people visual and tangible access to real-time information about their city enables them to take their decisions more in sync with their environment, with what is actually happening around them.',1,'2011-08-17 04:16:13','2011-08-17 04:16:13','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(287,510,72,'Link','Hello everyone, \n\nI just wanted to let you know that the September 2011 issue of Scientific American is devoted to Better / smarter cities.  If you have a digital subscription you can read it now or try to find a print version.  the link below gives you a teaser of what is in the issue through you can click through to the supplemental material for each article. ',1,'2011-08-17 04:27:22','2011-08-17 04:27:22','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(288,510,73,'Link','I came across this event via Bruce Sterling\'s blog- I think many PICNICer\'s wold find it interesting...\n\n\nWE HAVE OUR OWN CONCEPT OF TIME AND MOTION\n25th – 28th August 2011 \n\nAuto Italia in collaboration with Federico Campagna, Huw Lemmey, Michael Oswell and Charlie Woolley present \'We have our own concept of Time and Motion\': a four day event devoted to the idea and practice of self-organisation.\n\nFeaturing a temporary bookshop run by the new cooperative organisation Book Bloc, archival material selected by participating artists and commissioned furniture by Charlie Woolley, the exhibition space will become a base for the production of new work and ideas. Through a series of events this project will investigate pre-conceived ideas of self-organisation and the role of gender politics within this. The project will examine models of organisation especially from the position of an artist-run space and how this fits within a neo-liberal framework and is potentially complicit in the growing precarity of all labour. The project title references the fourth issue of the publication \'Class War\', which controversially introduced Autonomist ideas to the London anarchist scene in the mid 1980s.\n\nEvents will feature a wide variety of artists, activists, writers, designers and academics who are part of a growing network engaged in self-organisation and self-publishing. Speakers include Franco ‘Bifo’ Berardi, Nina Wakeford, Mark Fisher, the Free Association and the Alliance of Radical Bookshops plus more to be confirmed.\n\nWorkshops and panel discussions will be held throughout the event by Auto Italia, Book Bloc and the Deterritorial Support Group, along with daily podcasts recorded and distributed online. A new publication will be produced outlining the live programme along with interviews and discussions from international organisations with an additional supplement made during the course of the project in the exhibition space by Michael Oswell.\n\n\'We have our own idea of Time and Motion\' comes from a network of artists who have formed around Auto Italia and its programme and is a product of artists finding affinity with each others’ projects, ideas and aspirations. It draws on the intangible expertise, knowledge and network which Auto Italia is a part of and will produce new information that can develop a wider narrative for the future of grass-roots projects and artist-led organisation.\n\nA timetable will be released shortly with a detailed schedule and full list of participants.',1,'2011-08-17 05:20:20','2011-08-17 05:20:20','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(290,693,304,'Photo','Cities of the future will regard Internet connectivity rather like water. Despite having fast web access, many hotels in Amsterdam still think it\'s cool to charge for Wifi access or limit it to the lobby. There are exceptions. Like the new Mint Hotel which really rocksl. Amazing how quickly the Sky Lounge at this Hotel (next to Central Station) has become the new place to hangout. Good coffee and fast wifi. Brand spanking new - only open since June. I can understand why they partner with the international festivals like PICNIC. Just saying that as a user when I am in the city - no connection with them.\r\n',1,'2011-08-17 06:24:22','2011-08-17 06:24:22','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(292,693,305,'Photo','You might want to check out this map during your stay in Amsterdam. It can save you a fortune. http://www.wifi-amsterdam.nl/free_wifi_internet.html',1,'2011-08-17 06:29:34','2011-08-17 06:29:34','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(293,693,75,'Link','I hope that the project people working on improving the cyclepaths in Lima Peru are part of the future cities discussion at Picnic. Although the project is in South America, those behind it actually work out of North Amsterdam. It\'s a sort of Fix my Street idea for cyclists. ',1,'2011-08-17 06:39:00','2011-08-17 06:39:00','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(295,693,306,'Photo','Would like to find out at Picnic whether these screens in various parts of the Netherlands have been successful. In Hague Central Station I asked a few passengers and they thought it was an ad for the new Call of Duty. It\'s actually an arts channel by the look of it. I see I can only attach one item, so here\'s a photo of the dropstuff.nl screen in The Hague central station.',1,'2011-08-17 06:50:10','2011-08-17 06:50:10','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(296,693,77,'Link','Very interesting talk putting the growth of cities into perspective. Beautiful timelapse photo sequence at the start, with a brilliant, considered talk by Geoffrey B. West immediately afterwards. Grab a coffee and be both worried but also inspired.',1,'2011-08-17 07:00:59','2011-08-17 07:00:59','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(297,139,NULL,NULL,'Hi Marcel,\n\nWe are really bumbed that once again, we Picnic has run out of time and out of budget to sit down and include us in your creativity. GreenGraffiti® is the perfect fit for this year\'s theme and we had hoped that being a sponsors on several occasions would at least get us the chance to contribute.\nThere is only soooo much we can do to try to help and we were in touch months ago to try to make sure we had the time!\nMaybe next year.\nWe hope Picnic is a big success. And as always we support Picnic and what it is trying to accomplish.',1,'2011-08-17 07:12:16','2011-08-17 07:12:16','Member',46,NULL,NULL,NULL),(298,540,NULL,NULL,'Hi, having a beer and chat at Picnic sounds great - outside Picnic might be even better, considering our (OK, your) busy schedules.',1,'2011-08-17 09:12:58','2011-08-17 09:12:58','Member',46,NULL,NULL,NULL),(299,126,NULL,NULL,'I have a 24 hour plane trip ahead of my arrival to Picnic. Any suggestions on books I should read before the event? I\'m an enthusiast rather than an expert on most of the themes, so would love your suggestions.',1,'2011-08-17 23:31:48','2011-08-17 23:31:48','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(300,388,NULL,NULL,'really swiftly design of PICNIC site,its what I wanted to do with my blog',1,'2011-08-18 13:51:51','2011-08-18 13:51:51','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(301,510,78,'Link','Amazing art for Paris in the tear 2084! Looks like it is for a game called Adrift by French Game publisher Dontnod. Great art  ! is this the future for the Mega-cities?',1,'2011-08-18 14:45:04','2011-08-18 14:45:04','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(302,932,NULL,NULL,'The core internet protocol will get to its second generation soon - IPv6. Technologists need to think about the possibilities',1,'2011-08-19 07:53:22','2011-08-19 07:53:22','',N